<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Open Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Being the top-ranked tennis player in the world  
doesn't guarantee recognition, as Yevgeny Kafelnikov discovered in 
Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian winner of the 1996 French Open tried to get into the  
players changing rooms on Monday without his badge and was stopped 
by security. 
</P>
<P>
	``My name is Kafelnikov and I'm the world No. 1-seed,'' he told  
the guards, but that didn't get him in either. The guard then 
called his superior to see if Kafelnikov could enter. 
</P>
<P>
	Kafelnikov was granted access and the guard apologized. But the  
player had to promise to take his badge with him next time. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	NO MONA LISA FOR MONICA: Monica Seles got an unwelcome surprise  
when she took some time off to visit the Louvre museum in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went to the Louvre,'' said Seles. ``But obviously it was on  
strike.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Museum workers have been on strike for two weeks in Paris,  
closing down the Louvre and the Orsay museums, among others, to 
demand job security and better working conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Like thousands of other tourists, Seles had to be content with  
touring the city's streets and monuments. 
</P>
<P>
	``With my mom, we just walked. The usual, same streets. The same  
thing as every year,'' she said, ``We keep the tradition going.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	AGASSI FAN: When Lindsay Davenport was asked to pick her  
favorite for the men's tournament, she didn't hesitate: Andre 
Agassi. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love watching Andre play,'' Davenport said. ``When he's  
playing well, there's nobody more exciting than Andre, the shots he 
can come up with, the intensity he gets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davenport lost Tuesday in the quarterfinals to Steffi Graf but  
Agassi went on to the semifinals. Davenport was already looking 
ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I mean that it would be great if he won it,'' she said. ``And  
a lot more fun to watch.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	FOREIGN TONGUE: The interpreter for the players' press  
conferences doesn't mince words when it comes to her likes and 
dislikes of players. 
</P>
<P>
	She doesn't like Hingis. ``She smiles all the time, even when  
she answers questions. That gets annoying in the end,'' said Diane 
Bourley-Medecin in an interview with French daily Liberation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Williams sisters got a better review. ``I understand them a  
lot better since they got their braces out,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	On the men's tournament Bourley-Medecin had little to say.  
Gustavo Kuerten is ``a charming, polite boy'', while Marcelo Rios 
is ``insufferably scornful.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
