<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 11:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reinforcements Called for Fla. Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Fire officials called for reinforcements today as  
they battled a huge wind-whipped fire in the Okefenokee Swamp that 
already was being fought by crews from across the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire along the Florida-Georgia state line was about 20  
percent controlled today. The blaze was more than a week old, and 
firefighters predicted containment might take an additional two 
weeks if there is no significant rain. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like a war zone,'' said Bill Paxton, a spokesman for  
the firefighting operation. ``We've had some real close calls -- 
fire crews barely making it over burning bridges that are the only 
way in and out of areas. Then there's the snakes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, no injuries were reported and no structures had been  
damaged. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire, which may have been ignited by lightning on May 21,  
has burned across 53,000 acres. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 30 more fire engines and a minimum of 60 extra  
firefighters are needed, said fire information officer George 
Broyles. The new manpower and equipment are expected to arrive 
within three days. 
</P>
<P>
	They would be in addition to the 482 firefighters already at  
work with 50 fire engines and 50 bulldozers. Those forces had come 
from 30 states, as far away as Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the ground forces, 11 helicopters and four planes  
had dropped more than 1 million gallons of water and 365,000 
gallons of retardants on the tinder-dry swamp. 
</P>
<P>
	Containment lines were being shored up today along the swamp's  
western and northwestern edges, closest to small communities such 
as Fargo and Council in Georgia, Broyles said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel pretty confident that those communities are all safe  
right now,'' Broyles said. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire, whipped by wind gusting to 20 mph, was moving toward  
busy U.S. 441, which runs north-south along the western side of the 
swamp. However, it was still nine miles east of the highway. 
Bulldozers had cleared a containment line two miles from the 
pavement. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, fires that started during the Memorial Day weekend  
blackened nearly 500,000 acres in Florida, forced 100,000 residents 
to flee and caused $400 million in damage. 
</P>
<P>
	In the West, wind gusts up to 50 mph helped spread a fire over  
11,000 acres extending from Grand Canyon National Park north to the 
Arizona-Utah line. Another lightning-caused fire 80 miles west of 
Phoenix burned 14,600 acres but was contained by Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters in Nevada called in reinforcements to help battle a  
lightning-sparked blaze that had charred 10,000 acres of rugged 
terrain about 85 miles northeast of Las Vegas. It was only 20 
percent contained today, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	In California's Joshua Tree National Park, a 13,900-acre  
lightning-sparked wildfire was contained. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 13:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brit. Utility Buys Connecticut Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Yorkshire Water PLC is buying Connecticut-based  
water supplier, Aquarion Co., for $440 million and hopes to make 
additional acquisitions in the United States 
</P>
<P>
	The cash deal announced today is Yorkshire Water's first venture  
into the U.S. market, where the likelihood of consolidation offers 
greater opportunities than in Britain's more mature water treatment 
industry, chief executive Kevin Bond said. 
</P>
<P>
	The principal business of Bridgeport, Conn.-based Aquarion is to  
provide water for a population of more than 141,000 customers in 
Connecticut and New York. It also has real estate and timber 
processing interests. Yorkshire Water has 1.9 million customers and 
operates from the city of Leeds in northern England. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchase values Aquarion shares at $37.05 each, representing  
a premium of 19 percent over the U.S. company's share price at the 
close of business Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies have been working together for several years  
in areas such as an employee exchange program. 
</P>
<P>
	The Aquarion acquisition reflects what Bond said is a limited  
number of opportunities at home. Yorkshire Water is ``very 
open-minded'' about the possibility of buying other U.S. 
businesses, and it's seeking to expand in continental Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Within five years, it hopes to generate half of its revenues and  
30 percent of its earnings from outside Britain, Bond said. 
</P>
<P>
	Aquarion earned $20 million on revenue of $116 million in 1998.  
</P>
<P>
	Yorkshire Water earned $211 million pounds, or $340 million, on  
sales of 671 million pounds, or $1.08 billion, in the financial 
year ending March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is still subject to approval by regulators in the U.S.  
and Britain. It is expected to boost Yorkshire Water's earnings in 
the first full financial year after completion. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 12:16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Orders Kids-Violence Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Modeling his anti-school-violence campaign  
after his assault on Joe Camel and the tobacco industry, President 
Clinton ordered a government investigation today of how the 
entertainment business markets violence to children. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our children are being fed a dependable daily dose of  
violence. And it sells,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty years of studies, he said, have documented that by the  
time a typical American child turns 18, he or she has seen 40,000 
``play'' murders and 200,000 dramatized acts of violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``The boundary between fantasy and reality violence -- which is a  
clear line for most adults -- can become very blurred for vulnerable 
children,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The $1 million joint study by the Federal Trade Commission and  
Justice Department, expected to take up to 18 months, will examine 
industry marketing practices much as the government investigated 
tobacco ad campaigns that it determined were aimed at tempting to 
kids to smoke. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton held up ads for video games, one of which pictured a gun  
and promised ``More fun than shooting your neighbor's cat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at some of these ads, it's hard to argue with a  
straight face that the games were made for adults in the first 
place,'' Clinton said. ``Advertisements have a particular role 
here. They have the power to egg children on and lure them in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rose Garden announcement today by the president and Hillary  
Rodham Clinton comes three weeks after the Clintons convened a 
White House meeting of movie-industry lobbyist Jack Valenti and 
five dozen of the nation's leading educators, officials, 
entertainers and gun makers to brainstorm ways to reduce violence 
among youth amid a rising tide of school shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton cited a ``culture of violence that is engulfing  
American children every day,'' and asked: ``What kind of values are 
we promoting when a child can walk into a store and find video 
games where you win based on how many people you can kill or how 
many places you can blow up? '' 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady quoted from a 1972 Surgeon General's report that  
documented how children imitate the violent scenes they see on 
television. 
</P>
<P>
	Added Attorney General Janet Reno: ``We now need to know more  
about how children learn about the existence and the content of 
violent material and why they are drawn to them -- whether it be 
movies of video cames.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to a White House background paper, the entertainment  
study will review ``whether and how the video game, motion picture 
and recording industries'' purposefully market adult material to 
children and only laxly restrict sales to minors. 
</P>
<P>
	White House press secretary Joe Lockhart called it a ``real  
serious study,'' but it was unclear whether the federal agencies 
would subpoena internal marketing memos and other industry 
documents. Clinton's chief domestic policy adviser, Bruce Reed, 
said the FTC already has some subpoena powers and, while the study 
would be independent of White House control, Clinton envisions it 
looking beyond what is already in the public doman and into 
internal industry records. 
</P>
<P>
	A lobbyist for the Motion Picture Association of America did not  
immediately return a call for comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 12:16:00 </DATE_TIME>
