<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres Want Lord Stanley's Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- The Buffalo Sabres don't care about the  
trophy they won for making the NHL finals, their first trip since 
1975. The bigger one is all that matters. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't the Stanley Cup,'' captain Michael Peca said. ``You  
don't grow up working as a kid to hold the conference trophy over 
your head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres refused to celebrate after eliminating the Toronto  
Maple Leafs from the playoffs with a 4-2 victory in Game 5 in 
Toronto Monday night. That earned the Prince of Wales Trophy. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest series will be the one against the winner of the  
Western Conference final between Dallas and Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres have never won a Stanley Cup since they joined the  
NHL in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to keep it very levelheaded,'' said defenseman Jason  
Woolley, the team's leading scorer in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Woolley started the play that resulted in the game-winning goal  
by Erik Rasmussen with a pass to Brian Holzinger with just over 
eight minutes left in the third period. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres celebrated too soon after they swept Montreal to  
advance to the Eastern Conference finals last season. They lit 
cigars. They cranked up the music. They smiled for the cameras. 
Then Washington knocked them out in six games. 
</P>
<P>
	Lesson learned. Had it not been for the horde of media, the  
locker room Monday night would have been as quiet as a library. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to the dance and we're not going to stand on the  
sidelines,'' Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff said. ``I think we still have 
something to prove.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only other time Buffalo played for the Stanley Cup was in  
1975, when the team lost to hard-hitting Philadelphia in six games. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres split two games with the Stars and Avalanche this  
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody expected the Sabres to have a shot at the Stanley Cup  
this year, especially after goalie Dominik Hasek, the reigning 
two-time league MVP, was hurt in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo overcame injuries to key players and a regular-season  
slump. They made a mockery of the seedings, rising to the top from 
No. 7 in the Eastern Conference. They made believers of everyone, 
even their adversaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were in first place in January, then they had some  
injuries,'' Maple Leafs coach Pat Quinn said. ``They were probably 
underestimated by a lot of people because it's Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at that team now, they made some changes. They added  
talented players, and now they are doing things they didn't do 
before. They finish a lot of checks now. The Joe Juneaus, the Geoff 
Sandersons, they never finished any checks in their life, but 
they're doing it right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ruff, captain of the Sabres during his playing days, demands  
that his players work just like he used to. That means they also 
hit and contribute in some way. 
</P>
<P>
	The result was a surprisingly swift five-game series with  
Toronto, a team that led the league in scoring this season after 
failing to make the playoffs the previous two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Not bad for a bunch of no-names.  
</P>
<P>
	``The only reason we're still here is because of our depth,''  
said Sabres wing Dixon Ward, who finished the Maple Leafs with an 
empty-net goal in the closing seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the past few years, we've learned one or two lines and  
four or five defensemen won't win the Cup. We have 20 guys all 
going in the same direction.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
