<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Rallies Women for His Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore received the  
endorsement of his boss' wife Tuesday as he sought to rally women 
behind his bid for the Democratic presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``Al Gore has been out in front for women, for families, for  
children, throughout his life,'' Hillary Rodham Clinton told 
several hundred women at a downtown hotel. ``Now is the time for 
all of us to be out in front for him. He is my choice and I hope 
your choice for the next president of the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore will officially announce his candidacy for the nation's top  
job on June 16 in Carthage, Tenn., according to spokesman Roger 
Salazar. That is the site of the Gore family farm. 
</P>
<P>
	Women are expected to play a pivotal role in the 2000 elections  
and Gore is seeking to inherit the support that President Clinton 
had enjoyed among them. His focus on family issues helped him win 
the women's vote 55 percent to 37 percent in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a head-to-head matchup with Texas Gov. George W. Bush,  
the Republican leader in early presidential polls, Gore trails 
among women by 10 points -- 52 percent to 42 percent, according to a 
CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll in late May. 
</P>
<P>
	Women were about equally split in that poll on whether Gore has  
the vision to solve the nation's problems. By a 50 percent to 32 
percent margin, they said they were less likely to vote for Gore if 
Clinton actively supports and campaigns for him. 
</P>
<P>
	At the rally, Gore talked about his pride in cosponsoring, as a  
senator, the bill that was the first signed into law under the 
Clinton-Gore administration -- the Family and Medical Leave Act, 
which gives workers up to 12 weeks of unpaid leave to take care of 
a new children, a seriously ill family member or personal illness. 
</P>
<P>
	He promised additional family-friendly policies as president.  
``I have listened to working families and I know our work is not 
done,'' Gore said as the mostly female crowd waved ``Gore 2000'' 
placards or mini-American flags. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said he wants to extend the family leave law ``so parents  
can meet with their children's teacher without fearing the loss of 
their job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also talked about making preschool available to every child,  
reducing class sizes, allowing parents to pay for college tuition 
``tax-free and inflation-free'' and using new technologies to 
tailor learning to individual children. 
</P>
<P>
	Tipper Gore noted the importance of women to her husband's  
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we know from past elections, when women vote Democrats  
win,'' she said. ``We need your help to share with the country his 
vision and we need your help to get the word out about his 
commitment ... on the issues that matter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A partial list of female supporters distributed by the Gore 2000  
campaign names members of Congress, former governors, other state 
officials and mayors. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those on stage with Gore were Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee of  
D-Texas; Del. Eleanor Holmes Norton, D-D.C; Maryland Lt. Gov. 
Kathleen Kennedy Townsend and Carol Browner, administrator of the 
Environmental Protection Agency. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 14:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Futures Down on Glut Worries  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Energy futures tumbled Tuesday on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange after European refiners announced additional cutback on 
crude purchases, moves that could worsen a world supply glut. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, gold futures fell sharply. Grain and soybeans  
also moved lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude posted its third consecutive decline as refiners continued  
to weigh in with processing cutbacks in Europe, a region that 
consumes nearly a quarter of the world's oil supply. 
</P>
<P>
	Italy's ERG SpA said it would cut the amount of oil it uses at a  
Sicilian refinery this month, an announcement that follows BP 
Amoco's announcement last week that it would reduce processing 
rates at European refineries run in a joint venture with Mobil 
Corp. by 225,000 barrels a day. 
</P>
<P>
	Royal-Dutch Shell Group also cut processing last month, as  
refiners saw profit rates tumble. 
</P>
<P>
	While sharp increases in the price of oil have been good for  
members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and 
other world producers, refiners have been socked by tightening 
margins. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because prices of refined products such as gasoline and  
heating oil have not moved in step with rising crude prices, which 
jumped sharply after producers moved to take supplies off the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude for July delivery fell 50 cents to $16.34 a barrel; July  
heating oil fell .50 cent to 39.13 cents gallon; July unleaded 
gasoline fell 1.56 cents to 47.37 cents a gallon; and July natural 
gas fell 1.3 cents to $2.345 per 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold futures fell sharply on the New York Mercantile Exchange as  
Australian producers dumped new supplies on the market to lock in 
prices that are likely to go lower. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to find anyone positive on gold right now,'' said  
Leonard Kaplan, chief bullion trader of LFG Bullion Services. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold prices have tumbled 10 of the past 12 trading sessions,  
posting continuous 20-year lows, in response to Britain's decision 
to sell more than half of its reserves beginning a few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors are finding little that glitters in a market bogged  
down by jitters that other governments and international agencies 
will sell their stockpiles in favor of better-returning investments 
such as Treasury bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, Australia, Canada, the Netherlands and Belgium  
have quietly sold reserves, while Switzerland and the International 
Monetary Fund are moving to do the same. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian producers now are dumping their inventories as prices  
threaten to slip below the cost of production. Other major 
producers, including Canada and South Africa, also may move to sell 
ahead of the British gold sales, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	August gold tumbled $2.50 to $269.50 an ounce.  
</P>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures prices retreated on the Chicago Board  
of Trade amid near-ideal growing conditions for spring crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters are predicting warm weather and scattered showers  
across Midwest growing regions this week. That should prove ideal 
for early growth of corn and spring wheat crops, where farmers were 
expected to have completed planting in the past week. Market 
participants expected the government this week would report about 
75 percent of soybean crops have been planted. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors are worried that record soybean acreage and large corn  
acreage could lead to bumper fall harvests, at a time when weaker 
than normal world demand has lead to ample inventory buildups. 
</P>
<P>
	July wheat fell 1/2 cent to $2.51 3/4 a bushel; July corn fell 3 1/4  
cents to $2.16 1/4 a bushel; July soybeans fell 3 3/4 cents to $4.58 a 
bushel. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
