<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Washington State Receiver Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PULLMAN, Wash. (AP) -- Nian Taylor, Washington State's top  
receiver who was elected a team co-captain last week, was being 
held in Whitman County Jail on Tuesday after his arrest for 
investigation of domestic assault. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, three Washington State players are to be arraigned  
on burglary and theft charges in Whitman County. One is the 
Cougars' top rusher, Kevin Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	Pullman police allege Taylor, 22, followed a 22-year-old woman  
to her apartment on Tuesday, kicked the door off its hinges, and 
threw the door into the apartment. 
</P>
<P>
	``The suspect is accused of grabbing and hitting the female and  
striking her in the chest with his fist,'' according to a police 
press release. ``He is also accused of throwing water on the 
victim.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The woman was bruised, but declined medical attention, police  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor was arrested on investigation of fourth-degree assault,  
domestic violence and malicious mischief after a witness supplied 
police with a vehicle license plate number and a description. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-2, 200-pound senior from Riverside, Calif., had been  
granted a special year of eligibility by the NCAA for the upcoming 
season. Last year, he led the Cougars with 847 receiving yards and 
eight touchdowns, catching 45 passes in 10 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor had to sit out his freshman year because of low SAT  
scores and the NCAA's Proposition 48. But he graduated from 
Washington State in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Under new rules adopted in 1997, Prop 48 players who lost their  
freshman year of eligibility were given the year back if they 
graduated within four years. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no answer Tuesday at the office of football coach Mike  
Price or athletic director Rick Dickson. Sports information 
director Rod Commons said Price would typically discuss the issue 
with Taylor and law enforcement officers before making any comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, 20, of West Covina, Calif., rushed for 1,046 yards, a  
sophomore team record. 
</P>
<P>
	Defensive back Ramin White, 19, will be a freshman and receiver  
Jason White, 20, will be a sophomore this coming season. Ramin 
White and Jason White are not related. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Price suspended all three players and said that, if  
they're convicted, they would be dismissed from the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, Jason White and Ramin White would remain on suspension  
indefinitely pending the outcome of their court cases, Price said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is imperative for our program to hold high standards, no  
matter the talent of the individual player,'' Price said last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The players were arrested May 20 at a campus apartment complex.  
</P>
<P>
	The men were arrested after witnesses said they saw them enter  
an apartment through an unlocked back door and leave with a laptop 
computer and other electronics gear, police have said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said $1,900 worth of electronics equipment was recovered.  
The players each face six to 12 months in jail if convicted of the 
felony counts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
