<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Surge / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks surged today after a small  
investment newspaper reported that Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi may 
decide to freeze the national sales tax. The dollar fell against 
the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 296.85  
points, or 1.84 percent, ending the day at 16,408.50. On Monday, 
the average closed up 138.97 points, or 0.87 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.11 yen in late afternoon trading, down  
0.25 yen from late Monday in Tokyo. Currency markets in New York 
were closed Monday for a national holiday. The dollar ranged from 
120.93 yen to 121.90 yen today in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock prices rose on the report by the Nikkan Toshi Shimbun, or  
Japan Investment Journal, that Obuchi's government may decide in 
June to suspend the 5 percent national sales tax as part of a new 
economic stimulus measure. The little-known newspaper, which did 
not identify sources, said the announcement may come on June 16 
before the Group of Seven summit in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's strong denial of the report did not halt the  
rapid rise, while the report pushed hedge funds into the market, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks were also supported by Japanese jobless data and  
expectations that New York stocks might advance later today, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier today, the government said Japan's April unemployment  
rate stayed at the record high 4.8 percent, although a higher rate 
had been expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The jobless rate among men rose to an all-time high of 5.0  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 20.29 points, or 1.56 percent, to 1,317.48. 
The TOPIX closed down 5.12 points, or 0.39 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the First Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was  
estimated at 433.13 million shares, up from 375.54 million on 
Monday. Gainers outpaced decliners 848 to 327, with 128 issues 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar fell as the speculation of the  
sales tax freeze triggered selling of the U.S. currency against the 
yen, although buying by Japanese investors soon underpinned the 
dollar, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a rumor, and we are not sure whether it's true or  
not. We can't continue selling dollars on just that report,'' said 
Shigeru Hashimoto, a senior trader at Sanwa Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 126.28 yen, down  
from 128.31 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.6150 percent late afternoon, up from Monday's finish 
of 1.4750 percent, driving its price down to 98.14 yen from 99.34 
yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
