<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Fall on Inflation Fears / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices plummeted Tuesday on new fears about  
higher interest rates, pushing yields to their highest level in 
more than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury fell 1 7/32 point,  
or $12.19 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, rose to 5.94 percent from 5.83 percent late 
Friday. The market was closed Monday for the Memorial Day holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds tumbled after the National Association of Purchasing  
Management said its index of manufacturing activity rose to 55.2 in 
May, higher than analysts expected and the highest level since 
October 1997. The group's index of prices paid also rose in the 
month, indicating more companies reported price increases during 
the month. 
</P>
<P>
	The report provided fresh evidence that the vigorous U.S.  
economy may be overheating heading into the summer. Traders fear 
that may cause the Federal Reserve to hike interest rates to slow 
it down. Last month, the Fed opted against a rate increase, but 
hinted that it's leaning toward a raise. 
</P>
<P>
	Short-term issues fell between 7/32 point and 11/32 point, while  
intermediate-term issues fell between 19/32 point and 1 1/32 point, 
according to Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 4.66 percent as the  
discount rose to 4.63 percent from 4.51 percent. Six-month yields 
rose to 4.87 percent, as the discount gained 0.12 percentage point 
to 4.76 percent. One-year yields rose to 5.04 percent as the 
discount rose 0.09 percentage point to 4.80 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.06 1/4 percent from 4.87 1/2 percent late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 19/32 to 121 1/4 from 121 27/32 Friday. 
The average yield to maturity rose to 5.42 percent from 5.39 
percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
