<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 10:22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Orders Kids-Violence Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Modeling his anti-school-violence campaign  
after his assault on Joe Camel and the tobacco industry, President 
Clinton ordered a government investigation today of how the 
entertainment business markets violence to children. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our children are being fed a dependable daily dose of  
violence. And it sells,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty years of studies, he said, have documented that by the  
time a typical American child turns 18, he or she has seen 40,000 
``play'' murders and 200,000 dramatized acts of violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``The boundary between fantasy and reality violence -- which is a  
clear line for most adults -- can become very blurred for vulnerable 
children,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The $1 million joint study by the Federal Trade Commission and  
Justice Department, expected to take up to 18 months, will examine 
industry marketing practices much as the government investigated 
tobacco ad campaigns that it determined were aimed at tempting to 
kids to smoke. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton held up ads for video games, one of which pictured a gun  
and promised ``More fun than shooting your neighbor's cat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at some of these ads, it's hard to argue with a  
straight face that the games were made for adults in the first 
place,'' Clinton said. ``Advertisements have a particular role 
here. They have the power to egg children on and lure them in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rose Garden announcement today by the president and Hillary  
Rodham Clinton comes three weeks after the Clintons convened a 
White House meeting of movie-industry lobbyist Jack Valenti and 
five dozen of the nation's leading educators, officials, 
entertainers and gun advocates to brainstorm ways to reduce 
violence among youth amid a rising tide of school shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton cited a ``culture of violence that is engulfing  
American children every day,'' and asked: ``What kind of values are 
we promoting when a child can walk into a store and find video 
games where you win based on how many people you can kill or how 
many places you can blow up? '' 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady quoted from a 1972 Surgeon General's report that  
documented how children imitate the violent scenes they see on 
television. 
</P>
<P>
	Added Attorney General Janet Reno: ``We now need to know more  
about how children learn about the existence and the content of 
violent material and why they are drawn to them -- whether it be 
movies of video cames.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to a White House background paper, the entertainment  
study will review ``whether and how the video game, motion picture 
and recording industries'' purposefully market adult material to 
children and only laxly restrict sales to minors. 
</P>
<P>
	White House press secretary Joe Lockhart called it a ``real  
serious study,'' but it was unclear whether the federal agencies 
would subpoena internal marketing memos and other industry 
documents. Clinton spokesman Jake Siewert said the Justice 
Department and FTC already have subpoena power and, while the study 
would be independent of White House control, Clinton envisions it 
as encompassing internal industry records. 
</P>
<P>
	A lobbyist for the Motion Picture Association of America did not  
immediately return a call for comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 11:40:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall; Dow Down 66.07 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today as a new report on the growing  
U.S. economy intensified traders' fears about inflation and higher 
interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 66.07 at 10,493.67. Earlier in the session, the blue-chip 
index had tumbled as much as 150 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were lower as well. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was down 11.67 at 1,290.17, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was down 39.08 at 2,430.81. 
</P>
<P>
	Concerns about inflation, which have increased the market's  
volatility over the past two weeks, were behind today's decline as 
well. Prices dropped after the National Association of Purchasing 
Management said the nation's industrial economy expanded for a 
fourth straight month in May. The report, which gauges the health 
of the nation's factories, was much stronger than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The NAPM's report is widely followed by economists because it  
usually provides the first indication of how the economy performed 
in the just-ended month. Today's report was highly anticipated as 
traders sought a sign that the economy is not overheating. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the report, which revealed strong price rises in raw  
materials for the first time in 16 months, sent stocks skidding. 
</P>
<P>
	``With all the skittishness about inflation, the real surprise  
from this report is that we didn't drop even farther, even 
faster,'' said William Meehan, chief market analyst for Cantor 
Fitzgerald. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also pressured bond prices. The 30-year Treasury bond  
plunged, sending its yield up to 5.93 percent from late Friday's 
5.83 percent. The yield is now at its highest level in more than a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock traders are increasingly worried that rising inflation  
will prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates, leading to 
higher corporate borrowing costs and lower profits. Rising rates 
also make bonds a more attractive investment alternative. 
</P>
<P>
	Another report released today suggested some softening in the  
economy, but the news wasn't enough to offset the effects of the 
purchasing managers' survey. The Index of Leading Economic 
Indicators fell 0.1 percent in April, its first decline since June 
1998, according to the Conference Board. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks led today's decline, as IBM fell 4 1/8 to 111 7/8.  
Hewlett Packard fell 3 7/16 to 90 7/8 after an analyst at Banc of 
America Securities downgraded its stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Telebanc Financial Corporation shot up 10 5/8 to 77 1/8 on the Nasdaq  
Stock Market after online brokerage ETrade said it will acquire 
Telebanc to create an Internet-based financial services company. 
ETrade fell 3 3/4 to 40 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch led a number of brokerage stocks lower, dropping 7  
1/16 to 76 15/16, after it announced plans to offer low-fee 
Internet stock trading. Conventional brokerages are facing 
competitive pressure from the growing number of online brokerages, 
yet they fear losing their hefty commissions from full-fee 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 431.6 million shares, 
slightly behind Friday's quiet pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 4.01 at 618.25, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 3.83 at 774.91. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was down 1.99 at  
436.69. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
