<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 01:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> George Brett, Brothers To Make Bats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- After getting 3,154 hits in a Hall of Fame  
career, George Brett knows bats the way a winemaker knows grapes. 
So getting into bat production is a natural. 
</P>
<P>
	Brett and his brothers just bought half-ownership of TriDiamond  
Sports, a revolutionary bat maker, and renamed it Brett Bros. Bat 
Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike traditional bats milled from single pieces of wood, these  
bats are composed of three strips of Northern White Ash. The strips 
are glued to form a stick said to be 20 percent stronger than the 
models swung by Hank Aaron or Mickey Mantle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard so many good things about these bats that it was a  
no-brainer,'' said Brett, a 13-time All-Star with Kansas City who 
will be inducted into the Hall of Fame on July 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Brett Bros. will join a movement to replace aluminum bats with  
so-called composite wooden ones that last longer than old-fashioned 
models, said Brett, who never used an aluminum bat in a game. 
Professional baseball has never allowed aluminum bats. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the high cost of replacing broken wooden bats that fueled  
the rise of aluminum bats in the amateur ranks about 30 years ago. 
Since then, a generation of Little Leaguers and college players 
have played the game without ever knowing the sublime feeling of 
crushing a cowhide ball with a wooden bat. 
</P>
<P>
	But times are changing.  
</P>
<P>
	Several companies are making composite wooden bats of various  
forms, hoping to reclaim the high school and college markets, and 
even softball leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anybody who grows up and plays baseball knows wood is the way  
baseball is meant to be played,'' said Spokane businessman Bobby 
Brett, a former minor league player who brought the bat deal to his 
three brothers: George, former major leaguer Ken Brett and former 
minor leaguer John Brett. 
</P>
<P>
	Ken Brett, 83-85 in a 15-year pitching career with 10 teams,  
will be vice president of marketing for the bat company. Ken Brett 
batted .262 during his major league career. 
</P>
<P>
	Showing admirable family togetherness, the Bretts also co-own  
minor league baseball, hockey and soccer teams in Spokane, and real 
estate in Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
	Bobby Brett became aware of TriDiamond Sports about two years  
ago, when co-owner Joe Sample asked the Bretts' Class A Spokane 
Indians to try out the new composite bats. The sticks held up well 
during batting practice, and Brett was intrigued. 
</P>
<P>
	Sample, a thoroughbred horse breeder, and his partners developed  
the new bats with researchers at Washington State University's 
nearby Pullman campus who worked under contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Their process electronically scans each piece of ash, screening  
the wood for imperfections that can cause a bat to break. Pieces of 
cleared wood then are glued together, shaped into bats and 
laminated for extra strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, braided fibers of aerospace materials are bonded up the  
first 18 inches of the neck, forming what look like permanent 
batting grips. No need for extra pine tar here. 
</P>
<P>
	The grips were added when research by WSU's Wood Materials and  
Engineering Laboratory found that most wooden bats break below the 
label, where the wood starts to taper towards the knob. 
</P>
<P>
	Testing proved the new bats can withstand about 20 percent more  
``impacts per bat'' than regular bats. 
</P>
<P>
	TriDiamond began marketing the bats a couple of years ago, but  
progress was slow until the Bretts entered the picture a few weeks 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``TriDiamond lacked name recognition,'' Sample said. ``When the  
bats changed to Brett, it eliminated that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brett Bros. has already shipped its bats to 20 major league  
teams for their farm systems, Sample said. The bats are approved 
for use in the rookie and Class A ranks of the minor leagues, and 
the company hopes for approval in higher rungs of the minors next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	George Brett, a vice president with the Royals, hands the bats  
out to interested major league players for use in practice. 
</P>
<P>
	But he concedes it's unlikely major league baseball will shift  
to composite bats. 
</P>
<P>
	``They'd have to put an asterisk on all batting records,'' Brett  
said from Kansas City. 
</P>
<P>
	Brett Bros. bats are cheaper than aluminum bats, and are being  
marketed as a money-saving tool for teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Bobby Brett said his Spokane Indians broke 392 wooden bats  
during their 76-game season last year, an average of five per game, 
and he expects better from the composites. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had 12 unbroken bats at the end of the season,'' Brett  
said. ``We think these will save money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In college baseball, concerns have been raised about the safety  
of players due to the increasing velocity of balls bashed with 
high-tech aluminum bats. 
</P>
<P>
	Because aluminum bats hit the ball longer than wooden bats,  
college baseball has seen an eruption of power hitting, George 
Brett said. He contends wooden bats will make the college game more 
comparable to professional baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	``College kids are used to getting jammed and still getting home  
runs,'' Brett said. ``With a wooden bat you can't do that. You've 
got to hit balls on the sweet spot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sweet spot is technically known as the bat's longitudinal  
nodal point. On a 35-inch, 32-ounce bat, the sweet spot is at 27.3 
inches from the handle end. 
</P>
<P>
	If hit there, the ball will sail farther and the player will  
feel no sting in the hands from vibrations. But if the player 
misses the sweet spot, the ball may not go as far, and the bat 
might break. 
</P>
<P>
	Players who grew up with aluminum bats have to be taught to  
avoid hitting a baseball on the vulnerable label of a wooden bat. 
For that reason, Brett Bats also sells a flat-faced bat designed to 
teach young players to keep the label facing up. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
