<DOCNO> APW19990601.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 15:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Student Testifies at Lewis Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- In apparent violation of his doctor's orders  
against heavy exercise, Boston Celtics captain Reggie Lewis was 
running, shooting baskets and dunking days before he died in July 
1993, a former Northeastern University student said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In testimony marking the start of the defense case at the  
malpractice trial stemming from Lewis' death, Sean Curran told how 
a chance encounter at a gym water fountain four days before Lewis' 
death led to a one-on-one practice session with his idol. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, the All-Star even fetched Curran's rebounds.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was missing a lot of shots, so he had to jump and run and  
get the ball back to me as quick as possible,'' said Curran, whose 
story suggested Lewis may have been ignoring the orders of his 
cardiologist, Dr. Gilbert Mudge, not to engage in heavy exercise. 
</P>
<P>
	Under questioning by Mudge's attorney, Curran -- who testified  
that he was alone with Lewis during the 2-hour session -- said the 
practice was intense enough to make both men sweat. He also said 
that before meeting Lewis, he watched the player run up and down 
the court, taking shots and dunking. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Tuesday, Superior Court Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith  
denied defense motions to dismiss the suit against Mudge and two of 
his consultants but said the case -- particularly against the 
consultants -- was far from strong. 
</P>
<P>
	``Frankly, the case is very slim,'' Fremont-Smith said, without  
the jury present, in his first extended courtroom comments since 
the trial began almost a month ago. ``But that's why we have 
jurors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The jury will have to decide whether Drs. Mudge, Mark Creager  
and Peter Friedman were negligent in their care of Lewis, who died 
of a cardiac arrhythmia as he practiced jump shots July 27, 1993. 
He was 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge had told Lewis he had a neurological condition that causes  
fainting spells, going against a previous diagnosis by a team of 
doctors who said Lewis had a life-threatening, potentially 
career-ending heart ailment. 
</P>
<P>
	Donna Harris-Lewis is suing for the money Lewis could have made  
had he lived, estimates of which have been as high as $117 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Curran, who practiced daily in hopes of making the Northeastern  
basketball team, said he was amazed when the former star at that 
school took the time not only to offer tips, but to engage in a 
strenuous practice session with him after the two met at the water 
fountain. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a real down-to-earth person,'' said Curran, who  
attended Northeastern from 1991 to 1994. ``He didn't put on any 
airs about anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Curran, now living in Ramona, Calif., and studying computer  
science, never made the team. 
</P>
<P>
	During cross-examination, plaintiff's attorney Robert Harley did  
not challenge Curran's assertions about Lewis' alleged exertion on 
the court. He sought instead to portray Curran as a failed, 
starstruck athlete and highlight the fact that Lewis was generous 
with his time. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was kind of overwhelming,'' Curran said. ``It was a very  
nice day and I'll remember it for the rest of my life.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 16:07:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ocalan Denies Ordering Key Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IMRALI ISLAND, Turkey (AP) -- On trial for his life, Kurdish  
rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan rejected blame Tuesday for the 1993 
slaughter of dozens of unarmed soldiers, an attack that shattered a 
rebel cease-fire and led to a massive military crackdown on 
Turkey's Kurds. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan also denied that his group had a hand in the 1986 slaying  
of Swedish Prime Minister Olof Palme and rejected accusations that 
he ordered attacks on Turkish tourist sites in which several 
foreigners were killed or injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan, however, accepted overall responsibility for the 15-year  
war waged by his Kurdistan Workers Party, or PKK. The conflict has 
killed 37,000 people, mostly Kurds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am the person with the highest responsibility for the deeds  
and actions of the organization,'' he told the court on the second 
day of his trial. He spoke through a microphone in a bulletproof, 
bombproof cage on the prison island of Imrali, where he is the only 
inmate. 
</P>
<P>
	Responding to questions by Judge Turgut Okyay, Ocalan said his  
militants have received training in camps in Greece and Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan's testimony appeared designed to distance himself from  
the most brutal attacks attributed to his fighters. The Kurdish 
guerrilla leader faces death if convicted of treason. 
</P>
<P>
	There is widespread support in Turkey for executing Ocalan, who  
is considered by most Turks to be personally responsible for the 
suffering caused by the war. 
</P>
<P>
	When Ocalan repeated his apology -- first made Monday -- for the  
deaths of Turkish soldiers, relatives of the war dead silently 
raised pictures of their loved ones Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``You took 25,000 lives from me!'' Ocalan shot back.  
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Tuesday, about a dozen of the relatives addressed the  
court, calling for Ocalan's execution. The mother of one slain 
soldier fainted after she spoke. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want the head of this snake to be crushed as soon as  
possible,'' said Metin Karabiyik, the father of a slain soldier, 
pointing at Ocalan. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan told the court that the 1993 slaying of 33 unarmed  
soldiers in the southeastern province of Bingol was carried out by 
a regional PKK commander. 
</P>
<P>
	The slaughter ended the rebel's unilateral cease-fire and led  
the military to intensify a campaign aimed at annihilating the 
guerrilla group. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of that campaign, soldiers have burned thousands of  
Kurdish villages, leaving large sections of the southeast 
abandoned, a tactic aimed at denying the rebels local support. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not possible to condone the death of these soldiers,''  
Ocalan said. 
</P>
<P>
	He added there were struggles within the PKK and that dozens of  
former guerrillas had been executed for deviating from the 
organization's line. 
</P>
<P>
	He suggested that allegations that he was behind the  
assassination of Palme were circulated by dissidents. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been attempts to put the blame for several murders  
in Europe, including the murder of Olof Palme, on me,'' Ocalan 
said. ``The senior members of the organization who have said that 
orders for those actions were given by me, are those who are 
opposed to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Ocalan -- who ruled his group with an iron hand --  
appeared conciliatory, ordering his fighters to lay down their arms 
but threatening Turkey with more bloodshed if he is hanged for 
treason. It was Ocalan's first direct call for an end to the 
fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	He also offered to transform his group into a political  
organization, a move certain to be rejected by Turkey, which 
regards any hints of Kurdish nationalism as a direct threat to the 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkish newspapers expressed outrage at Ocalan's offer.  
</P>
<P>
	``Traitor and coward,'' the daily Aksam said Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Hours after his apology Monday, rebels attacked a police outpost  
in the southeastern province of Van, killing one soldier and 
wounding three others, the Anatolia news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial is taking place before a State Security Court. Such  
courts have been called biased by human rights organizations, since 
the three-member panel includes a military judge. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 08:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Leading Economic Indicators Decline  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A key gauge of future economic activity declined  
in April for the first time since June 1998, suggesting some 
softening in the economy, the Conference Board said today. Still, 
economists at the nonprofit business research group said the 0.1 
percent fall in the Index of Leading Economic Indicators -- 
following six months of advances -- was not a cause for alarm or a 
suggestion that the U.S. expansion was at an end. This looks like 
only a temporary pause, although last week's drop in the stock 
market adds some complications,'' said Michael Boldin, director of 
business cycle research at the Conference Board. 

</P>
<P>
	Purchasing Managers Index Rises  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As the nation's industrial economy expanded for  
a fourth straight month in May, prices paid by manufacturers rose 
for the first time in 16 months, a private report said today. The 
National Association of Purchasing Management said its monthly 
index of business activity rose sharply to 55.2 in May from 52.8 in 
April -- a much stronger showing than analysts had expected. 

</P>
<P>
	Construction Spending Down 2.4 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Construction spending, which had been one of  
the driving forces in the economic expansion, fell by a sharp 2.4 
percent in April, the biggest monthly decline in more than five 
years, the government reported today. The Commerce Department said 
the declines were widespread with decreases reported in 
single-family homes, apartment buildings, office buildings and big 
government projects. The 2.4 percent drop caught analysts by 
surprise. Many had been expecting the country's construction boom 
to continue in April although at a slightly slower pace than 
previous months. The April decline followed five straight monthly 
increases. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Move Lower; Dow Down 124.00  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved lower this morning. Just before 11  
a.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 124.00 at 
10,435.74. Traders returned cautiously to the market following the 
three-day weekend in observance of Memorial Day. Broad market 
indicators also were lower. The Nasdaq Composite index was down 
36.02 at 2434.50. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 11 a.m. EDT:  
Dow Industrials:        10435.74 - 124.00
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1046  Declines 1384  Unchgd  565
NYSE Volume:         149,890,130
Most Active NYSE issue:        America Online 116 1/2   - 2 3/4
S&AMP;P 500:         1284.52 - 17.32
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          774.12  -  4.62
Nasdaq Composite Index:       2434.50  - 36.02
Gold(final) -    $268.00    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.

</P>
<P>
	Car-Hauler Talks Extended 24 Hours  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Negotiators for the Teamsters union and  
companies that haul new cars to auto showrooms are resuming 
contract talks after averting a strike early today that could have 
meant long delays in the delivery of some models. Union President 
James P. Hoffa told reporters following a post-midnight bargaining 
session that the 12:01 a.m. EDT strike deadline was being extended 
for 24 hours to discuss management's ``11th hour'' economic 
proposal. Talks were to resume this morning. Hoffa said the main 
sticking points with the 17 affected companies were management 
proposals to pay a lower wage to newly hired drivers and to hire 
part-time workers. 

</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch To Offer Online Trades  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., joining startups like  
ETrade as well as long-established brokerages like Charles Schwab, 
announced today it is creating an Internet site for individuals to 
buy and sell stocks for $29.95 a trade. The nation's largest 
brokerage said in a statement the site will begin operating in 
December and will also allow users of the site to purchase mutual 
funds, bonds and other securities. The move poses a big risk for 
Merrill Lynch, which makes billions of dollars annually through 
full-fee commissions on stock and other trades and depends on its 
network of 15,000 brokers for its customer base. But mainstream 
investment firms are finding themselves increasingly pressured to 
compete with online brokerages by offering lower fees for trades 
executed online. Merrill Lynch stock is down 6 11/16 to 77 5/16. 

</P>
<P>
	ETrade Is Buying Telebanc  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Online broker ETrade Group Inc. will merge  
with online banker Telebanc Financial Corporation, creating the 
first purely Internet-based company uniting banking and brokerage 
services, the two firms announced today. Under the terms of the 
deal, ETrade will acquire Arlington-based Telebanc in a stock 
transaction worth about $1.8 billion, the companies said in a 
written statement. ETrade, based in Palo Alto, Calif., made its 
name as a stock brokerage but has been trying to diversify. With 
Telebanc in its fold, ETrade has moved closer to becoming a 
full-service financial site, offering a range of online services 
for all sorts of transactions, company officials said. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Tech Chief Takes Leave  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- After 13 years of trying to foresee the future  
for Microsoft, chief technology officer Nathan Myhrvold is taking a 
yearlong leave of absence and has a hunt for dinosaur fossils on 
top of his agenda. Myhrvold, who headed the huge software company's 
$3 billion research effort, will begin his leave on July 1. In his 
absence, the 500-person Microsoft research department will be run 
by Rick Rashid, vice president of research. Among Myhrvold's first 
stops after leaving his Redmond office will be eastern Montana, to 
look for tyrannosaurus and triceratops fossils. 

</P>
<P>
	Barnes &AMP; Noble Deal Hits Roadblock  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Federal Trade Commission staff is opposing  
Barnes &AMP; Noble's $600 million plan to merge with the nation's 
largest book wholesaler, saying it violates antitrust laws, The New 
York Times reported today. The staff has recommended that the full 
FTC block the plan by the nation's largest bookseller to acquire 
the Ingram Book Group, the Times reported, citing an unidentified 
source familiar with the deal. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Airlines Raising Domestic Fares  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Summertime air fares are heating up, with four  
large carriers raising their standard domestic leisure rates by 4 
percent. Continental Airlines Inc., which moved first to raise 
fares Friday, was joined yesterday by American Airlines Inc., 
Northwest Airlines Corp. and U.S. Airways Inc. Travel expert Tom 
Parsons predicted that Delta Air Lines Inc. and United Airlines 
Inc. would announce a 4 percent increase today, followed by America 
West Airlines Inc. and Trans World Airlines Inc. 

</P>
<P>
	Asian Stock Markets Close Higher  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed higher today,  
with the key index surging in Tokyo on a report that the Japanese 
government may suspend a national sales tax to boost the country's 
faltering economy. The Japanese 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average 
gained 296.85 points, or 1.84 percent, ending the day at 16,408.50. 
Hong Kong stocks closed sharply higher, boosted by a late rally in 
reaction to a surge on the Tokyo bourse. The Hang Seng Index, the 
Hong Kong market's key indicator of blue chips, rose 216.44 points, 
or 1.8 percent, closing at 12,363.56. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Leading economic indicators: down 0.1 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Purchasing managers: up from 52.8 to 55.2  
</P>
<P>
	Construction spending: down 2.4 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: New home sales  
</P>
<P>
	Thursday: Retail sales  
</P>
<P>
	Thursday: Jobless claims  
</P>
<P>
	Thursday: Factory orders  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Unemployment  

  	   	
</P>
