<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 21:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Economy Shows Strength </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANBERRA, Australia (AP) -- The Australian economy continues to  
grow strongly in the face of the Asian crisis, expanding beyond 
expectations in the first three months of 1999, official figures 
released Wednesday show. 
</P>
<P>
	The growth was attributed to strong domestic consumer spending.  
</P>
<P>
	Australia gross domestic product grew 1.1 percent in the three  
months ended March 31, seasonally adjusted, the Australian Bureau 
of Statistics reported. 
</P>
<P>
	This brought the 12-month growth rate to 4.8 percent, the bureau  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The results are above the expectations of the government, which  
predicted little better than one percent quarterly growth for an 
annual figure of 4.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The bureau said household spending strengthened by 1.7 percent  
in the March quarter, making it 2.6 percent higher than the same 
period a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Household spending grew in all areas except in purchases of cars  
and cigarettes. Major contributors were recreation and culture, 
hotels, cafes and restaurants. 
</P>
<P>
	General government spending was down 3.2 percent during the  
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Home construction strengthened and while business investment  
also rebounded by 9.6 percent -- although it remained seven percent 
lower than a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Exports of goods and services were down 0.6 percent, seasonally  
adjusted, for the quarter, while imports increased by 3.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Production in agriculture, forestry and fishing and mining rose,  
as did manufacturing production. Construction, however, was down 2 
percent as activity in the non-dwelling building sector weakened. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil and gas bounced back from a low December quarter and coal  
production also increased, the bureau said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wholesale trade strengthened by 3.2 percent, adjusted, in the  
quarter while retail trade rose 1.8 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
