<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed higher Tuesday,  
with the key index surging in Tokyo on a report that the Japanese 
government may suspend a national sales tax to boost the country's 
faltering economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained  
296.85 points, or 1.84 percent, ending the day at 16,408.50. On 
Monday, the average closed up 138.97 points, or 0.87 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares rose on a report by the Nikkan Toshi Shimbun, or Japan  
Investment Journal, that Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's government 
may decide in June to suspend the 5 percent national sales tax as 
part of a new economic stimulus measure. The newspaper, which did 
not identify sources, said the announcement may come on June 16 
before the Group of Seven summit in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's denial of the report did not halt the rapid  
rise, while the report pushed hedge funds into the market, traders 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks were also supported by Japanese jobless data and  
expectations that New York stocks might advance later Tuesday, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Tuesday, the government said Japan's April unemployment  
rate stayed at the record high 4.8 percent, although a higher rate 
had been expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 121.11 yen in late  
afternoon trading, down 0.25 yen from late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong stocks closed sharply higher, boosted by a late rally  
in reaction to a surge on the Tokyo bourse. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, rose 216.44 points, or 1.8 percent, closing at 
12,363.56. On Monday, the index gained 87.87 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said share prices were little changed at midday in  
absence of any market-moving news before surging in the afternoon 
following the rally on the Tokyo exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Hong Kong's Cathay Pacific Airways, which has canceled  
a large number of flights because of a pay dispute with its pilots, 
managed to climb back partially from a big drop on Monday. Cathay 
shares rose 2.35 percent to close at 10.90 Hong Kong dollars (U.S. 
$1.39) after plunging almost 10 percent on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Malaysian shares closed sharply higher, with the key index  
rising 2.2 percent, as investors went on a bargain-hunting spree. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange's benchmark Composite Index,  
which tracks 100 blue-chip stocks, rose 16.33 points to close at 
759.37. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed generally mixed, but the key index  
rose for a sixth consecutive session on buying by foreign 
investors. The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 17.70 points, 
or 2.4 percent, to 753.72. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed higher in line with rises at  
key Asian bourses. The Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) Index rose 
8.19 points, or 1.8 percent, to 461.79. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed higher on a technical rebound. The  
market's key Weighted Stock Price Index rose 81.05 points, or 1.10 
percent, to 7,397.62. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed higher. The  
benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 36.82 points, or 1.8 percent, 
to 2,098.22. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed mostly higher, led by property  
stocks that surged on the steady softening of interest rates. The 
Philippine Stock Exchange index of 30 selected companies rose 20.49 
points, or 0.8 percent, to 2,440.32. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed higher. The All  
Ordinaries Index rose 15.4 points, or 0.5 percent, to 2,915.6. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares closed mixed as a rally in retail stocks ran  
out of steam in afternoon trading. The Straits Times Index rose 
5.02 points, or 0.2 percent, to 1,908.88. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed marginally lower. The  
Composite Index fell 1.985 points, or 0.3 percent, to 583.257. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
