<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ocalan Denies Ordering Key Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IMRALI ISLAND, Turkey (AP) -- On trial for his life, Kurdish  
rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan rejected blame Tuesday for the 1993 
slaughter of dozens of unarmed soldiers, an attack that shattered a 
rebel cease-fire and led to a massive military crackdown on 
Turkey's Kurds. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan also denied that his group had a hand in the 1986 slaying  
of Swedish Prime Minister Olof Palme and rejected accusations that 
he ordered attacks on Turkish tourist sites in which several 
foreigners were killed or injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan, however, accepted overall responsibility for the 15-year  
war waged by his Kurdistan Workers Party, or PKK. The conflict has 
killed 37,000 people, mostly Kurds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am the person with the highest responsibility for the deeds  
and actions of the organization,'' he told the court on the second 
day of his trial. He spoke through a microphone in a bulletproof, 
bombproof cage on the prison island of Imrali, where he is the only 
inmate. 
</P>
<P>
	Responding to questions by Judge Turgut Okyay, Ocalan said his  
militants have received training in camps in Greece and Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan's testimony appeared designed to distance himself from  
the most brutal attacks attributed to his fighters. The Kurdish 
guerrilla leader faces death if convicted of treason. 
</P>
<P>
	There is widespread support in Turkey for executing Ocalan, who  
is considered by most Turks to be personally responsible for the 
suffering caused by the war. 
</P>
<P>
	When Ocalan repeated his apology -- first made Monday -- for the  
deaths of Turkish soldiers, relatives of the war dead silently 
raised pictures of their loved ones Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``You took 25,000 lives from me!'' Ocalan shot back.  
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Tuesday, about a dozen of the relatives addressed the  
court, calling for Ocalan's execution. The mother of one slain 
soldier fainted after she spoke. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want the head of this snake to be crushed as soon as  
possible,'' said Metin Karabiyik, the father of a slain soldier, 
pointing at Ocalan. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan told the court that the 1993 slaying of 33 unarmed  
soldiers in the southeastern province of Bingol was carried out by 
a regional PKK commander. 
</P>
<P>
	The slaughter ended the rebel's unilateral cease-fire and led  
the military to intensify a campaign aimed at annihilating the 
guerrilla group. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of that campaign, soldiers have burned thousands of  
Kurdish villages, leaving large sections of the southeast 
abandoned, a tactic aimed at denying the rebels local support. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not possible to condone the death of these soldiers,''  
Ocalan said. 
</P>
<P>
	He added there were struggles within the PKK and that dozens of  
former guerrillas had been executed for deviating from the 
organization's line. 
</P>
<P>
	He suggested that allegations that he was behind the  
assassination of Palme were circulated by dissidents. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been attempts to put the blame for several murders  
in Europe, including the murder of Olof Palme, on me,'' Ocalan 
said. ``The senior members of the organization who have said that 
orders for those actions were given by me, are those who are 
opposed to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Ocalan -- who ruled his group with an iron hand --  
appeared conciliatory, ordering his fighters to lay down their arms 
but threatening Turkey with more bloodshed if he is hanged for 
treason. It was Ocalan's first direct call for an end to the 
fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	He also offered to transform his group into a political  
organization, a move certain to be rejected by Turkey, which 
regards any hints of Kurdish nationalism as a direct threat to the 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkish newspapers expressed outrage at Ocalan's offer.  
</P>
<P>
	``Traitor and coward,'' the daily Aksam said Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Hours after his apology Monday, rebels attacked a police outpost  
in the southeastern province of Van, killing one soldier and 
wounding three others, the Anatolia news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial is taking place before a State Security Court. Such  
courts have been called biased by human rights organizations, since 
the three-member panel includes a military judge. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 05:40:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Changes Slow IRS Transformation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans increasingly perplexed by the  
country's complex tax laws may find little relief in sight: one out 
of every five bills introduced in Congress this year would tinker 
with the tax code, and President Clinton himself is proposing 131 
changes. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the Internal Revenue Service is starting to feel the strain  
of 6,493 tax law changes since 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	The worry is that more tinkering could divert precious resources  
and slow the IRS' transformation into a more taxpayer-friendly 
agency. 
</P>
<P>
	``You add all these things up and the IRS can't handle it,''  
said Rep. Amo Houghton, R-N.Y., chairman of the House Ways and 
Means subcommittee that oversees that oversees the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Val Oveson, the IRS national taxpayer advocate, said rapid-fire  
changes make it difficult to interpret laws, draft forms, program 
already-overloaded computers and train employees. As a result, 
taxpayers have a harder time understanding the rules and getting 
the right answers from the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	``Failing to understand the law results in frustration at both  
ends,'' Oveson told a congressional committee recently. ``Don't 
change the tax laws so much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But there is little sign that Congress and the White House are  
listening. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, for example, proposed 28 new specific tax cuts in his  
budget for fiscal 2000, including credits for care of disabled 
elderly and the newborn, and 73 ways to raise revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers from both parties have dozens of bills providing tax  
relief for almost every imaginable constituency. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS says about 20 percent of all bills introduced so far  
this year in the Republican-controlled would have some impact on 
the tax code. That compares with about 15 percent in 1993-94, the 
last time Democrats controlled the House and Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Republican Sens. Paul Coverdell of Georgia and Susan  
Collins of Maine introduced a proposal allowing teachers to deduct 
up to $250 a year for their out-of-pocket classroom expenses, such 
as supplies and instructional aids. 
</P>
<P>
	For Coverdell, the bill has a key political purpose: Teacher  
unions oppose separate legislation he proposed to allow tax-free 
IRA-like accounts to pay private school costs, but many average 
teachers like the $250 deduction idea. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as we are confronted with the tax code we have, I will  
be among those trying to find ways to relieve pressure on the 
working people of this country,'' Coverdell said. ``We just have to 
live with the fact that we have a very complicated tax code.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because these tax changes often are targeted for political  
reasons at the middle class, they frequently are phased out for 
higher-income taxpayers. That means the IRS must produce a way for 
taxpayers to figure out if the break applies to them, and then 
taxpayers have to do the calculations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do our best to try to take the law and simplify it,'' said  
Sheldon Schwartz, IRS national director of forms and publications. 
``But there is a lot of underlying complexity that is very 
difficult to get around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For example, the Clinton administration's proposed $1,000 credit  
for elderly care would be phased out by $50 for each $1,000 (or 
fraction thereof) that a taxpayer's adjusted gross income exceeds 
$110,000 for married people filing jointly, $75,000 for singles and 
$55,000 for married people filing separately. 
</P>
<P>
	Got it?  
</P>
<P>
	David Lifson, chairman of the tax executive committee of the  
American Institute of Certified Public Accountants, noted a recent 
Associated Press poll showing 66 percent of taxpayers believe taxes 
are too complex and 56 percent pay someone to do their returns. 
</P>
<P>
	``When over half our individual taxpayers have so little  
comprehension of, or faith in, their tax system ... something is 
not right,'' he said. ``The end result is erosion of voluntary 
compliance. It is only human to disobey a law if you do not or 
cannot understand the rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some in Congress are trying to simplify things.  
</P>
<P>
	Houghton has introduced a comprehensive bill eliminating some  
confusing tax provisions. He would exempt many taxpayers from 
having to fill out capital gains forms or falling into the dreaded 
alternative minimum tax, which is intended to ensure higher-income 
people do not completely escape income taxes through credits or 
deductions. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Richard Neal, D-Mass., has a bill that would reduce income  
phase-outs for some of the tax credits, shorten the capital gains 
forms and repeal AMT for individuals. Neal says that would 
eliminate 200 lines from the tax forms. 
</P>
<P>
	But given the costs of such efforts and popularity of targeted  
tax relief, sponsors face an uphill climb. 
</P>
<P>
	``History says things will not get better,'' Houghton  
acknowledged. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
