<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *Kenneth Dodson    	
</P>
<P>
	STANWOOD, Wash. (AP) -- Kenneth Dodson, who wrote popular books  
about his experiences in World War II, died May 24 after a long 
battle with congenital heart disease, Parkinson's disease and 
malaria. Dodson was 91. 
</P>
<P>
	Dodson then spent 20 years in the merchant marine before  
enlisting in the Navy shortly after the attack on Pearl Harbor in 
1941. He saw action in nine major battles, including Okinawa and 
the invasion of Makin in the Gilbert Islands as part of the capture 
of Tarawa in 1943. 
</P>
<P>
	He was discharged in 1946 after his vocal cords were severely  
damaged when a machine gun mount tore loose during a training 
session. 
</P>
<P>
	After poet Carl Sandburg urged him to write about his wartime  
experiences, Dodson took writing classes at the University of 
Washington. With the success of his first effort, ``Away All 
Boats,'' published in 1954, Dodson and his family appeared on radio 
and television shows around the country . 
</P>
<P>
	The book was the basis of a film by Universal Studios. Hi other  
books include ``Stranger to the Shore,'' ``China Pirates'' and 
``Hector the Stowaway Dog,'' later made into a Walt Disney film. 
</P>
<P>
	His last book, ``The Poet and the Sailor,'' was completed  
shortly before his death. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Harold Grumhaus    	
</P>
<P>
	NAPLES, Fla. (AP) -- Harold Grumhaus, a longtime Chicago Tribune  
and Tribune Co. executive, died Saturday at age 96. 
</P>
<P>
	During his nearly four decades with the Tribune, Grumhaus held  
almost every top executive position with the company, including 
chairman and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	An expert in production, he joined the Tribune in 1934 and soon  
became a trusted aide to legendary editor and publisher Col. Robert 
R. McCormick. 
</P>
<P>
	After McCormick's death, Grumhaus moved up through the ranks of  
the company and spearheaded the restructuring of corporate 
relationships that set the stage for the company to go public in 
1983. 
</P>
<P>
	Grumhaus retired in 1976 as a director of Tribune Co. and  
chairman of its executive committee. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, a son, a sister, eight grandchildren  
and 12 great-grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Richard Hunter Hemp    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Richard Hunter Hemp, an editor at the San  
Francisco Chronicle for nearly four decades, died Monday of 
complications from cancer. He was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Hemp rose from copy boy to reporter, eventually becoming one of  
the staff's most respected editors. 
</P>
<P>
	For 19 years, Hemp served as night city editor, and was  
assignment editor from 1969 to 1988. Hemp later worked on the 
editorial page and retired on Nov. 5, 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	During World War II in the Marine Corps, Hemp served in Puerto  
Rico, the Virgin Islands and Okinawa, and he did postwar duty in 
Tientsin, China. 
</P>
<P>
	Hemp is survived by his wife, a brother and several nieces and  
nephews. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Rupert Lonsdale    	
</P>
<P>
	BOURNEMOUTH, England (AP) -- Submarine commander Rupert Lonsdale,  
the only British naval captain to surrender his warship during 
World War II, died April 25. He was 93. 
</P>
<P>
	Lonsdale later became a minister in the Church of England and  
finally Canon Emeritus. 
</P>
<P>
	Lonsdale was the captain of the mine-laying submarine Seal,  
which was surrendered to the Germans in the Kattegat, the channel 
between Denmark and Sweden, on May 5, 1940. Lonsdale and his crew 
became prisoners-of-war. 
</P>
<P>
	Lonsdale was court-martialed when he returned to England at the  
end of the war in 1945, charged with failing to take immediate 
action to engage enemy aircraft and failing to ensure that the Seal 
was sunk. He testified that he deeply regretted the surrender, 
``but at the time it seemed the only thing to do.'' He was 
acquitted with honor. 

</P>
<P>
                          *William Ringel    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- William Ringel, a judge who once ruled that Andy  
Warhol's ``Blue Movie'' is obscene, died Thursday. He was 97. 
</P>
<P>
	The Austrian-born Ringel worked for the U.S. Army's intelligence  
unit during World War II before becoming a judge and serving in 
various courts in New York for 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1969, he was in a three-judge panel that ruled ``Blue Movie''  
obscene. The judges said the film's graphic sex was portrayed 
``with no redeeming social value.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
