<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Phantom' Strong at Box Office / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``Notting Hill'' with Julia Roberts and Hugh  
Grant opened with a strong $27.7 million against the powerhouse 
``The Phantom Menace,'' which had a huge Memorial Day weekend that 
put it over the $200 million mark in a record 13 days. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Phantom Menace'' grossed $66.9 million over the four-day  
weekend to lead the North American box office and bring its 
two-week total to $207.1 million. It took previous record holder 
``Independence Day'' 21 days to reach the $200 million milestone in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	While second-place ``Notting Hill'' enjoyed big business as a  
romantic alternative, two other films withered under the force of 
the Force: ``The Thirteenth Floor'' opened with a disappointing 
$4.3 million in fifth, and ``The Love Letter'' dropped 59 percent 
to collect just $1.4 million in its second week for 10th. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Mummy'' continued to do well, however, with $12.9 million  
for third place. ``Entrapment'' was fourth with $7.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In art houses, ``Tea With Mussolini'' remained a big draw, with  
another $1.2 million in its third week. 
</P>
<P>
	The top 20 movies at North American theaters Friday through  
Monday, followed by distributing studio, gross, number of theater 
locations, average receipts per location, total gross and number of 
weeks in release, as compiled Tuesday by Exhibitor Relations Co. 
Inc. and ACNielsen EDI Inc.: 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``Star Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace,'' 20th Century  
Fox, $66.9 million, 3,023 locations, $22,132 average, $207.1 
million, two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	2. ``Notting Hill,'' Universal, $27.7 million, 2,747 locations,  
$10,080 average, $27.7 million, one week. 
</P>
