<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuadorean Family Mourned in Conn. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRUMBULL, Conn. (AP) -- As mourners said goodbye to four little  
boys and their mother killed in a train accident, the most touching 
words came from children who wrote messages on their caskets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sorry,'' wrote one. ``Enjoy the rest of eternity,'' wrote  
another. 
</P>
<P>
	Julia Toledo de Urgiles and her sons -- Carlos, 11, Jose, 10,  
Angel, 6, and Pedro, 3 -- were killed last week while walking along 
train tracks in the middle of the night. 
</P>
<P>
	The family was buried Monday following an emotional service in  
which the youngsters and their mother were eulogized as simple, 
humble people who were always smiling. 
</P>
<P>
	``Happiness is born. It was born in them,'' said Nora Toledo,  
the boys' aunt. 
</P>
<P>
	The family emigrated from the Ecuadorean village of Cojitambo 18  
months ago, settling in Bridgeport, where Mrs. Urgiles' sister and 
brother had lived for more than a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	But life in Bridgeport proved difficult. Within a few months,  
Mrs. Urgiles' husband, Carlos, returned to Ecuador. She filed for 
divorce and struggled on her janitor's wages to raise the children 
alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Urgiles and her boys had been living in a homeless shelter.  
The night of the accident, she had packed up her family and left. 
It was still unclear Monday why she left. 
</P>
<P>
	They were struck from behind by an Amtrak train in Fairfield.  
Mrs. Urgiles, Pedro, Angel and Carlos were killed instantly. Jose 
was declared brain-dead two days after the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 500 people attended the Spanish-language funeral  
service at The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, where 
the family had been active members. Carlos Urgiles sat with his 
in-laws in the front pew. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel very bad because I didn't get a chance to speak to them  
before their death,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Children who paid their respects wrote messages with markers in  
both Spanish and English on the light-colored caskets. 
</P>
<P>
	Three large flower arrangements had the word ``Classmates''  
embossed in gold lettering. Another arrangement was made out of 
brightly colored tissue paper. 
</P>
<P>
	A handmade card made into the form of a white dove bore the  
hand-written message of a child: ``Jose, We Love You.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
