<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Avondale May Accept Litton Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Avondale Industries Inc., a major Navy  
shipbuilder, says it is prepared to accept a $500 million cash 
buyout offer from defense contractor Litton Industries Inc. but is 
giving a rival bidder two days to top it. 
</P>
<P>
	The Litton offer is better than the $470 million stock swap deal  
that Avondale previously accepted from Newport News Shipbuilding, 
Avondale chairman Albert L. Bossier Jr. said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Litton offer amounts to $39.50 per share.  
</P>
<P>
	Avondale, based in New Orleans, said it has given Virginia-based  
Newport News 48 hours notice of its intention to go with the Litton 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Newport News-Avondale merger was apparently doomed Friday  
when Defense Secretary William Cohen said the Pentagon would 
probably tell the Justice Department to reject Litton's $1.3 
billion bid for Newport News for anti-competitive reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Cohen said the Navy had determined it would  
not oppose Litton's offer for Avondale. 
</P>
<P>
	Newport News had no comment on Avondale's announcement, said  
company spokeswoman Jerri Fuller Dickseski. 
</P>
<P>
	Litton owns Ingalls Shipbuilding in Pascagoula, Miss. Litton  
made its bids for Avondale and Newport News earlier in May after 
Cohen rejected an attempt by General Dynamics Corp. to acquire 
Newport News. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Cohen said that the Navy had made a ``preliminary  
determination'' that Litton's bid for Newport News would 
excessively limit competition in naval shipbuilding. 
</P>
<P>
	The Litton-Newport News deal would have reduced the number of  
companies competing to build most classes of Navy warships from 
three to two. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale and Ingalls Shipbuilding have few overlaps in their  
projects, although they both build amphibious ships and both have 
competed for cruise ships. Newport News, which builds aircraft 
carriers and nuclear submarines, has a distinctly different product 
line from Avondale. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
