<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 20:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Edge Up Early / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was lower against the yen Wednesday  
morning, while Japanese stocks edged up on expectations the 
government may hammer out additional measures to buoy up nation's 
slumping economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.59 yen at midday, down 0.52 yen from late  
Tuesday in Tokyo but marginally higher than its late New York level 
of 120.56 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 24.71  
points, or 0.15 percent, to 16,433.21 at the end of the morning 
session. On Tuesday, the index rose 296.85 points, or 1.84 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar's weakness followed its trend in  
New York, where the currency slipped as inflation fears pushed down 
U.S. stock and bond markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was under selling pressure after a  
stronger-than-expected manufacturing report on Tuesday increased 
speculations the U.S. Federal Reserve will raise interest rates to 
cool the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Purchasing Management said its price  
index rose to 52.2 in May from 49.9 in April, leading analysts and 
investors to interpret that as an indication inflation was revving 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	Although higher interest rates typically are supportive of a  
nation's currency, in this case they are felt to mean that 
businesses will have a harder time getting loans to conduct 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 126.05 yen, down  
from 126.28 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices opened mixed on profit-taking after  
Tuesday's rise and buying on hopes for more economic stimulus 
measures. 
</P>
<P>
	``Buying and selling are intertwined,'' said Kunihiro Hatae,  
general manager of the stock division at Tokyo Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said investor sentiment improved somewhat following a  
report Tuesday in a small Japanese investment newspaper saying that 
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi may decide later this month to suspend 
Japan's unpopular 5-percent national sales tax. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 9.93 points, or 0.75 percent, to 1,327.41. The 
TOPIX rose 20.29 points, or 1.56 percent, the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 36.52 points  
to close Tuesday's session at 10,596.26. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.6200 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.6050 
percent, driving its price down to 98.10 yen from 98.23 yen 
Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
