<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suzuki Boosts Hungarian Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) -- Suzuki Motor Corp. of Japan is  
expanding its operations in Hungary to build a car jointly with 
General Motors, Suzuki's chief executive officer announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Osamu Suzuki said at a news conference that 16 billion forints  
($67 million) will be invested in the city of Esztergom, where a 
third Suzuki plant will be built. 
</P>
<P>
	Suzuki said overall annual capacity will remain at about 70,000  
vehicles but that some 20,000 of them will be new-model cars 
manufactured jointly with General Motors. 
</P>
<P>
	The new vehicle has yet to be named, but currently is being  
referred to as a Suzuki-GM Opel compact. Production is to start in 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Plans call for production to rise to 30,000 vehicles to 50,000  
vehicles a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Parts for the new car will be manufactured in Hungary and in  
Poland, at the General Motors Polska plant, which will turn out 
120,000 of the new vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, Suzuki's Esztergom plant, 25 miles north of Budapest,  
produced 66,000 cars. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
