<DOCNO> APW19990601.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 16:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants Miffed by Gomes Celebration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Philadelphia Phillies closer Wayne Gomes  
likes to celebrate. The San Francisco Giants don't like to watch. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't take offense to it,'' Giants second baseman Jeff Kent  
said Tuesday. ``I just think it shows a lack of class.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gomes got the attention of the slumping Giants on Monday night  
with a demonstrative celebration on the mound after striking out 
Rich Aurilia and Brent Mayne in the eighth inning of the Phillies' 
4-3 comeback victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The right-hander spun around on the mound and pumped both arms  
several times while running to the dugout. Gomes then pitched a 
1-2-3 ninth for his fourth save, sending the Giants to their fifth 
straight loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just an emotional person,'' said Gomes, who recently took  
over the closer's job when Jeff Brantley went down with a 
season-ending shoulder injury. ``I really can't hold that in. Big 
outs put food on my table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gomes and the Giants have a history.  
</P>
<P>
	In the aftermath of a brawl last Aug. 2, J.T. Snow homered off  
Gomes, watched the ball's flight and then flipped his bat 
derisively to the side. The next day, Gomes struck out Snow and 
waved both arms as if shooing him off the field. Words were 
exchanged, and the two players had to be separated. 
</P>
<P>
	The Phillies were swept in four games by San Francisco during a  
seven-game losing streak that effectively ended their chase for an 
NL wild card spot. Philadelphia manager Terry Francona doesn't 
expect Gomes' actions on Monday night to fuel more hard feelings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why would it?'' Francona asked. ``That was last year.''  
</P>
<P>
	Kent, a quietly fiery presence who disdains showboating, said  
the Giants plan to get Gomes back with their bats and nothing else. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think he's established himself to celebrate like  
that,'' Kent said. ``It's not like it was a playoff game. I think 
it's magnified because we had a situation with him last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gomes said, ``I don't mean to disrespect their ballclub or  
anybody on that team. That's just how I pitch. I just get excited 
out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the incident with Snow last year, Gomes sent the Giants  
first baseman a letter of apology. Snow said he received the note 
but never responded. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'll learn to have more self-control the longer he pitches,''  
Kent said. 
</P>
<P>
	Francona said he talked briefly with Gomes, urging the  
26-year-old closer to concentrate on pitching instead of 
celebrating. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to take away any of his enthusiasm,'' Francona  
said. ``But I also don't want the other team to have extra 
incentive to beat him.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
