<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Takes Steps on Path to Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- As the International Olympic  
Committee considers how to restructure itself, Juan Antonio 
Samaranch has made it clear there isn't any imminent change at the 
top. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch reiterated Monday his intention to serve the final two  
years of his term as IOC president, dismissing speculation -- 
including from one of his own deputies -- that he might step down 
early. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with The Associated Press, Samaranch said he  
will heed the wishes of the IOC delegates who gave him an 
overwhelming vote of confidence -- 86-2 -- during the crisis meeting 
in March on the Salt Lake City scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``My position depends on the IOC members,'' Samaranch said  
Monday. ``The secret ballot we had in Lausanne was very clear. The 
IOC members think I am the right man at this moment to lead the 
changes we need in the IOC. With the confidence of the IOC members, 
I am ready to finish my mandate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch, who has been in office since 1980, was re-elected to  
his latest four-year term in 1997 and is due to serve until the IOC 
session in Moscow in September 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC vice president Dick Pound of Canada, a leading presidential  
contender, recently suggested that Samaranch could decide to retire 
at the end of this year after ushering in a series of reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	In an unusual public rebuke by a fellow IOC executive board  
member, Kevan Gosper of Australia -- another presidential hopeful -- 
said Pound's remarks were ``rather unfortunate to say the least.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``His postulation that Samaranch might go early was unwelcome,''  
Gosper said. ``Samaranch's intentions are quite clear: he intends 
to see out his mandate. He has repeated that to me and I fully 
support that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch, who wrote to Pound expressing disappoinment at his  
comments, said Monday that the two remain on good terms. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't judge what he said or did not say,'' Samaranch said.  
``What I am judging with Dick Pound is our relations of 18-19 
years. He is always working very close to me. I am giving him the 
most important responsibilities. Dick Pound was one who always 
defended me. I consider Dick Pound one of the most important 
members of the IOC.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch spoke on the eve of the inaugural meeting of the IOC's  
new reform commission, an 80-member task force charged with 
reshaping the 105-year-old organization after its worst scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC 2000 panel, meeting today and Wednesday, will begin  
examining ways of overhauling the IOC's structure and the process 
for selecting Olympic host cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, the commission is expected to consider  
changes to the way IOC members are selected, including the 
possibility of term limits and reduction of the age limit from 80 
to between 70 and 75. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission is scheduled to submit a preliminary report June  
20 at the next IOC general assembly in Seoul, South Korea. 
Samaranch hopes final recommendations will be approved at a special 
IOC session in December. 
</P>
<P>
	``This meeting is only the beginning,'' Samaranch. ``We cannot  
expect any kind of resolution this week. Our aim is to have final 
decisions by the end of the year. If that's not possible, then by 
the spring of next year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch said the reforms would not be dictated by pressure  
from Arizona Sen. John McCain and other congressional critics who 
have threatened to enact legislation that would punish the IOC 
financially. 
</P>
<P>
	``They can do what they desire,'' Samaranch said. ``But I  
repeat: The IOC is run by the IOC members. ... We highly respect 
the Senate of the United States, but I am sure they also will 
respect the IOC.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Originally planned as a group of 20-24 people, the reform  
commission has expanded to 80 members -- 44 from the IOC and 36 from 
outside. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission is divided into three working groups: the  
composition and structure of the IOC, the role of the IOC, and the 
selection of Olympic host cities. 
</P>
<P>
	A 26-member executive committee, divided equally among IOC and  
non-IOC members, will oversee the reform process. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the most prominent non-IOC members on the commission are  
Henry Kissinger, the former U.S. Secretary of State; Peter 
Ueberroth, chief organizer of the 1984 Los Angeles Games; Italian 
industrialist Giovanni Agnelli; former U.N. Secretary General 
Boutros Boutros-Ghali of Egypt; NBC Sports chief Dick Ebersol; and 
Nobel Peace Prize winner and former Costa Rica president Oscar 
Arias Sanchez. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
