<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fans Angry As Stanley Cup Sold Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Mike Szpylman was wet, tired and ticketless  
after waiting 14 hours through a rainy night for a chance to see 
his beloved Sabres in the Stanley Cup finals, where they haven't 
been since 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	He couldn't help but cry.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've been waiting my whole life to go,'' the 16-year-old fan  
said, a tear forming at the corner of his eye. 
</P>
<P>
	Fan Tony Failla, also unable to get tickets, seemed to take it  
even harder. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to die,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	More than 1,000 fans found themselves out of luck Tuesday  
morning when the limited number of tickets available to the general 
public sold out in eight minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of them had waited through the night at Marine Midland  
Arena and were outraged when told there were no more tickets left, 
chanting, ``Hell no, we won't go!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two men rammed a metal barricade into a locked glass door as  
employees and security officers waited for the police. A burst of 
rain dispersed much of the crowd after a few tense moments. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo defeated the Toronto Maple Leafs 4-2 Monday night to win  
the Eastern Conference title, four games to one. 
</P>
<P>
	The chance to see the Sabres' long-awaited return to the Stanley  
Cup finals brought Adam Becker of Buffalo and his sister, Amanda, 
to the arena at about 7:00 p.m. Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was pretty cold after a while,'' Becker said.  
</P>
<P>
	Season-ticket holders and fans who bought 10-packs of tickets  
for the regular season purchased in advance 14,000 tickets for each 
game of the finals, said Ron Bertovich, the Sabres' executive vice 
president of administration. 
</P>
<P>
	About 2,000 other tickets went to the NHL, competing teams and  
ownership, and 300 more were lost to an auxiliary press box, he 
said. That left about 2,000 tickets per game for the general 
public, available at the box office and through Tops supermarkets, 
an Internet site, and by phone. 
</P>
<P>
	About 590 tickets sold in the first minute, Bertovich said. At  
least two games, perhaps as many as three, will be played in 
Buffalo because the Western Conference champion will have home-ice 
advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to put tickets in as many people's hands as  
possible,'' Bertovich said. ``There was a small quantity for the 
level of interest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Schappert was among a dozen or so newly graduated St.  
Francis High School students willing to wait all night in the rain 
to spend his graduation money on tickets. He wished someone would 
have told him he had virtually no chance of getting them. 
</P>
<P>
	``They knew we weren't going to get tickets,'' he said, ``and  
they let us stay here overnight.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
