<HEADLINE> Six Die in Crash on Penn. Turnpike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEDFORD, Pa. (AP) -- Two sets of Amish sisters were among six  
people killed when their van swerved through a highway divider and 
plowed into an oncoming truck. 
</P>
<P>
	A seventh occupant of the van survived and was hospitalized. The  
truck driver was not seriously injured. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ford van was traveling west on the Pennsylvania Turnpike  
early Monday about 115 miles southeast of Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	The group was returning to an Amish community in southwest Homer  
City after a weekend trip to Intercourse, in the southeastern part 
of the state, said surviving passenger Benjamin King. He was in 
fair condition today at UPMC-Bedford Memorial Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The van went out of control, hit the divider and crossed into  
the eastbound lane, state police said. Three passengers were thrown 
from the vehicle when it struck the tractor-trailer rig head-on and 
then burst into flames. 
</P>
<P>
	State police said the cause of the wreck was still under  
investigation. King, who was being treated for a broken collarbone 
and punctured lung, said he was asleep before the crash and didn't 
know what went wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims were identified as King's brother, Amis King, 21, of  
Penn Run; Martha Stoltzfus, 19, and her sister, Anna Mae, 17, both 
of Homer City; Lydia King, 20, and her sister, Suzie, 16, both of 
Gap; and the van's non-Amish driver, Randy Brubaker, 40, of Homer 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	The Amish often hire drivers because their religious beliefs  
discourage driving. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
