<DOCNO> APW19990601.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 15:53:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: No Compromise on Peacekeepers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NATO will not compromise on its demand that  
the alliance be ``at the core'' of any peacekeeping force that 
enters Kosovo as part of a settlement to end airstrikes against 
Yugoslavia, the Clinton administration said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``By being at the core, that means there must be a command and  
control structure that is NATO's in charge of any peacekeeping 
operation,'' Defense Secretary William Cohen told reporters after 
addressing a suburban Washington high school. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, after meeting with  
Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini, said the United States and 
Italy are ``solidly behind these objectives and we will not settle 
for less.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dini, agreeing, said Italy was not proposing a pause in NATO's  
air campaign until Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic accepted 
all the conditions set out by the alliance. ``We cannot, at this 
point, fall into negotiating tricks,'' Dini said. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO is planning to put as many as 50,000 armed troops in a  
peacekeeping force, but Cohen reiterated that the alliance would 
enter Kosovo only after Milosevic gives up fighting ethnic Albanian 
rebels and withdraws his troops -- not to invade and expel Serb 
forces. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO military representatives met in Brussels, Belgium, on  
Tuesday to determine how many peacekeepers each member country 
would contribute to the 50,000-troop total. At the Pentagon, 
spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the United States would provide about 
15 percent of the total, which would be about 7,500. Bacon would 
not be more specific, but he indicated the administration would 
announce a firm figure shortly. 
</P>
<P>
	Bacon also raised the possibility that NATO would not get  
peacekeepers into Kosovo soon enough to return all of the more than 
1 million displaced ethnic Albanians to Kovoso before the winter 
sets in. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if there were a peace agreement tomorrow or next week,  
it's not reasonable to assume that every refugee would return home 
instantly, and some may end up in Macedonia or Albania through the 
winter,'' Bacon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen also ruled out a pause in the 70-day-old NATO bombing  
campaign, as demanded in a letter delivered from Belgrade on 
Tuesday to German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer in which 
Yugoslav officials said they accepted a peace proposal by the G-8 
group of major industrialized nations and Russia. On the sticky 
question of allowing NATO into Kosovo, the letter acceded to ``a 
United Nations presence, mandate and other elements to be decided 
by a U.N. Security Council resolution in accordance with the United 
Nations charter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen said the bombing would stop only when Milosevic accepted  
all of NATO's main demands, including the return of hundreds of 
thousands of ethnic Albanians refugees, and withdrawal of his 
troops to demonstrate his acceptance of peace. 
</P>
<P>
	``A pause would only serve Milosevic's interests,'' Cohen said.  
``He is seeking to try to divide the alliance. He's seeking delay. 
We are now at the point where the air campaign is being intensified 
on a 24-hour basis.'' He said the bombing is exacting a ``heavy 
penalty'' from Milosevic and his military. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright met with Dini as part of a series of sessions with NATO  
foreign ministers to show unity in the alliance. She said Milosevic 
had accepted the principles established by Russia and seven 
industrialized democracies but not NATO's conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	The G-8 nations did not specify, as the alliance does, that all  
Serb troops must quit Kosovo and that NATO be at the core of the 
peacekeeping mission designed to guarantee safe return of ethnic 
Albanian refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	``Foreign Minister Dini and I, along with other allies, remain  
committed to concluding the conflict on the basis of the conditions 
NATO set and the international community endorsed,'' Albright said. 
``The Serb forces must leave Kosovo so that the refugees and 
displaced persons may return safely to their homes. And (an) 
international military presence with NATO at its core must be 
established. And the people of Kosovo must be allowed democratic 
self-governance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Bonn, Germany, Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari and  
Russia's special Balkans envoy, Viktor Chernomyrdin, met with 
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott in hopes of establishing a 
common position that Ahtisaari and Chernomyrdin could take to 
Belgrade on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech to students at Woodbridge High School in Woodbridge,  
Va., Cohen portrayed NATO's air war against Yugoslavia as a 
struggle to reverse Milosevic's inhumane treatment of ethnic 
Albanians, who before the start of NATO's bombing made up about 90 
percent of Kosovo's population. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Kosovo we have a situation in which one man has decided  
that a whole group of people should be expunged from the face of 
the Earth -- that they should be ethnically cleansed,'' Cohen said 
to several hundred students. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that more than 1 million ethnic Albanians have been  
driven from their homes in the past several months. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot continue to watch this kind of a campaign carried  
out, something we thought was beyond our imagination, that we 
thought was over at the end of World War II,'' Cohen said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
