<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lukas Wants Charismatic Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Trainer D. Wayne Lukas is concerned about  
Charismatic's competition when he bids for the Triple Crown in the 
Belmont Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	He wants the best available. He doesn't want to hear comments  
about the quality of the rivals or questions about whether 
Charismatic deserves to be a Triple Crown champion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just hope everybody who has one ready runs him,'' Lukas  
said. ``We don't want any second-guessing on Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Kentucky Derby-Preakness winner ran Tuesday at Churchill  
Downs on a track wet from overnight rain, his final significant 
work before Saturday's race. 
</P>
<P>
	Also working for the final time was the filly Silverbulletday,  
one of Charismatic's major challengers in what is expected to be a 
12-horse field for the 1 1/2-mile classic. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic worked in predawn darkness at about 6 a.m. EDT and  
went five-eighths of a mile in 1:00 2-5, going the last quarter in 
24 seconds. He galloped out three-quarters in 1:14. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was pleased,'' Lukas said. ``I was happy he was able to  
stretch his legs and open his lungs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday, who will be making her debut against males,  
worked five-eighths of a mile about 2 1/2 hours later. 
</P>
<P>
	Trainer Bob Baffert said the winner of 11 of 12 starts, was  
timed in 59 1-5 and galloped out in 1:12. 
</P>
<P>
	``Doesn't she look beautiful, though,'' Baffert said as the  
filly raced down the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was fantastic,'' Baffert said. ``It showed me what I was  
looking for.'' Then, he quipped, ``I don't know what I was looking 
for, but it looked good when I saw it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I just hope she runs the way she worked,'' said owner Mike  
Pegram, also owner of the Baffert-owned Real Quiet, who failed to 
win the Triple Crown last year when he finished second in the 
Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert also missed the Triple Crown in 1997 with a second-place  
Belmont finish by Silver Charm, owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis, 
owners of Charismatic. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, Silverbulletday and three other Belmont contenders  
-- Prime Directive, Patience Game and Pineaff -- will be flown from 
Louisville to New York on Wednesday. They are expected to arrive at 
Belmont Park at about 10 a.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	Another top Belmont contender, Menifee, second in both the Derby  
and Preakness, already is at Belmont Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, a strapping chestnut, seems to have started acting  
like a star. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's getting a little more difficult to handle, but only since  
the Preakness (May 15),'' Lukas said. ``He's a little more on the 
muscle. That could be from (all of) the racing. It's not a problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The Belmont will be Charismatic's fifth race in 10 weeks. A  
fourth straight victory -- he won the Lexington on April 18 at 
Keeneland -- would make him the 12th Triple Crown winner and the 
first since Affirmed in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday will be the 21st filly to start in 131 Belmonts.  
The only two to win were Ruthless in the first Belmont in 1867 and 
Tanya in 1905. Ruthless beat three males over 1 5-8 miles, and 
Tanya beat six rivals, including another filly, at 1 1/4 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	``If she wins it's going to be a great race,'' Baffert said.  
``If Charismatic wins, it's going to be a great race. It will be 
good for racing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also expected to be entered Wednesday are Adonis, Best of Luck,  
Lemon Drop Kid, Stephen Got Even, Vision and Verse and Teletable. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
