<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybeans Down on Good Weather / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices fell sharply  
early today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid near-ideal growing 
conditions for spring crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors quickly removed a risk premium added amid uncertainty  
over weather conditions during the long Memorial Day weekend. 
Forecasters now are predicting warm weather and scattered showers 
across Midwest growing regions this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Those weather conditions should prove ideal for early growth of  
corn and spring wheat crops, where farmers were expected to have 
completed planting in the past week. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat also was pressured by upcoming active harvesting of the  
winter wheat crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 4 3/4 cents to $2.47 1/2 a bushel; July  
corn fell 5 1/4 cents to $2.14 1/4 a bushel; July oats fell 2 cents to 
$1.21 a bushel; July soybeans fell 7 3/4 cents to $4.54 a bushel 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and pork futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while feeder cattle advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle fell .05 cent to 64.20 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .23 cent to 75.75 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell .93 cent to 52.02 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell .72 
cent to 52.65 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
