<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airlines Working on China Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Fewer restrictions and the advent of larger  
airplanes mean U.S. airlines are brawling over carrier rights to 
China, the world's largest market with some of the tightest 
restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives of Beijing and Washington signed an agreement in  
April that relaxes the rules on flying to and from China. Those 
changes, along with the recent introduction of the Boeing 777, 
which can fly farther and bypass gate-restrictive Japan, will allow 
air carriers to fly straight to Asia, where air travel is growing 
10 percent annually. The 777 is capable of carrying up to 328 
passengers a distance of 8,300 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 777 certainly makes China a reality for American,'' said  
John Hotard, a spokesman for the Fort Worth-based airline. ``Now, 
nonstop or direct service into China will make it much easier for 
the U.S. carriers to do business in that region.'' 
</P>
<P>
	China, which let foreign investors into the country 20 years  
ago, has long kept some sectors, such as aviation, closed to 
outside investment. The country had been offering to make 
concessions in its trade barriers to get backing for World Trade 
Organization membership, a goal it has sought for 13 years. 
</P>
<P>
	But deliberations between China and the U.S. faltered not long  
after the aviation deal was struck. The success of further talks 
has grown unlikely recently due to violent anti-U.S. demonstrations 
in Beijing to protest NATO's mistaken bombing of the Chinese 
Embassy in Belgrade and by recent allegations of Chinese nuclear 
spying. 
</P>
<P>
	Those incidents will not effect the aviation deal signed April  
9, according to Bob Adams, a spokesman for the Department of 
Transportation. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal will double the total number of passenger and cargo  
flights among all U.S. airlines between the two countries from 27 
to 54. The Department of Transportation plans to award eight new 
flights immediately and nine more on April 1, 2000. The rest will 
be added in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement removes all restrictions on gateway departure  
cities from the United States. Passengers traveling to China 
currently must go from New York, Chicago, Los Angeles, Anchorage, 
Alaska, San Francisco, Honolulu, Seattle and Detroit. They must 
land in Beijing, Shanghai or Guangzhou. 
</P>
<P>
	And the changes allow each country to authorize one more carrier  
to fly between the nations. Currently, United Airlines, Northwest 
Airlines and Federal Express fly to China. 
</P>
<P>
	-- FedEx, the world's largest air express shipping company, has  
four flights a week landing at either Beijing or Shanghai. The unit 
of Memphis, Tenn.-based FDX Corp. would like to triple its number 
of flights. 
</P>
<P>
	The cargo-only air carrier said it would petition for eight more  
slots, but did not release what other cities it hopes to serve. 
</P>
<P>
	-- United Airlines plans to ask for rights to launch new nonstop  
service from San Francisco to Shanghai. United currently serves 
Shanghai and Beijing with one-stop service in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Northwest operates five nonstop flights to Beijing from  
Detroit and sends other passengers from Detroit to Beijing via 
Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our success to Beijing was wonderful,'' said Northwest  
spokesman Jon Austin. About 80 percent of seats are sold on 
Northwest's four-times-a-week flights to China, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline has not announced where it would add new flights.  
</P>
<P>
	With only one additional carrier to receive permission to fly to  
China under the deal, the interested airlines will lobby Washington 
for the routes. 
</P>
<P>
	-- American is considering Dallas-Fort Worth and Chicago as  
origination gateways, but hasn't yet filed for anything specific. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mainly we have just said we're interested in serving China  
when those routes become available,'' Hotard said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Atlanta-based Delta Air Lines has said it hopes to fly between  
Portland, Ore., and China. As the carrier prepares its bid to fly 
to China, it has cut service between Portland and Seoul, South 
Korea, and postponed its Osaka, Japan, launch because of the 
economic downturn in Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	China's own fledgling commercial airlines, all but two of which  
are government-owned, lost $300 million last year. Chinese airlines 
had been forced to cancel up to 900 domestic flights a week, 
according to Airline Industry Information. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, airline capacity to the Pacific will top all other routes  
during most of the year, according to Salomon Smith Barney's 
Quarter Regional Capacity Analysis. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
