<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SFX To Buy Most of Livent's Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In a bid to become a major player on Broadway,  
SFX Entertainment, the nation's leading producer of live music 
shows, is offering to buy most of the assets of troubled Canadian 
musical producer Livent. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the deal were not disclosed Tuesday by either company,  
although published reports last week put the expected purchase 
price at more than $100 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale, which must be approved by a federal bankruptcy court,  
includes Livent theaters in New York, Chicago and Toronto as well 
as rights to current Livent productions, which include ``Fosse,'' 
``Ragtime'' and the Toronto production of ``The Phantom of the 
Opera.'' It does not include a theater in Vancouver or Livent's 
headquarters in Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	SFX already is a powerhouse on the road, not only in staging and  
promoting concerts and other live entertainment, but in touring 
Broadway shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Through its subsidiary, Pace Theatrical Group, it is producing,  
co-producing or has investments in current tours of ``Cabaret,'' 
``Evita'' and ``Chicago,'' among other shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Pace also has produced or co-produced several Broadway musicals,  
including the long-running ``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde,'' and ``The Civil 
War,'' which has been struggling at the box office since opening in 
April. 
</P>
<P>
	SFX was born out of SFX Broadcasting, a radio company founded by  
Robert F.X. Sillerman in 1992 and which he sold five years later 
for millions. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past two years, SFX has aggressively purchased  
amphitheaters, ticketing agencies and music-promoting offices. The 
company controls more than 82 venues and last year produced or 
promoted over 13,000 events attended by 37 million people. 
</P>
<P>
	Livent filed for bankruptcy protection in November after its new  
owners, which include Hollywood super-agent Michael Ovitz, said 
they discovered accounting fraud by the company's Canadian 
founders, Garth Drabinsky and Myron Gottlieb. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. authorities filed fraud and conspiracy charges against  
Drabinsky and Gottlieb, but the two men have denied any wrongdoing 
and remained in Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	SFX also will acquire rights to projects Livent had in  
preparation, including a musical version of the film ``Sweet Smell 
of Success'' and ``The Seussical,'' based on the Dr. Seuss stories, 
which has a score by Stephen Flaherty and Lynn Ahrens, who wrote 
``Ragtime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ironically, Livent's sale comes at a time when two of the shows  
Drabinsky nurtured and brought to fruition, ``Fosse'' and 
``Parade,'' are the top contenders for the best musical prize at 
the 1999 Tony Awards this Sunday. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
