<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
 *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *Merrill Lynch fell 8 3/4 to 75 1/4    	
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street brokerage unveiled plans to offer an Internet  
site for individuals to buy and sell stocks for $29.95 a trade. The 
new service is a big departure for Merrill, which makes billions of 
dollars annually through full-fee commissions. 

</P>
<P>
 *Aquarion Co. rose 3 1/2 to 34 9/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Britain's Yorkshire Water PLC will buy Aquarion, a  
Connecticut-based water treatment company, for $440 million, or 
$37.05 per share. The two companies have been working together for 
several years. 

</P>
<P>
 *AmSouth Bancorporation fell 3 15/16 to 24 7/16  
</P>
<P>
 *First American Corp. rose 2 13/16 to 43 5/8 
</P>
<P>
	AmSouth Bancorporation is buying First American Corp. for $6.3  
billion in stock. The deal will create a banking concern with 
operations in nine Southern states from Kentucky to Florida. 

</P>
<P>
 *Crompton &AMP; Knowles Corp. rose 1 1/4 to 19 5/8  
</P>
<P>
 *Witco Corp. rose 15/16 to 18 7/16 
</P>
<P>
	The rival specialty-chemicals companies will merge in a deal  
estimated at $1 billion in stock, plus $1 billion in assumed debt. 
The combined company, to be known as C&AMP;K Witco, will have annual 
revenues of $3.2 billion. 

</P>
<P>
 *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Telebanc Financial Corporation rose 8 to 74 1/2  
</P>
<P>
 *ETrade Group Inc. fell 5 3/16 to 39 5/16 
</P>
<P>
	ETrade is buying online banker Telebanc Financial Corporation  
for about $1.8 billion in stock, creating an Internet-based 
financial services company. 

</P>
<P>
 *Dialogic Corp. rose 10 1/16 to 43 7/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Intel Corp. plans to buy telecommunications software maker  
Dialogic Corp. for about $780 million. The combined company's 
products are expected to allow e-mail, voice mail and the Internet 
to run on one computer system. 

</P>
<P>
 *Silknet Software.com rose 3/8 to 37 7/8    	
</P>
<P>
	Investment firms Credit Suisse First Boston and BancBoston  
Robertson Stephens launched coverage of Silknet with ``buy'' 
ratings. Silknet makes software that lets companies link sales and 
marketing functions through a single Web site. 

</P>
<P>
 *Complete Business Solutions Inc. fell 7 7/8 to 16 3/8    	
</P>
<P>
	An SG Cowen &AMP; Co. analyst trimmed his 1999 and 2000 earnings  
views on the company, citing delays in overseas projects. Complete 
Business provides information technology services, including Year 
2000 computer conversion. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
