<DOCNO> APW19990601.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 12:10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Crisis Closes 400 Venezuela Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- A reduction in Venezuelan oil  
production has caused some 400 private oil companies to shut down 
and thousands of workers to lose their jobs, according to industry 
figures. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are facing a recession never before seen in the country's  
history,'' Hugo Hernandez, first vice-president of the Venezuelan 
Petroleum Chamber, said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Venezuela, which competes with Saudi Arabia as the No. 1 foreign  
supplier of oil to the United States, has cut its oil production 
this year as part of an effort to prop up sagging prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The policy has been largely successful, with the price of a  
barrel of Venezuelan oil having gone from a low of $7 last year to 
a current price of about $14. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the oil sector has paid a heavy price.  
</P>
<P>
	Central Bank official Armando Leon told The Associated Press  
that his organization expects the petroleum sector to contract by 8 
percent this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past eight months, some 12,000 oil workers have been laid  
off, according to the Petroleum Workers Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil accounts for about 40 percent of all economic activity in  
Venezuela, and about three-quarters of the country's export 
earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez said the 400 petroleum companies that have closed were  
in the areas of engineering, drilling, well services, construction 
and supplies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
