<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 16:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AL, Indians' Wright Hold Discussion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jaret Wright and AL president Gene Budig met  
Tuesday about the perception of some that the Cleveland Indians 
star has a tendency to throw many inside pitches. 
</P>
<P>
	The AL apparently wants the issue put to rest because officials  
think they might have gone too far in announcing the meeting with 
Wright about his ``deportment on the mound.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I regard the content as private,'' Budig said. ``It was a  
meaningful discussion. The matter is closed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians hope the matter is closed for Wright, who was  
affected by the public announcement of the meeting last Thursday. 
Wright was hammered for eight runs and nine hits in a season-low 3 
2-3 innings in a 12-5 loss to Boston the next night and later 
admitted the discussion got ``into his head a little bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wright, who likes to control the inside part of the plate, kept  
most of his pitches away against the Red Sox and paid the price. 
The Indians want to make sure he doesn't make the same mistake 
Wednesday against the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jaret was really unfocused and distracted in his last start,''  
manager Mike Hargrove said. ``He has to compartmentalize his 
thoughts better. Good athletes are able to do that. He did not do 
that his last start because there was still a lot of stuff 
unresolved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove said the 75-minute meeting resolved most of those  
issues. Wright refused to talk before Tuesday's game against the 
Yankees, but Hargrove said his pitcher seemed more at ease when 
they left the league offices. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a good meeting, a good exchange of ideas,'' Hargrove  
said. ``All of my fears were put to rest. Beyond that, we agreed to 
keep the rest private.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wright has a history of hitting batters. He hit 11 last year and  
four already this season. He was suspended for five games earlier 
this season for hitting Boston outfielder Darren Lewis in the head 
and he was called into Budig's office after hitting Detroit's Tony 
Clark. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright also raised the ire of the Yankees in spring training in  
1998, when he broke Luis Sojo's hand with a pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to be able to pitch inside, but you don't have to hit  
people,'' Hargrove said. ``Roger Clemens does that as well as 
anybody. Jaret Wright is just a younger version of that type of 
power pitcher.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
