<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan Calls Kosovo a 'Blunder' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful Pat Buchanan  
said Tuesday that the NATO attacks on Kosovo were a blunder that 
``may prove the ruin of the most successful alliance in history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seeking to set himself apart from his rivals for the GOP  
presidential nomination, Buchanan said George W. Bush, John McCain, 
Elizabeth Dole and Steve Forbes were ``virtual Xerox copies'' of 
President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore when it comes to the 
Balkans and a variety of other trade and economic issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican nominee next year must take a different stand on  
such policies or lose voters, he said in a speech at the National 
Press Club. 
</P>
<P>
	``While all are good and able individuals, all four endorsed the  
president's decision to launch this war on Serbia,'' he said. ``Mr. 
Bush, Mrs. Dole and Sen. McCain even endorse sending a U.S. Army to 
fight its way into the Balkans to occupy Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am not a citizen of the world; I am an American,'' Buchanan  
said. ``And I am not running for president of the world, but for 
president of the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bombing of Yugoslavia is unfairly targeting utilities and  
other basic services that hurt the ordinary people of Serbia, he 
said, adding the bombing campaign ``may prove the ruin of the most 
successful alliance in history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan is running in single digits in the latest national and  
New Hampshire polls of GOP candidates. But he said he's not worried 
about his distance behind front-runner Bush, the Texas governor. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're gauging things compared to how we were doing in May and  
June at this time in the last election,'' he said in an interview 
after his speech. ``There are far more people coming out. There's 
no doubt you don't have the explosive electricity you had in 
January and February of 1996.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire pollster Dick Bennett said there's a higher  
expectation for Buchanan this year since he was winner of the 
state's primary in 1996, but he noted Buchanan made the most impact 
in the closing weeks before the primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Duprey, New Hampshire GOP party chairman, said Buchanan  
has more competition for the conservative vote this time from 
Forbes, former Vice President Quayle and others. 
</P>
<P>
	``When he comes up here, he sounds out his themes and he has a  
real good ear,'' Duprey said. ``He figures out which message 
resonates with voters and then hammers it out with a real 
discipline. Anybody who underestimates him is making a big 
mistake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan ruled out a third-party bid if he doesn't win the GOP  
nomination. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
