<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Refuses N.Y. Harassment Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Having recently decided that schools can be  
sued under one federal law for failing to stop student sexual 
harassment, the Supreme Court today refused to clarify whether such 
lawsuits can rely on another federal law as well. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, without comment, turned away the case of a New York  
girl who says school officials did nothing to stop her male 
classmates from sexually harassing her. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal appeals court had refused to reinstate a civil rights  
claim made in the girl's behalf. It said her school district could 
be sued only under a law banning bias in federally funded schools -- 
a claim she already had lost in a jury trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Eve Bruneau said she and other female classmates were repeatedly  
harassed by boys in her sixth-grade class at South Kortright 
Central School during the 1993-94 school year. 
</P>
<P>
	Her lawsuit said boys regularly called the girls derogatory  
names and that the boys grabbed the girls' breasts, stuffed paper 
down their blouses and cut their hair. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit said Bruneau and her mother repeatedly complained to  
school officials who did little about the problem and refused to 
transfer her to another class. In March 1994, she transferred to 
another school. 
</P>
<P>
	Her mother, Pat Schofield, sued under a much-used federal civil  
rights law, alleging a violation of her daughter's constitutional 
right to equal protection. The suit also invoked an anti-bias law 
known as Title IX of the Education Amendments of 1972, which bans 
gender discrimination in schools that receive federal funding. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge in Binghamton, N.Y., ruled for the school  
district on the civil rights claim, saying Congress intended for 
such lawsuits to be filed under Title IX. After a trial, a jury 
ruled against Mrs. Schofield's Title IX claim. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals refused to revive the  
civil rights lawsuit. Title IX provides the exclusive remedy for 
such claims, the appeals court said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court ruled last week that schools can be sued under  
Title IX when school officials fail to stop students from sexually 
harassing other students. But that decision did not address school 
liability under the separate civil rights law. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for Schofield and Bruneau  
said Congress did not intend to shut off civil rights lawsuits when 
it enacted Title IX. Federal appeals courts have split on that 
issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The school district's lawyers said she should not be allowed to  
sue again because she already lost a sex-harassment claim based on 
the same facts. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Bruneau vs. South Kortright Central School District,  
98-1541. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
