<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Serbs Say NATO Derailing Peace  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Less than 24 hours before  
Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic is to meet with 
international envoys, NATO bombing remains intense, and Serb 
officials are saying that means NATO wants to derail any peace 
efforts. Every time a breakthrough seems near, Goran Matic, a 
government minister who is believed close to Milosevic said, there 
is ``an intensification of the bombing that turns these diplomatic 
efforts useless.'' NATO, for its part, showed no letup in the air 
bombardment, striking Serb military targets across Kosovo and 
hitting several locations. 

</P>
<P>
	Teamsters' Deadline Nears Again  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Time is winding down for the contract talks  
between companies that haul new cars to dealerships and the 
Teamsters, with a midnight strike deadline looming. The talks were 
already extended after a last-minute offer by the companies last 
night. ``We're making progress but it's going to be a late 
evening,'' Teamsters president James P. Hoffa said. Among remaining 
points of contention that Hoffa has said the union is willing to 
strike over are the companies' proposals to start new workers at 
lower wages and to hire part-time drivers. 

</P>
<P>
	Jones Lawyers Want Fee From Clinton  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- President Clinton's proposal for what  
he should pay in his Paula Jones case ``would do little precious to 
redress'' his misconduct, a Jones representative said. In documents 
filed today, John W. Whitehead and the Rutherford Institute said 
the sanctions proposed by Clinton would be of little help. Mrs. 
Jones' lawyers have asked the court to order Clinton to pay almost 
$500,000. Clinton's lawyers on May 21 proposed that the president 
pay $33,737 to the court and other attorneys for Mrs. Jones. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton Meets Potential Staff  
</P>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- While not making an official announcement  
about her potential run for the Senate, First lady Hillary Rodham 
Clinton interviewed potential campaign staff at the White House 
today. She also told at least two associates that she intends to 
seek the Senate seat from New York. The associates said Mrs. 
Clinton is virtually certain to seek the seat being vacated by 
retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan and is close to finalizing 
that decision. A senior adviser to the first lady said the decision 
is not quite final, ``but she's edging awfully close to it.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Sinn Fein Takes Deputy Mayor's Post  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The IRA-linked Sinn Fein party  
won the deputy mayor's post on the Belfast City Council for the 
first time today, reflecting the rising Catholic population in the 
capital of Northern Ireland. Marie Moore, one of Sinn Fein's 13 
members on the 52-member council, was elected on a 26-25 vote. 
Besides her party colleagues, support came from the Social 
Democratic and Labor Party, which moderate Catholics support, and 
the middle-of-the-road Alliance Party, which draws support from 
both sides of the community. 

</P>
<P>
	Cuban Lawsuit Seeks $181B From U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Saying that it has suffered in U.S. attacks over  
the last four decades, Cuba filed a lawsuit demanding $181 billion 
from the U.S. government for damages, the Communist Party daily 
Granma reported today. The lawsuit filed yesterday was in response 
to a U.S. federal court judge's demand that the Cuban government 
pay the families of three of four civilian pilots killed in a 
shootdown off the island's coast in 1996. The tribunal said that 
the U.S. government had caused far more death and damage with 
incursions into Cuban territory and attacks on diplomatic missions 
and aircraft in the last 40 years. 

</P>
<P>
	Air Fares Hike Upwards Again  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The cost of flying is up almost 11 percent this  
year after another fare increase from the major airlines at the 
start of the summer travel season. The third fare increase of 1999 
is expected to stick since Northwest Airlines Corp. has gone along 
with a 4 percent increase levied by Continental Airlines last week. 
Northwest has been the stickler in the fare game for the air 
industry. Last year, more than a dozen attempts to raise airline 
fares failed because Northwest declined to go along with other 
airlines' prices. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Mixed; Nikkei Slips 35.56  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks traded mixed Wednesday amid hopes  
of additional measures to aid Japan's slumping economy. The Nikkei 
slipped 35.56 to 16,372.94 in early trading. On Wall Street, the 
Dow industrials closed up today 36.52 at 10,596.26. 

</P>
<P>
	Stars Force Game Seven  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The Dallas stars, top-seeded in the West, forced a  
deciding Game 7 with the Colorado Avalanche tonight as Jamie 
Langenbrunner scored twice in the third period to lead the Stars a 
4-1 victory over the Avalanche. Game 7 is Friday night in Dallas, 
where the Stars are 6-2 in the playoffs -- with both losses coming 
in this series. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
  	   	
</P>
