<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Golfer Seeks To Defend NCAA Title  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHASKA, Minn. (AP) -- James McLean never thought he'd be this  
nervous as he prepared to defend his title at the NCAA men's golf 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, he didn't count on being without his driver, either.  
</P>
<P>
	McLean, the University of Minnesota sophomore known for his long  
tee shots, nervously awaited a new driver Tuesday after a friend 
accidentally broke his precious club at Hazeltine National Golf 
Course, site of this week's 72-hole tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``The driver's nonexistent at the moment,'' said McLean, who  
expected to get a new one by day's end. ``Definitely, I'm a little 
nervous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Following Monday's practice round, McLean headed to the driving  
range, where fellow Australian Adam Scott, a freshman from UNLV, 
asked if he could borrow his driver to hit a few shots. 
</P>
<P>
	``He bent down to pick up a tee and snapped it accidentally,''  
McLean said. ``I didn't know what to think. Panic sunk in. He went 
into shock. He was really speechless.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The club manufacturer was on hand and went scrambling with  
McLean's specifications to get a replacement in time for 
Wednesday's first round of the four-day tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, it shouldn't take too long to get used to it,''  
said McLean, who is trying to become the first player since Phil 
Mickelson (1989-90) to win consecutive NCAA titles. 
</P>
<P>
	Even without the distress over his driver, McLean was preparing  
himself for a tough week in which he figures a 5- or 6-under par 
might win the title. Last year, he tied a championship record with 
a 17-under at Albuquerque, N.M. 
</P>
<P>
	McLean and Georgia Tech's Matt Kuchar, who won the U.S. amateur  
championship two years ago and sparkled in the Masters and U.S. 
Open, lead a remarkably balanced field in which any one of 40 or 
more golfers stand a decent chance to win the individual title. 
</P>
<P>
	The field is so tough that top-ranked Joel Kribel of Stanford  
and SMU's Hank Kuehne, defending U.S. amateur champion, failed to 
qualify. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd say 30 or 40 could win it. It might be more than that,''  
McLean said. ``I came out of the pack last year and I wasn't 
expected to do it. And I'm sure a guy could do just the same this 
year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McLean, Kuchar and the rest of the NCAA field, including  
defending team champion UNLV, will take on a 7,196-yard, par-72 
layout featuring big greens, U.S. Open-like rough and a reputation 
for turning into a monster if the winds whip up. 
</P>
<P>
	They did that Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``You can't learn the whole course in a couple of days,'' said  
Paul Casey of Arizona State, who shot a collegiate record 
10-under-par 60 in the final round of the Pac-10 championship last 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	The private course is difficult on so many levels.  
</P>
<P>
	``The length is definitely a factor,'' McLean said. ``The greens  
are hard and fast and they can tuck the flags away if they want to. 
And the rough's up. So, all that tends to make the course pretty 
tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The benefit for McLean and his teammates, who won the Big Ten  
title two weeks ago, is they've played this complicated course 
many, many times. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's definitely a little bit of an advantage, just knowing the  
course, knowing the greens,'' McLean said. ``But still, you've got 
to play the course and it's a tough course. You can't really get 
complacent out there because it will jump up and bite you. So, I've 
got to play it fairly safe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And you can bet McLean won't be lending out that new driver this  
week, either. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
