<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aussie Pleads Innocent in Spy Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- A former Australian intelligence analyst,  
lured to this country and arrested in an FBI sting last month, 
pleaded innocent Tuesday to a charge of attempting to sell U.S. 
defense secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	Jean-Philippe Wispelaere entered his plea through his  
court-appointed attorney, Nina Ginsberg, who requested a jury 
trial. The sandy-haired 28-year-old, wearing a green jumpsuit with 
``Prisoner'' printed on the back, stood silently beside his 
attorney during the seven-minute proceeding. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge T.S. Ellis III set trial for Sept. 13 after  
Ginsberg waived Wispelaere's right, under the Speedy Trial Act, to 
have it begin in late July. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsberg said she needed additional time for a ``substantial  
inquiry into whether the information (Wispelaere gave undercover 
agents) could actually aid a foreign country or be harmful to this 
country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the agreement of prosecutor Robert Spencer, Ginsberg sought  
an Oct. 1 trial date to give her co-counsel, Greg Beckwith, time to 
get a security clearance and help review the classified 
information. But Judge Ellis settled on September instead, noting 
that judges in the northern Virginia district prefer speedy 
proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said Wispelaere was paid $120,000 for nearly  
1,000 secret and top secret U.S. defense documents by undercover 
FBI agents who posed as foreign spies, lured him to Virginia and 
arrested him at Dulles International Airport last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Unmarried, Wispelaere is an Australian citizen whose last known  
address was in Australia. He told undercover FBI agents he needed 
money for a knee operation and other concerns ``involving 
females,'' according to an FBI affidavit. 
</P>
<P>
	On a single count of attempted espionage, he faces a maximum  
penalty of life in prison, or even death if certain conditions, 
such as disclosure of nuclear secrets, are met. 
</P>
<P>
	Wispelaere worked for Australian military intelligence from July  
1998 until his abrupt resignation Jan. 13. The U.S. government 
alleges that six days later he walked into the Bangkok embassy of a 
foreign country, which U.S. officials would not identify, and 
offered to sell classified U.S. documents. That country tipped off 
U.S. officials and FBI agents set up a meeting with him. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI said he sold 713 classified U.S. defense documents,  
including photographs presumably from U.S. spy satellites, to an 
undercover FBI agent in Bangkok for $70,000. He also mailed more 
than 200 others to a post office box the FBI set up in Virginia for 
an additional $50,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents had been shared with Australia under  
U.S.-Australian defense treaties, and the U.S. government said 
their disclosure could cause ``exceptionally great damage'' to U.S. 
national security. 
</P>
<P>
	Wispelaere is being held without bond.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
