<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A band of strong thunderstorms moving across eastern Oklahoma  
spawned several tornadoes Tuesday night, including one that killed 
a person and injured several others. 
</P>
<P>
	A woman died when a twister hit two communities on the eastern  
shores of Fort Gibson Lake. Six other people were injured, one 
critically. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, fair and warm weather continued along much of the  
East Coast, while showers and thunderstorms were seen in parts of 
the Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the big cities in the Northeast and Mid-Atlantic hit the  
80s. 
</P>
<P>
	Moisture surged northward on the back side a high pressure area  
over the Mid-Atlantic states and brought clouds and scattered 
showers to the Ohio and Tennessee valleys. 
</P>
<P>
	Other showers and thundershowers were seen from Indiana, south  
across Kentucky and Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	A stationary frontal boundary extending from the eastern Great  
Lakes, through the middle-Mississippi Valley into the southern 
Plains produced some showers and thunderstorms. 
</P>
<P>
	Fair and dry weather continued over a large part of the West.  
</P>
<P>
	High pressure over the Rockies brought pleasant conditions to  
the western High Plains into the Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	A cold front sagging southward across the Pacific Northwest  
brought a few light showers to parts of Montana, Idaho and Oregon. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures across the Lower 48 ranged from a low of 30 in  
Leadville, Colo., to an early-afternoon high of 91 in Daggett, 
Calif. With the wind chill it felt like 16 in Leadville, while the 
heat index mate it feel like 96 in the Texas towns of Del Rio and 
Dyess. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
