<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Says Cyberstores Need Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Cybershopping is soaring, but a new survey found  
that improved customer service would help take online sales to new 
heights. 
</P>
<P>
	Online sales are expected to increase to $18 billion this year,  
up from $8 billion in 1998, but only 5.75 percent of consumers who 
visit e-commerce Web sites actually try to make a purchase, 
according to a poll by Net Effect and published in today's edition 
of USA Today. 
</P>
<P>
	And 67 percent of those attempted purchases are not completed,  
falling victim to the lack of real-time customer service and 
support, the five-month survey showed. 
</P>
<P>
	Net Effect, a British Internet consultant, studied two dozen  
companies, including Amazon.com, eToys and Dell Computer Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer concerns included deliveries, returns and product  
specifications. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet retailers should consider greeting new customers to  
their Web sites and recognizing them on future visits and be able 
to move customers with questions from an automated-response system 
to personal responses when needed, Julie Schoenfeld, chief 
executive officer of Net Effect, told USA Today. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 12:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rejects CNN Appeal Over Raid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court left in doubt Tuesday the  
fate of a lawsuit accusing Cable News Network of violating a 
Montana couple's privacy rights because its camera crew accompanied 
federal agents who raided their ranch. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices rejected, without comment, a CNN appeal of a  
federal appeals court ruling that said the network should have to 
defend itself at trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Just last week the justices threw out the Montana couple's  
lawsuit against the federal agents who agreed to let CNN accompany 
them on the 1993 raid. The court ruled last week that the federal 
officers cannot be sued because it was not clearly established in 
1993 that allowing such news media access was unlawful. 
</P>
<P>
	Logic would seem to dictate that CNN, too, should be protected  
against being sued. But a 1992 Supreme Court decision complicates 
matters. In that ruling, the court made it easier to sue private 
citizens accused of acting with government agents to violate 
someone's rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Private citizens do not enjoy the same ``qualified immunity''  
when violating a right that was not yet clearly established, the 
court said then, because ``the public interest will not be unduly 
impaired if private individuals are required to proceed to trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Where does that leave CNN? ``The short answer is `I don't know  
the answer,''' said Lee Levine, a Washington lawyer who filed a 
friend-of-the-court brief for a coalition of news organizations in 
the Montana case. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for the Atlanta-based network said CNN does not  
comment on pending litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still celebrating,'' said Henry Rossbacher, a Los  
Angeles lawyer representing the Montana couple. ``Now that the 
Supreme Court has denied review, we anticipate this case soon will 
go to trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The justices ruled last week that police violate people's  
privacy rights when they bring TV camera crews and other 
journalists into homes during arrests or searches. The court ruled 
unanimously that police who allow such access can be sued for 
violating the Constitution's Fourth Amendment ban on unreasonable 
searches and seizures. 
</P>
<P>
	But the court also said that violation of privacy rights was not  
obvious in 1993 and ordered the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals 
to restudy the Montana case. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN could be expected to argue that last week's decision  
scuttled the entire case -- against the federal agents and the 
network. 
</P>
<P>
	While last week's decision made clear that police can be held  
financially responsible for such incidents in the future, it 
remains undecided whether news media organizations also can be held 
liable. 
</P>
<P>
	Only governmental action -- not acts by private citizens or  
companies -- can violate someone's constitutional rights such as the 
Fourth Amendment's privacy protections. But private citizens and 
companies can be deemed to have been governmental agents under 
certain circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9th Circuit court ruled in the Montana case that CNN should  
be considered a government agent because it engaged in a ``joint 
action'' -- one carried out ``for the mutual benefit of both the 
private interests of the media and the government officials' 
interest in publicity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CNN's appeal said the ruling ``will result in less public  
scrutiny of government functions'' and ``raises important First 
Amendment issues.'' The amendment protects freedom of the press. 
</P>
<P>
	``Journalists pursuing news for independent, professional  
purposes do not act under color of law, even when their 
news-gathering activities inherently involve making arrangements 
with government officials,'' the appeal argued. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court's rejection of the appeal left intact the  
appeals court ruling as a legal precedent in nine Western states. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service agents raided the 75,000-acre  
ranch of Paul and Erma Berger after obtaining a search warrant to 
look for evidence that they were poisoning wildlife. 
</P>
<P>
	The government suspected the Bergers were using pesticides to  
poison endangered species such as eagles to protect their central 
Montana ranch's livestock from predators. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result of the raid, Paul Berger was charged with violating  
federal laws that protect eagles. But a trial jury acquitted him of 
all charges except improper use of a pesticide, a misdemeanor. 
</P>
<P>
	After Berger's trial, CNN used portions of its footage of the  
search on the environmental news programs ``Earth Matters'' and 
``Network Earth'' as part of its coverage of government efforts to 
protect endangered species. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 15:25:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Brack Had Everyone's Number at Indy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- For Kenny Brack, the final laps of the Indy 500  
came down to a simple matter of numbers and some long division. 
</P>
<P>
	Brack and his pit crew, headed by feisty car owner A.J. Foyt,  
had the calculations figured to the last decimal point, and it all 
added up to leader Robby Gordon running out of fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	And when that happened, it meant Brack would win the world's  
most famous car race. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew he would have to have to pit again,'' Brack said  
Tuesday, still aglow in his victory. ``He went in at lap 164. We 
went in at 169. To go 36 laps, you can't do it unless you have a 
bigger tank.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Gordon was equipped with the standard 35-gallon tank. So  
Brack was comfortable with his situation. It was just a matter of 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had to pit,'' Brack said. ``We weren't that worried.''  
</P>
<P>
	Still, auto racing is all about speed so Brack decided in the  
final laps to step on the gas -- since he had some left and Gordon 
did not. 
</P>
<P>
	There was, after all, the possibility that, despite a fuel  
indicator pointing to empty, Gordon wouldn't pull in, gambling that 
a yellow flag would come up at the end, protecting his position. It 
never did. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he had a yellow, obviously he'd be able to make it,'' Brack  
said. ``I was faster at the end. A yellow before that last lap 
would not have been so good. I was a second behind when he pulled 
in. It was a relief. After that, it was a cruise to the flag.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his headphone, Brack heard Foyt screaming, ``We won this  
thing!'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was a payoff for careful planning by Foyt and Brack and the  
rest of their team. The Swedish driver was cautious with his last 
fill-up of fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were economy driving after the last pit stop,'' Brack said.  
``By 193 or 194, we had saved enough to go faster at the end. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was conservative at the start. I was leading. I didn't want  
to do anything stupid to keep the lead. We kept pace. I knew there 
would be more yellows and a lot of stuff happening. I stayed on my 
pace. I didn't take unnecessary risks at the start, in the middle 
or at the end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His victory was worth $1,465,190, the second biggest prize in  
Indy history. 
</P>
<P>
	``To win a race like this, you have to prepare every little  
detail, when to take risks and when not to take risks,'' Brack 
said. ``You don't win by taking chances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And how much fuel was left in Brack's tank at the end?  
</P>
<P>
	``About two gallons,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	More than enough, it turned out.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 15:25:16 </DATE_TIME>
