<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Environment Groups Urge IOC Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- Three environmental groups today  
asked for a year's delay in choosing the host city for the 2006 
Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Three cities -- Sion, Switzerland; Turin, Italy; and Klagenfurt;  
Austria -- are front-runners for the 2006 Games. The other 
candidates are Helsinki, Finland; Zakopane, Poland; and 
Poprad-Tatry, Slovakia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Swiss, Italian and Austrian branches of the World Wide Fund  
for Nature want environmental issues further examined before a site 
is chosen. 
</P>
<P>
	The groups are affiliated with the World Wildlife Fund in the  
United States. They contend the Alps aren't suitable for events on 
the scale of the Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is no longer acceptable that Olympic ideals ... are brought  
to life at the price of the destruction of the environment,'' the 
WWF said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	An IOC panel will reduce the field of six European cities to two  
finalists in South Korea on June 19. On the same day, the full 
assembly will choose the winner. 
</P>
<P>
	An IOC commission is looking into ways of overhauling the IOC's  
structure and the process for selecting host cities. 
</P>
<P>
	The WWF says the IOC is mistaken in choosing a host city with  
all the Olympic venues within close range. Instead, it suggests the 
IOC choose a host country or region, minimizing the construction of 
short-term facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	The group said the IOC shouldn't wait until the 2010 Games to  
address environmental issues. The WWF wants to delay the choice of 
a site for 2006 by a year or two, allowing the candidates a year to 
produce revised bids. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
