<HEADLINE> Menifee Looking Good for Belmont </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Menifee, looking to duplicate stablemate Victory  
Gallop's success in the Belmont Stakes, had his final tune-up for 
Saturday's race, going 5-8 of a mile in a brisk 59 seconds at 
Belmont Park on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Trainer Elliott Walden, minus the crutches that supported him in  
the winner's circle last year, said he could not be happier with 
the progress of Menifee, who was second to Charismatic in both the 
Kentucky Derby and Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	``He worked very well this morning,'' said Walden, whose horses  
have finished second in four of the last five Triple Crown races. 
``He's a talented horse, and he's doing great. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing I can do about finishing second. I don't worry  
about things I can't control. Sure, I'd like to win Saturday, but 
all we can do is get him ready the best way we can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under exercise rider Shannon Ritter, Menifee galloped out 6  
furlongs in 1:11 2-5. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a little faster than I liked but he went easy,'' Walden  
said. ``It looks like he handles this racetrack pretty well.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ZITO LOOKS TO MAKE UP GROUND:* Like Elliott Walden, trainer  
Nick Zito has a history of second-place finishes, but in the 
Belmont Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Of Zito's eight Belmont starters, four finished second: Thirty  
Six Red (1990), Strike the Gold (1991), Go for Gin (1994) and Star 
Standard (1995). 
</P>
<P>
	``All I need is 5 lengths, not 20. Anyone know where I can get 5  
lengths?'' asked Zito, who Saturday will saddle Stephen Got Even 
and Adonis in the 1 1/2-mile Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Got Even was 14th in the Derby and fourth in the  
Preakness, about 7 lengths behind the winner Charismatic. Adonis 
finished 17th in the Derby and sixth in the Preakness, almost 11 
lengths behind Charismatic. 
</P>
<P>
	Zito won the Derby with Strike the Gold in 1991 and Go for Gin  
in 1994, and took the Preakness in 1996 with Louis Quatorze. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FILLIES AT BELMONT:* Silverbulletday will become just the 21st  
filly to run in the Belmont Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Two have won -- Ruthless, who won the first running in 1867 and  
Tanya, who won the first running of the Belmont at the new Belmont 
Park in 1905. 
</P>
<P>
	My Flag was the last filly to run in the Belmont, finishing  
third behind Editor's Note and Skip Away in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CHECK IS NOT IN THE MAIL:* Before the 1997 Belmont Stakes,  
officials at VISA had a $5 million bonus check already made out to 
Bob and Beverly Lewis, the owners of Silver Charm. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner Silver Charm finished  
second in the Belmont and was denied the Triple Crown and VISA's $5 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Charismatic, also owned by the Lewises, will be  
going for the Triple Crown and the $5 million bonus. This time, the 
check won't be made out before the fact. 
</P>
<P>
	``I asked them not to make it out before it's time,'' Bob Lewis  
said, ``It's like counting your chickens before they hatch.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FINISH LINES:* The Bill Mott-trained Vision and Verse had his  
final tuneup for the Belmont on Tuesday, breezing 5 furlongs in 
1:01 1/5 on the main track. ... Charismatic's jockey Chris Antley, 
who started an on-line investing newsletter before his return to 
riding this year, is scheduled to ring the opening bell at the New 
York Stock Exchange on Friday. Antley also gained the mount aboard 
'97 Derby and Preakness winner Silver Charm. ... Trainer Scotty 
Schulhofer said Lemon Drop Kid worked 5 furlongs in 1:01 2/5 
Monday, not 6 furlongs as clockers reported. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
