<HEADLINE> Confederate Flag Controversy in S.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- The new manual for South Carolina  
legislators has the Confederate flag in pictures on its cover, 
bringing about protests Tuesday from black lawmakers who want the 
book reprinted. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we send this out to our constituents, I mean they are going  
to really think we are crazy, have lost our minds,'' said state 
Sen. Robert Ford, a black Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1999 South Carolina Legislative Manual includes photos of  
the newly renovated House and Senate chambers. The U.S., state and 
Confederate flags are in the backgrounds of those pictures. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker David Wilkins, a Republican, said the photos were  
not meant to offend anyone and were merely used to show the 
interior of the Statehouse. Wilkins said the House would ``look at 
the cost'' of redoing the manual, but he was uncertain if it would 
be changed. 
</P>
<P>
	South Carolina is the only state to fly the Confederate battle  
flag, with its red background, blue cross and white stars, above 
its Statehouse dome and in its legislative chambers. Whether to 
lower remove them has been a recurring, divisive issue for 
lawmakers in a state where a third of the population is black. 
</P>
<P>
	Black legislators say the flag is a painful reminder of slavery.  
Those who support the flag say it symbolizes South Carolina's 
heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	Then-Gov. David Beasley's attempt to lower the flag two years  
ago was resoundingly rejected by his Republican colleagues. The 
issue came back to haunt Beasley last year as he lost his bid for 
re-election. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislators had avoided the issue this year, although the Senate  
passed a bill providing for the Martin Luther King Jr. holiday only 
after it also included recognition of Confederate Memorial Day. A 
House committee has refused to act on the bill. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 09:20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Fund Voices on the 'Net </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Any time you go prospecting for mutual-fund  
information on the Internet, don't limit yourself to the official 
World Wide Web sites operated by fund companies, regulators and 
trade groups. 
</P>
<P>
	New realms of data and commentary keep opening up at sites run  
by independent advisers who have no direct stake in the fund 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Befitting the Web's freewheeling reputation, these voices tend  
to be irascible, irreverent and occasionally downright wacky. You 
probably wouldn't want to use any of them as your sole source of 
guidance for setting up a prudent portfolio. 
</P>
<P>
	But at their best the independent sites entertain and amuse  
while they inform, cutting through the officialese you may 
encounter wherever sites operate under the constraints of good 
business manners and the securities statutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Example, from Errold F. Moody Jr., who bills himself as ``the  
Internet's financial consumer advocate'' at www.efmoody.com: 
``There never has been, nor is there currently, any reason for ever 
buying an investment or insurance at a bank.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moody argues that costs are usually higher, and the investment  
expertise of the staff lower, at banks than at more specialized 
financial services firms. ``If it was sold by someone without a 
true investment background,'' he says, ``you invariably are buying 
the wrong thing at the wrong time and at the wrong risk level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, you may or may not agree with that assertion. But even if  
you decide he is way off base, Moody's comments arm you with a 
measure of healthy skepticism for the next time your footsteps take 
you to a bank branch's securities and insurance desk. 
</P>
<P>
	At journalist Dian Vujovich's site, Dian's Fund Freebies  
(www.diansfundfreebies.com), the watchword is convenience. Ms. 
Vujovich has collected descriptive pamphlets, financial planning 
tools and other material offered free by many fund groups, and 
organized it all by topic -- for instance, mutual fund basics, 
retirement, taxes, and college planning. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, the site also offers a directory of hundreds  
of funds' toll-free telephone numbers and Web site addresses. 
</P>
<P>
	The site that has made the biggest splash lately is Fund Alarm  
(www.FundAlarm.com), run by Roy Weitz, a Los Angeles accountant 
with both business and law degrees (``I have never -- I swear -- 
practiced law,'' he avers). 
</P>
<P>
	Weitz rates funds on a scale of No-Alarms (good) to Three-Alarms  
(bad), offers a ``bulletin board'' where visitors can post 
questions or reply to queries, and provides links to other Web 
sites of interest to fund investors, all salted with his trenchant 
observations. 
</P>
<P>
	``See what all the excitement isn't about!'' he proclaims at a  
link to a new fund research service that is struggling to make room 
for itself in an already crowded field. 
</P>
<P>
	The prime attraction of FundAlarm is Weitz's monthly commentary  
on developments all around the world of funds. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, he threw jabs at laggard large-cap growth funds,  
``socially responsible'' funds, and funds run by big Wall Street 
firms. Of the latter, he said, ``funds sponsored by large brokerage 
firms have a bad reputation ... A review of this month's Fund Alarm 
database shows that the reputation is mostly deserved. 
</P>
<P>
	``On average, for every 10 times these funds are compared to  
their respective benchmarks, they underperform eight times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weitz also took a turn at dissecting the largest fund of them  
all, Fidelity Magellan: ``My, what big assets you have: Fidelity 
Magellan recently passed the $90 billion mark in net assets. Laid 
end to end, we have absolutely no idea how far 90 billion dollars 
would stretch ... But we have come up with some interesting ways to 
start a conversation, or stop one, depending on your social circle. 
</P>
<P>
	``--The technology holdings of Magellan are more than 3 1/2 times  
the size of the largest stand-alone technology fund, T. Rowe Price 
Science and Techology. 
</P>
<P>
	``--The utilities holdings of Magellan are 2 1/2 times the size of  
the largest stand-alone utility fund. 
</P>
<P>
	``--The single largest holding of Magellan (General Electric, at  
an estimated $3.6 billion) is by itself larger than all but 91 
domestic stock mutual funds.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 00:40:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Trial To Resume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As final testimony begins in the Microsoft  
Corp. antitrust trial, the software company is trying to convince a 
judge that federal intervention isn't necessary to keep the 
high-tech industry robust, while minimizing the ill effects of its 
past actions on competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	The company wants the judge to peer into the computer industry's  
future, where Microsoft officials believe their flagship Windows 
software will face unprecedented competition from a raft of 
fledgling technologies. 
</P>
<P>
	Government attorneys, however, are arguing that the judge should  
focus on Microsoft's aggressive behavior toward its rivals earlier 
this decade and on its dominance now. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial was resuming today after a 13-week recess, despite  
ongoing secret efforts to settle the landmark case. The verdict, 
expected as early as this fall, could dramatically change the way 
consumers buy software during a period when the industry is making 
huge technology strides and helping drive the nation's economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers from each side met unsuccessfully last spring to  
negotiate a truce and have met privately at least twice more since 
the trial began last fall, once in late February and again on March 
24. 
</P>
<P>
	But the lawyers remain far apart on some core issues after  
months of an acrimonious courtroom battle, such as how Microsoft 
can continue adding new technology to its Windows operating system 
without undercutting competitors that offer similar software 
products. 
</P>
<P>
	The government and Microsoft each have identified three  
witnesses who will testify during this phase of the trial, when the 
sides rebut earlier allegations. Franklin Fisher, an economist who 
testified previously for the government, was to take the stand 
again today. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's most important witness will be Garry Norris, an  
IBM Corp. manager who will describe pressure Microsoft allegedly 
exerted on IBM to sacrifice its rival OS/2 operating system 
software during the early 1990s. That software competed directly 
with Windows until its popularity waned in late 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	In a deposition last week, Norris claimed Microsoft told IBM it  
was charged a higher price for Windows in 1995 than other computer 
makers ``because you compete with us,'' and because IBM included 
what Microsoft called ``objectionable software'' from other rivals 
on its machines. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris also testified that major computer makers, such as Compaq  
Computer Corp., agreed not to sell OS/2 on their machines in 1993 
because Microsoft threatened ``to make it difficult for Compaq.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In what was considered a shortcoming in its legal case, the  
Justice Department was previously unable to persuade any of the 
nation's computer makers to testify at trial against Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft will focus its testimony in the coming weeks on  
encouraging U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson to consider 
future competition to Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the last courtroom testimony, America Online Inc.  
finalized its $10 billion purchase of Netscape Communications 
Corp., the Internet pioneer whose Web browser software competes 
with Microsoft's own Internet Explorer. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice lawyer David Boies has derided Microsoft's emphasis on  
the merger as a sideshow, but the judge remarked previously that 
the deal ``might be a very significant change in the playing 
field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft contends that AOL, as the world's largest Internet  
provider, could resuscitate Netscape's popularity as the most 
popular browser, and that other alliances would fuel the 
development of handheld, wireless devices that don't use Windows 
and could displace Microsoft's importance. 
</P>
<P>
	In a deposition last month with AOL Chairman Steve Case,  
Microsoft also suggested that future high-speed Internet 
connections for consumers threaten to reduce the industry's 
reliance on Windows. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 15:25:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Olympic Committee Reform Talks Begin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- Evolution, not revolution, was the  
theme as the International Olympic Committee opened debate Tuesday 
on ways to change in the wake of its biggest scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger was among several  
speakers who called on the IOC to be more open, accountable and 
representative. 
</P>
<P>
	And several athletes, including speedskating great Johan Olav  
Koss, challenged the IOC to give a bigger voice to those who 
actually compete in the games. 
</P>
<P>
	But the opening session of the IOC's new reform commission was  
also tempered by words of caution about moving too far too fast. 
</P>
<P>
	Delegates warned against radical change in a 105-year-old  
organization which has survived world wars, terrorism and boycotts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must not feel obliged to revolutionize the whole system, as  
some critics inspired by commercial and political interests have 
requested,'' Italian member Mario Pescante said. 
</P>
<P>
	Summing up the day's talks, IOC spokesman Franklin  
Servan-Schreiber said: ``We need to adapt and to update the 
structure of the IOC -- not destroy and rebuild it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday marked the first meeting of IOC 2000, an 80-member  
reform commission created in the wake of the vote-buying scandal 
stemming from Salt Lake's successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel, which continues talks Wednesday, is examining ways of  
reshaping the IOC's structure and the process for selecting Olympic 
host cities. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission is expected to consider changes to the way IOC  
members are selected, including introducing term limits and 
reducing the mandatory retirement age, which is now 80. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission, which is divided into three working groups, is  
to submit a preliminary report June 20 at the next IOC general 
assembly in Seoul, South Korea. Final recommendations are scheduled 
to be adopted at a special IOC session in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Kissinger -- one of 36 outside members on the commission -- said  
it was time for the IOC to ``adjust to new realities'' and be more 
open and responsive. 
</P>
<P>
	Kissinger suggested the IOC widen its membership to include  
outside groups on a rotating basis. He said the committee's 
meetings should be open ``as far as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The strongest words came from Koss, winner of three gold medals  
at the 1994 Lillehammer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is the IOC determined to remain a private club or open to  
transparency and accountability?'' Koss said. ``If not, the IOC 
will remain the same, which will ensure further corruption and 
abuse of power.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``How can we change the soul of the IOC back to where it was  
supposed to be?'' he said. ``What we have seen in the last eight 
months is the IOC has not taken its responsibility. ... The chosen 
men and women of the IOC have not been the right role models.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a member of the democratically elected IOC athletes'  
commission, Koss proposed that 10 more members be elected to the 
panel and that all 20 athletes be appointed to the IOC itself. He 
suggested that two athletes serve on the decision-making IOC 
executive board. 
</P>
<P>
	``Will the IOC, who claim that the Olympics are for the  
athletes, support the athletes, empower the athletes, give them 
full status in the Olympic family?'' Koss said. ``If it's not about 
the athletes, then what is it about?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Ctvrtlik, who played on three U.S. Olympic volleyball teams,  
said athletes ``do have a voice, but it's a small voice. If we are 
to have a role as a third pillar in the Olympic movement, we have a 
long way to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hassiba Boulmerka, the Algerian runner who won the 1,500-meter  
gold medal at the 1992 Barcelona Games, said the IOC must change 
from being an ``institution of elderly men.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The athletes ``are the most legitimate people in the IOC,'' she  
said. ``We were elected. We should have the most power.' 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Ueberroth, chief organizer of the 1984 Los Angeles Games,  
urged the IOC to curb the size of the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bigger is not better,'' he said. ``If the games get any  
bigger, no city or country will be able to do it well. There must 
be restraint of growth or the games will fail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ueberroth said the IOC should ensure that money flows to those  
who really need it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems to me the Olympic movement is at the top of the  
mountain of sport,'' he said. ``At the next level are sponsors and 
officials. Toward the bottom are the athletes and young people. Why 
not become a service organization serving those people and turn the 
mountain upside down?'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Macaloon, an Olympic scholar at the University of Chicago,  
said the IOC faced a moral crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``People hope the reforms produce an IOC that is the servant of  
the Olympic movement and less an IOC that sometimes mistakes itself 
for the Olympic movement,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other developments:  
</P>
<P>
	--Dick Ebersol, the president of NBC Sports and an IOC 2000  
member, said American athletes were suffering from ``cynical ... 
self-serving'' attacks on the IOC by John Hancock insurance 
president David D'Alessandro. 
</P>
<P>
	D'Alessandro, whose company is a top-level Olympic sponsor, said  
Ebersol was concerned that the scandal would devalue his network's 
$3.5 billion Olympics rights package. 
</P>
<P>
	--Australian IOC member Phil Coles said he would clear his name  
when he appears Thursday before a special panel investigating 
charges of ethical misconduct. Coles is accused of abusing his 
position, most recently by passing memos and evaluations of other 
IOC members to Salt Lake's bid team. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 15:25:17 </DATE_TIME>
