<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 13:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Probes Iraq Businessman's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Va. (AP) -- Police have asked the FBI to look into  
the international connections of an Iraqi-American with business 
dealings in Iraq who was murdered along with his wife and son. 
</P>
<P>
	Police alerted by an anonymous call on Friday found the bodies  
of Fuad Khazi Taima, 63; his wife, Dorothy Mae, 54; and son, Leith, 
16, in their home in McLean, a Washington suburb. All had died of 
gunshots to the upper body. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no sign of forced entry and it was not a  
murder-suicide or robbery, said Fairfax County Police spokeswoman 
Katie Hughes. 
</P>
<P>
	Taima traveled frequently to Iraq, and the FBI was called in  
because of his international dealings, Ms. Hughes said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It appears they were targeted,'' she said. ``We're not  
alluding to who would have targeted them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	FBI spokeswoman Susan Lloyd said federal agents were ``checking  
various intelligence sources,'' but she refused to elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither police nor the FBI would cite any motive for the  
killings, and neither would comment on news reports that they were 
looking into whether the crime involved either the Iraqi government 
or its opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	Taima was prominent in the Iraqi-American community as founder  
of the American-Iraqi Foundation, which aimed at improving 
U.S.-Iraqi relations during the 1980-1988 Iran-Iraq War. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Post reported Tuesday that Taima had told  
colleagues he recently visited Iraq and landed a large business 
deal. Details of the reported deal were not immediately known. The 
Post said he had worked as a consultant in oil and high technology 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's certainly possible that he was engaged in some type of  
commercial deal with the Iraqi government that went bad,'' said 
Michael Hudson, a Georgetown University professor with the Center 
for Contemporary Arab Studies. 
</P>
<P>
	Ahmed Chalabi, the Washington representative of the opposition  
Iraqi National Congress, would not speculate on who killed Taima 
but said the murders fit the pattern of killings carried out by 
Iraqi government agents. 
</P>
<P>
	There usually is no sign of forced entry or a struggle because  
someone familiar to a victim usually is sent in first, Chalabi 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was available to comment on the case Tuesday at the Iraqi  
Mission to the United Nations, a secretary said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police believe the three may have been killed May 26, when  
neighbors recalled hearing noises that could have been gunshots. 
</P>
<P>
	Taima's wife was an English teacher and their son a sophomore at  
McLean High School. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 15:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Funeral Co. Files Chapter 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- The Loewen Group Inc., which ran up huge  
debts in expanding its funeral business in the United States, on 
Tuesday sought Bankruptcy Court protection from creditors for 
itself and about 870 of its U.S. subsidiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian-based funeral services company applied to  
reorganize its debts under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, 
and under Canadian law. 
</P>
<P>
	Although based in Vancouver, British Columbia, the company  
derives 90 percent of its revenue from U.S. operations. The company 
operates in the United States under the name Loewen Group 
International Inc. Loewen's United Kingdom subsidiaries, which 
generate less than 1 percent of its revenues, were excluded from 
the filings. 
</P>
<P>
	John S. Lacey, the chairman of Loewen, said the company will  
honor all of its outstanding contracts for prepaid funeral services 
at 1,100 funeral homes and 400 cemeteries in the United States and 
Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our clients should ... be assured that monies held in trust  
accounts for pre-need contracts are secure and protected by state 
and provincial regulations,'' Lacey said in a statement. ``It is 
the company's intent to continue operations without interruption,'' 
Lacey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Loewen said its American subsidiaries have a commitment of $200  
million from First Union National Bank to cover trade and employee 
obligations and other cash needs during the court-supervised 
attempt to restructure its debt. 
</P>
<P>
	It petitioned the U.S. court Tuesday to receive $23 million of  
those funds immediately. Loewen said its Canadian operations ``have 
sufficient liquidity to fund daily operations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Loewen has long been struggling to make payments on more than $2  
billion of debt that it took on to finance aggressive acquisition 
of cemetery space in the United States. Tuesday's action came as a 
$17 million interest payment came due. 
</P>
<P>
	The bankruptcy filing buys the company time to return to its  
focus as a funeral service company with some ancillary cemetery 
operations, Lacey said. The company also said it has suspended any 
new acquisitions. 
</P>
<P>
	At a hearing Tuesday before Chief Judge Joseph Farnan of the  
U.S. District Court in Wilmington, Bradley Stam, senior vice 
president in the law department of Loewen, said the company does 
not have any immediate plans to lay off any of its staff of 13,000 
but would review some of its operations for potential layoffs in 
the future. 
</P>
<P>
	According to papers filed with the court, Loewen earned $190  
million in 1998 but paid out $187 million of that in interest on 
long-term debt incurred by previous management. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will emerge sooner rather than later'' from bankruptcy,  
said Richard Cieri, another lawyer for Loewen. 
</P>
<P>
	In papers filed with the court, the U.S. operating company  
listed assets of $4.15 billion and liabilities of $3.25 billion. 
The company had $2.1 billion of debt outstanding, including $1.2 
billion of publicly traded high-yield debt maturing from 2001 
through 2008. 
</P>
<P>
	After Judge Farnan concludes preliminary hearings, the case will  
be assigned to the Chief Judge Peter Walsh of the Bankruptcy Court 
in Wilmington, where Loewen's U.S. operations are incorporated. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 10:23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Fighting Spills Into Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MORINI, Albania (AP) -- Fighting spilled across the Kosovo  
frontier into Albania today and NATO planes apparently bombed 
government bunkers by mistake. 
</P>
<P>
	Villagers fled Serb shelling and journalists joined the exodus  
after jets attacked as they were filming bomb damage. 
</P>
<P>
	No casualties were reported. There was no official confirmation  
from NATO of the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO jets continued their attacks against Serb border positions  
through much of the night following intense airstrikes and clashes 
Monday between Serb forces and Kosovo Liberation Army guerrillas. 
</P>
<P>
	An Albanian army officer at the Morini border crossing said NATO  
warplanes destroyed four defensive bunkers several hundred yards 
inside Albanian territory. 
</P>
<P>
	As Western journalists and television crews were filming bomb  
damage this afternoon, jets appeared overhead and launched another 
attack. As the journalists sped deeper into Albania, a jet appeared 
to follow them, dropping bombs nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe said at  
least seven bombs were dropped -- some falling two miles inside 
Albania. The OSCE did not identify the planes as NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	The OSCE also said Serb gunners shelled Albanian artillery  
positions and bunkers along the border overnight, damaging the 
Morini police station. 
</P>
<P>
	In wake of a night of shelling, many Albanian villagers and  
refugees took to the road, heading for Kukes, 12 miles to the 
southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the refugees have left,'' said Seeim Tusha, 62, a shepherd  
from the hamlet of Durak, the closest Albanian settlement to the 
frontier. ``I was born here and I will die in this place,'' Tusha 
said, tending sheep on a rocky hillside overlooking the border 
checkpoint. 
</P>
<P>
	KLA guerrillas have been trying to move deeper into Kosovo  
territory in an apparent effort to open up a supply corridor and 
capture the Serb border checkpoint at Morini. 
</P>
<P>
	Serb artillery and mortars have been pounding the guerrillas,  
while NATO warplanes are flying daily sorties in support of the 
pro-independence KLA. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 10:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Three Strikes Law' Open for Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Tragedy bound two fathers -- at least for a  
while -- in their fight for one of the nation's most influential 
tough-on-crime laws. The machinery of the media and the power of 
politicians kicked it up a notch. But how well did voters really 
understand ``three strikes,'' and is the popular law working? 
</P>
<P>
	``The Legacy: Murder &AMP; Media, Politics &AMP; Prisons,'' from  
filmmaker Michael J. Moore, attempts to answer those questions. The 
documentary airs Tuesday as part of ``P.O.V.,'' the PBS showcase 
for independent nonfiction films. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1 1/2-hour film tells the story of parents and crime victims  
Mike Reynolds and Marc Klaas and how tragedy, politicking and 
public outrage worked together to enact the state's three-strikes 
sentencing law for repeat felons. 
</P>
<P>
	It had been touted as a way of locking up violent repeat felons.  
But by June 1998, more than one in four California inmates had been 
sentenced under three strikes and more than 80 percent of those 
were sentenced for nonviolent offenses, Moore said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Normally with legislation, you have a whole system of checks  
and balances. ... All of that gets factored into it. A Fresno 
photographer (Reynolds) made this law,'' Moore said in an interview 
at a showing of his film in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	Reynolds' campaign was motivated by personal tragedy. His  
18-year-old daughter, Kimber, was shot and killed in 1992 when she 
refused to give a thief her purse. Klaas' 12-year-old daughter, 
Polly, was kidnapped from her home in 1993, prompting public 
outrage and one of the state's most extensive crusades for a 
missing child. She was later found murdered. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspects in both cases were previously convicted felons.  
</P>
<P>
	``There was no sleep. There was no food. There was nothing but  
anger at the person that had committed the crime against Polly and 
the system that had allowed him to be in a position to do something 
like that. And that was what had to be corrected,'' Klaas said in 
the film. ``And we were going to use anger to correct it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just three weeks after his daughter was killed, Reynolds said,  
he gathered an informal group of judges, attorneys and law 
enforcement officials for a barbecue in his backyard to talk about 
how one law could ``solve the problem of the re-release of the same 
criminals over and over again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Why was this man out on parole committing more crime?''  
Reynolds asks in the film. ``The state's responsibility is what 
we're talking about here. They're the one unindicted perpetrator in 
my daughter's murder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Out of this meeting grew the California three strikes  
initiative, which doubles the minimum sentence for two-time felons 
and mandates sentences of 25 years to life for three-time 
offenders, he says. 
</P>
<P>
	About four months later, just days after Richard Allen Davis was  
arrested and subsequently charged in Polly's murder, Klaas learned 
of the initiative. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seemed like a movement that I should be involved in, so we  
climbed on board three strikes,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Polly quickly became the poster child for the measure,  
galvanizing public support and offering people an outlet for their 
rage. Petitions were signed; rallies were held. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, Moore set himself up at the polls and talked to about  
100 people after they voted on the initiative. He says he was 
appalled at how little they knew about three strikes, which they 
all had supported. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just so sinister how policy is made and how it's  
promoted,'' Moore said. ``We citizens feel like we're making a 
difference, but really it's money, media ... There's just no debate 
about policy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Corrections Department told lawmakers back in 1994, a few  
days before they approved three strikes, that two-thirds of the 
people affected by the law would be nonviolent offenders. 
</P>
<P>
	But the wheels already were in motion and politicians were  
piggybacking on the rhetoric. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, Republican Assemblyman Bill Jones announced his  
candidacy for secretary of state and his support for three strikes. 
He brought the bill to lawmakers with the financial support of the 
Republican Party, the state's prison guard association and the 
National Rifle Association, among others. Less than two months 
later, the bill was signed into law by then-Gov. Pete Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
	Klaas by then had withdrawn his support of the measure, saying  
it did not restrict itself to violent felons. Burglary was a felony 
in California and Klaas didn't think it was right to send someone 
to prison for life on a burglary conviction. Reynolds countered 
that the man who kidnapped Polly was a robber before he murdered 
Polly. 
</P>
<P>
	``If three strikes had been law my daughter and his daughter  
would be alive today,'' Reynolds said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Polly's grandfather, Joe Klaas, said: ``You don't have to  
put half the population of the state in prison to get at people 
like (Polly's killer) Davis, all you've got to do is get at people 
like Davis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marc Klaas said he understands Reynolds, because both are driven  
by the same thing: ``Our daughters were murdered by people that 
shouldn't have been out there to murder children.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	BURIED TREASURE: The U.S.-Cuban political estrangement left the  
Caribbean island's deep undersea world largely unexplored. In 1997, 
for the first time since Cuba's 1959 revolution, an American 
research vessel was allowed into Cuban waters. The expedition and 
its discoveries -- including seven new species of fish and 53 
species new to the island -- is detailed in ``Forbidden Depths,'' 9 
p.m. EDT Sunday, June 6, on Discovery Channel. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0170 </DOCNO>
