<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Feds Study Violence in Entertainment  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is urging the movie industry  
and video-game makers to ``show some restraint'' in using bloody 
images to market their products. Clinton announced today that the 
government will investigate marketing practices of the 
entertainment industry. Clinton read from a series of ads for video 
games which touted their gory realism. Clinton said Americans 
``cannot be surprised'' when impressionable kids see such material, 
and get confused about the difference between violent fantasy and 
reality. The $1 million joint study by the Federal Trade Commission 
and Justice Department is expected to take up to 18 months. 

</P>
<P>
	Students Return to Columbine High  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Students returned to Columbine High  
School today to retrieve their belongings for the first time since 
a deadly shooting spree, and crews began cleaning up and repairing 
the damage from the April 20 rampage. Students left backpacks and 
other things as they ran from the building or hid in classrooms 
when Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold opened fire. Fifteen people, 
including the shooters, died in the attack. The students were 
barred from some areas -- including the library, where most of the 
victims were found. 

</P>
<P>
	Va. Family's Murder Called Targeted  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The FBI and area police are investigating the  
``targeted'' killing of an Iraqi-American businessman, his school 
teacher wife and their 16-year-old son. A police spokeswoman said 
the shooting appeared to be ``a targeted incident and does not 
appear to be a random incident.'' Fuad Khazi Taima; his wife, 
Dorothy Mae Taima, and their son, Leith Fuad, all died of gunshot 
wounds, police said. Taimi has been prominent in the Iraqi-American 
community as founder of the American-Iraqi Foundation to help 
improve U.S.-Iraqi relations during the 1980-1988 Iran-Iraq War. 

</P>
<P>
	Kennedys Urged JFK Casket Be Sunk  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Newly released documents show that the Kennedy  
family insisted that the polished bronze casket used to carry 
President Kennedy's body from Dallas to Washington be dumped into 
the ocean. Kennedy was buried at Arlington National Cemetery in a 
mahogany coffin after he was assassinated on Nov. 22, 1963. The 
660-pound coffin was paid for by the government but was considered 
property of the family. It was dropped into 9,000 feet of water 
beyond the continental shelf, a site chosen because it was away 
from regularly traveled air and shipping lines and would not be 
disturbed by trawling and other sea-bottom activities, the 
documents said. 

</P>
<P>
	United Way Chief's Sentence Upheld  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today let stand the  
seven-year prison sentence former United Way president William 
Aramony received for stealing money from the nation's largest 
charity. The justices rejected an appeal in which Aramony argued 
that his prison term exceeds federal guidelines. Aramony was 
convicted in 1995 of defrauding the charity out of about $600,000. 
He was found guilty of fraud, tax and conspiracy charges. Aramony 
was forced to resign in 1992 after 22 years with the charity. 

</P>
<P>
	Pirates Attack Mexican Resort Ferry  
</P>
<P>
	CANCUN, Mexico (AP) -- A half-dozen hooded pirates brandishing  
assault rifles robbed passengers of money and valuables last night 
aboard a ferry returning from the resort island of Cozumel. The 
bandits also threw two security guards overboard and beat a crew 
member before speeding off in another boat, local officials said. 
One of the security guards has been rescued, but the other is still 
missing. Foreign tourists make up most of the ferry passengers on 
the 10-mile route between Cozumel and Playa del Carmen, 36 miles to 
the south. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 102  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 102.48 to 10,457.26. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,761-1,067. The Nasdaq was down 41.29 to 
2,429.23. 

</P>
<P>
	Kissinger Calls for IOC Reforms  
</P>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- Henry Kissinger urged the IOC today  
to be more open and accountable as it tries to recover from the 
worst crisis in Olympic history. Kissinger is one of 36 outside 
members on the 80-member IOC 2000 commission, which was formed in 
the wake of the vote-buying scandal stemming from Salt Lake's 
successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games. The reform panel is 
meeting today and tomorrow to begin examining ways of overhauling 
the IOC's structure and the process for selecting Olympic host 
cities. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
