<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 16:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Member Looks To Clear Name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- Australian IOC member Phil Coles  
said Tuesday he would clear his name when he appears before a 
special panel investigating charges of ethical misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles said it was a ``good sign'' he had been asked to appear  
before the three-member panel on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I've got a lot to say, a lot to present,'' Coles said.  
``I've got every confidence in that special commission, they are 
very capable people. I wanted to come. I couldn't see the meeting 
taking place without me being here to present my information.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coles said he doesn't believe the panel will recommend his  
expulsion from the International Olympic Committee when it reports 
its findings to the executive board at its next meeting June 16 in 
Seoul, South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that will happen but we'll just play that as it  
comes,'' Coles said. ``But I really don't believe that will 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	IOC vice presidents Keba Mbaye and Anita DeFrantz and executive  
board member Marc Hodler could recommend that the case be dropped 
or that Coles be expelled. Any expulsion would have to go to the 
full IOC assembly for approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has already received a severe warning from the IOC for  
accepting lavish travel and other incentives from Salt Lake 
bidders, and is under investigation for further allegations of 
abusing his Olympic positions. 
</P>
<P>
	His ex-wife told the IOC that the couple received jewelry valued  
at $6,000 from a businessman associated with the Athens bid for the 
1996 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Most recently, the Australian has been accused of compiling  
secret dossiers on IOC members for Sydney's successful 2000 bid. 
Those files were also passed on to Salt Lake bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles again denied any wrongdoing.  
</P>
<P>
	``They certainly have attacked me without any consultation or  
any knowledge of where it all came from but we'll have the 
opportunity,'' he said. ``But it was terribly embarrassing to have 
private memo notes published.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The continued controversy has taken its toll on Coles, who was  
subdued and cautious throughout a news conference hours after his 
arrival from Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been an absolute nightmare,'' Coles said. ``I've never  
seen such vilification. But I'm confident there are brighter 
horizons ahead. ... I'm hoping this will be the finish of it 
here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
