<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 14:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybeans Off on Weather News / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices retreated  
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid near-ideal growing 
conditions for spring crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters are predicting warm weather and scattered showers  
across Midwest growing regions this week. That should prove ideal 
for early growth of corn and spring wheat crops, where farmers were 
expected to have completed planting in the past week. Market 
participants expected the government this week would report about 
75 percent of soybean crops have been planted. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors are worried that record soybean acreage and large corn  
acreage could lead to bumper fall harvests, at a time when weaker 
than normal world demand has lead to ample inventory buildups. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures also were pressured by upcoming active harvesting  
of the winter wheat crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 1/2 cent to $2.51 3/4 a bushel; July  
corn fell 3 1/4 cents to $2.16 1/4 a bushel; July oats fell 1 1/4 cents to 
$1.21 3/4 a bushel; July soybeans fell 3 3/4 cents to $4.58 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle futures were mixed, while feeder cattle futures  
advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Pork futures 
retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .25 cent to 64.50 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .35 cent to 75.87 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell 1.48 cents to 51.47 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell .67 
cent to 52.70 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 12:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cathay Pilots Threaten Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- As a sickout by Cathay Pacific Airways pilots  
entered its fifth day and grounded about a third of the carrier's 
flights Tuesday, the air crew union intensified the dispute by 
threatening to strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Responding to the company's plans to fire pilots who don't  
accept proposed salary cuts, the Hong Kong Aircrew Officers 
Association decided to call a strike vote if anyone loses his job, 
said John Findlay, the union's secretary general. 
</P>
<P>
	Findlay said the measure was supported by more than 700 of the  
850 union members who voted. Those numbers suggested a strike vote 
could pass, Findlay told a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay managers declined to say Tuesday night what they would do  
if pilots walk off the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the level of disruption escalates, we will respond  
accordingly,'' the company's director of corporate development, 
Tony Tyler, told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The union also urged management to enter into arbitration. Tyler  
said Cathay bosses were open to the idea, but he later added that 
the sides were too far apart to simply ``split the difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong-based Cathay canceled 37 of 110 scheduled flights  
Tuesday, halting its services throughout Asia and into Europe and 
North America, company spokeswoman Katherine Wang said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay said it would transfer passengers to other flights,  
including 10 chartered services it had hired from other airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	``The situation is under control,'' Tyler said. ``The  
overwhelming majority of our passengers are getting to their 
destinations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay has canceled a total of 140 flights, affecting more than  
16,000 passengers, since pilots began calling in sick en masse on 
Friday, claiming they are under too much stress because of layoff 
threats. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides have been locked in the dispute since Cathay asked  
senior pilots in March to take an 8 percent pay cut in exchange for 
stock options. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Cathay abruptly pulled out of nine weeks of talks and  
gave the pilots a June 11 deadline to decide whether to accept a 
revised pay offer, including a smaller pay cut and better stock 
options, resign or be fired. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay said the pilots' counter offer, which includes annual pay  
increases after two years of cuts and a yearlong pay freeze, was 
unacceptable. The company has refused to reopen talks unless the 
pilots give up demands for pay rises. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots' union said it has not organized the sickout, noting  
that Hong Kong law allows pilots to stay home due to stress. 
Neither side would say how many pilots have called in sick. 
</P>
<P>
	The impasse is hurting Hong Kong's tourism industry and has  
sparked calls for the government to step in, but the territory's 
secretary for education and manpower, Joseph Wong, said there were 
no immediate plans for intervention. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay operates nearly a third of all flights in and out of Hong  
Kong. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 15:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lopez Seeks Women's U.S. Open Title  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST POINT, Miss. (AP) -- Dan Marino has never won a Super Bowl.  
Greg Norman has never worn a green jacket. John Stockton and Karl 
Malone may end their careers without an NBA title. Roger Clemens 
has yet to pitch for a World Series winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Nancy Lopez knows the feeling.  
</P>
<P>
	Considering all that she has meant to her sport, perhaps no  
other athlete deserves to fill a glaring void in an otherwise 
illustrious career. 
</P>
<P>
	For Lopez, already a member of the Hall of Fame with 48  
victories and three major championships, what might be her last 
chance starts Thursday in the U.S. Women's Open at a course she 
calls home. 
</P>
<P>
	She played the first official round at Old Waverly Golf Club and  
returns once a year for corporate outings. She feels positive vibes 
just driving down the two-lane road and past the Southern 
plantation-style clubhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to look at it as if this is my best opportunity, the  
best one I've ever had,'' Lopez said Tuesday. ``It's there for me 
to take. If it's going to happen, this is the time for it to 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It may be her last chance because of the black brace wrapped  
snugly around her left knee. Lopez first started feeling the pain 
of arthritis about three months ago, when her legs ached at night 
and she had trouble walking in the morning. 
</P>
<P>
	It may be her last chance because her attitude has never been  
better. Lopez was among those who waved white flags of surrender 
last year at Blackwolf Run, a course she despised but was too 
gracious to say so until months later. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel really good this week,'' Lopez said after an 18-hole  
practice round, followed by a 30 minutes' rest. ``My confidence 
level is very high. I'm at a place where I feel comfortable. I love 
the golf course, and I feel it likes me a little bit, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The question is whether Old Waverly loves Lopez enough to reward  
her with a U.S. Open victory. 
</P>
<P>
	At 42, Lopez is trying to juggle the grind of the LPGA tour with  
the joy of spending time with her three daughters. She always finds 
enough daylight to sweat under the hot Georgia sun, trying to 
recapture that magic putting stroke and dreaming about finally 
winning a U.S. Open. 
</P>
<P>
	More often than not, she thinks about the ones that got away.  
</P>
<P>
	Lopez was 18 years old, not even a freshman at the University of  
Tulsa, when she matched strokes with her idol, JoAnne Carner, and 
finished second behind Sandra Palmer in the 1975 Women's Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years later, before she even had her LPGA tour card, Lopez  
made a spirited run at three-time Open champion Hollis Stacy but 
again settled for second. 
</P>
<P>
	Surely, it was just a matter of time.  
</P>
<P>
	``I probably thought that I would have a lot of opportunities to  
win the Open, and that hopefully I would win a few,'' Lopez said. 
</P>
<P>
	She had a chance in 1985 when she led after 36 holes and was in  
the final group at Baltusrol in 1985 until a 77 in the final round 
dropped her into a tie for fourth. In 1989, she closed with a 68 
but came up two strokes short and was runner-up again. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's got to be some way to win an Open,'' she said. ``You  
almost think there's a way to figure it out, and there's not. But I 
keep thinking that I can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She quit believing for a while. Lopez wanted to win the Open so  
badly that she put too much pressure on herself and never got the 
right results. She had only one top-10 finish over the next seven 
years, but got new life at Pumpkin Ridge in Oregon in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Just like the first time she set foot on Old Waverly, Lopez fell  
in love with Pumpkin Ridge. She shot in the 60s all four rounds, 
the only player in the 53-year history of the Women's Open to do 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	And even that wasn't enough. Her 20-foot birdie putt on the 72nd  
hold to force a playoff with Alison Nicholas stopped an inch from 
the heart of the cup. Lopez was in tears, but came away believing 
she wasn't done quite yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was like a rebirth,'' she said. ``I was going to have a  
chance to win another Open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This may be her last chance.  
</P>
<P>
	Imagine Marino, facing fourth-and-goal from the 5 and needing a  
touchdown to win the Super Bowl. Or Stockton and Malone, setting up 
the pick-and-roll with the score tied in the final seconds of Game 
7 in the NBA Finals. Or Norman, standing over a 20-foot putt on the 
18th green at Augusta National on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Imagine Lopez, flashing her unforgettable smile and shedding the  
tears of an Open champion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know my game is there,'' she said. ``I know it can win.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 15:53:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Opposition Courts S.African Whites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Relegated to a minor role in  
South Africa's election, white voters have been wooed by a 
half-dozen opposition groups, including a former anti-apartheid 
party now making headway with calls to reinstate the death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	No single party has emerged as the clear-cut standard bearer for  
the 4.5 million whites who comprise 11 percent of South Africa's 
population. 
</P>
<P>
	But polls indicate the largest bloc of white votes in the  
election Wednesday is likely to go to the Democratic Party, formed 
a decade ago as a coalition of anti-apartheid whites but now 
appealing to conservatives with calls for get-tough policies on 
crime. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic Party is a direct descendent of the Progressive  
Federal Party, which fought to ease segregation and extend 
political rights to blacks during the heyday of apartheid. Now, 
with the black-led African National Congress in power and favored 
to win re-election, the Democratic Party has adopted the slogan 
``Fight Back'' and transformed itself into a vehemently anti-ANC 
party. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ANC wants to colonize every possible nook and cranny of  
our society,'' said the Democratic Party's pugnacious leader, Tony 
Leon. ``Its appetite is bottomless.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic Party's gains in the polls have come largely at  
the expense of the New National Party, the current version of the 
National Party that ruled during more than four decades of 
apartheid. 
</P>
<P>
	For most of its reign, the National Party was supported loyally  
by most of the country's 3 million Afrikaners, the mainly 
Dutch-descended whites who began settling in South Africa in the 
1600s. 
</P>
<P>
	Hard-line Afrikaners began deserting the National Party during  
the 1980s, when the government tried to moderate the apartheid 
system. Pollsters say a new wave of Afrikaner defections is 
occurring as the New National Party woos mixed-race voters while 
the Democratic Party hammers away with anti-ANC messages. 
</P>
<P>
	The result has been an ironic reversal of the old roles of the  
two white-led parties, with the New National Party depicting itself 
as multiracial and accusing the Democratic Party of catering to 
white fear. 
</P>
<P>
	``The isolationist and adversarial approach now offered by  
parties such as the Democratic Party is counterproductive,'' New 
National Party leader Marthinus van Schalkwyk said Tuesday. ``The 
fueling of racial antagonism ... belongs to the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the far-right of the political spectrum, a couple of  
hard-line, Afrikaner-led parties are seeking votes from whites 
still tempted by talk of a white homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	Other whites are being wooed by the United Democratic Movement,  
which has a white and black as its co-leaders, and by the small 
Federal Alliance, led by the former czar of South Africa's rugby 
federation. 
</P>
<P>
	The ANC, confident of re-election, has been able to view the  
struggle among the white parties with a degree of condescension. 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson Mandela, who is stepping down as president, has dismissed  
the entire batch as ``Mickey Mouse parties'' and urged whites to 
join the majority by supporting the ANC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
