<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European, Asian Markets Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	European stock markets ended slightly higher in thin volume  
Monday, as national holidays in the United States and England left 
trading quiet. In Asia, stocks rose in Hong Kong and Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	In Germany, shares of Deutsche Telekom gained 5.8 percent as the  
company continued to benefit from its increased weighting on the 
blue-chip DAX stock index to 13 percent from about 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Paris-listed retailer Pinault Printemps Redoute rose 4.2 percent  
following a bullish interview with PPR's chief executive in The 
Wall Street Journal Europe Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in French drinks group Pernod Ricard also bubbled higher,  
gaining 4.2 percent on unconfirmed reports suggesting the company 
is planning a bid for Allied Domecq's spirits business. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index closed down 0.1 percent. The Paris  
CAC 40 index ended 0.8 percent higher, Milan's MIBtel index rose 
0.6 percent, and Madrid's IBEX-35 index was up 0.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Markets in London and Athens were closed for holidays.  
</P>
<P>
	On Asian markets, shares rose in Tokyo and Hong Kong but slumped  
in Taipei. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's Nikkei Stock Average gained 138.97 points to close at  
16,111.65, but trading remained quiet due to the holidays on other 
major markets. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, the Hang Seng Index rose 87.87 points to  
12,147.12. But shares of Cathay Pacific Airways slumped 10 percent 
because of a pay dispute between the airline and its pilots that 
caused many flights to be canceled. 
</P>
<P>
	In Taiwan, share prices closed sharply lower in the absence of  
market-boosting news. The Taipei market's main Weighted Stock Price 
Index fell 103.13 points, or 1.4 percent, to 7,316.57. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian share prices closed higher, with a sharp rise in  
banking stocks countering a fall in the resources sector to see the 
broader market push up into positive territory. The All Ordinaries 
Index rose or 0.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Manila's Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 1.2 percent; in  
Seoul, the Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose or 0.5 percent 
and Malaysia's Composite Index fell 0.7 percent. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
