<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Merrill Lynch To Offer Online Trades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the nation's largest stock  
brokerage, shook the securities industry Tuesday by announcing it 
will let customers trade stocks over the Internet for $29.95 a pop. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision marks a grudging and dramatic change for Merrill  
Lynch, which has spent decades forging a nationwide network of 
14,000 brokers who give investment advice and who earn commissions 
of hundreds of dollars for placing stock trades. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill debated for months whether online trading would  
undermine its traditional brokerage services. The firm was finally 
swayed by the rapid loss of business to a growing number of online 
brokers such as Charles Schwab, ETrade and Ameritrade. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is probably the most important decision we have made as  
an organization since the mid-1970s,'' said David Komansky, 
Merrill's chairman and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch's Internet strategy, which competitors are likely  
to follow, reflects the revolutionary impact of the Internet on 
financial services. With more than 7 million Americans trading 
online, Merrill and others can no longer ignore the sea change. 
Online trades now account for between 30 percent and 35 percent of 
all individual trades. 
</P>
<P>
	``It appeared foolish for us to ignore that part of the  
market,'' Komansky said. ``So we decided to attack it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's a big change from a year ago when Merrill's brokerage  
chief John Steffens was badmouthing online trading big-time. 
</P>
<P>
	``The do-it-yourself model of investing, centered on Internet  
trading, should be regarded as a serious threat to Americans' 
financial lives,'' he told an audience at the PC Expo conference in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	As Merrill embarks on its new strategy, it faces big risks.  
</P>
<P>
	Some of Merrill's brokers stand to lose up to 18 percent of  
their pay as customers bypass their services and trade via the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill is also charging more than many rivals, some of whom  
offer trades for as little as $5. And, Merrill is setting another 
high bar: a minimum $20,000 to open an account. Finally, by waiting 
until December to launch the new service, competitors will have 
time to respond with their own products. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, Merrill is preparing for battle.  
</P>
<P>
	Executives gave their Internet strategy the code name  
``Rubicon,'' the river Julius Caesar crossed on his way to take 
Rome. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Merrill's clear targets: Charles Schwab, which caters to  
a similar upper-middle-class clientele and also charges $29.95 for 
online trades. Shares of Charles Schwab dropped $6 to $99.50 
Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not concerned,'' said Charles Schwab, chairman and chief  
executive of the San Francisco-based brokerage. ``What they're 
introducing is the affirmation of what we've been talking about a 
long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other online brokers also got pounded: Shares of ETrade fell  
$5.18 3/4 to $39.31 1/4 on the Nasdaq Stock Market, while Ameritrade 
dipped $9.93 3/4 to $79.75, also on Nasdaq. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill's own stock dropped $8.75, or 10 percent, to $75.25 on  
the NYSE, though Komansky blamed it on the recent run up in 
Merrill's stock price and concerns in the market about inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	A second part of Merrill's Internet strategy involves more  
affluent investors. They will be offered an account with free, 
unlimited trading, either with a broker, online or over the phone, 
in return for an annual fee ranging from 0.02 percent to 1 percent 
of assets. As assets grow, the rate falls, but the minimum fee is 
$1,500. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to free research reports offered to all of its  
online customers, Merrill will offer its premium account holders 
financial planning, free ATM withdrawals and a Visa Signature 
credit card, which offers a wide-ranging reward program. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street's traditional brokerage firms will have to match  
Merrill. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody else sure as heck better follow suit or they're  
going to run the risk of not keeping up with their customers,'' 
said Scott Birnbaum, head of financial services for Mercer 
Management Consulting Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	One full-service brokerage firm is already online. Donaldson,  
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, which has about 400 brokers, last week spun off 
its online trading division, DLJ Direct into a separate company. 
</P>
<P>
	DLJ Direct had 519,000 online accounts at the end of March, up  
21 percent from March 1998. Daily trades via the Internet more than 
doubled to 20,200 over the same period. 
</P>
<P>
	PaineWebber, which has a nationwide staff of 7,000 brokers, will  
begin offering two types of online trading the fall. One account 
will charge a flat fee for a set number of trades. Another account 
will charge a fixed fee for financial advice, and then charge low 
fee for each trade. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
