<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nevada Has Highest Rate of Suicide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Tony Hammond arrived in Las Vegas on a  
Greyhound bus with $250 in his pocket and, like migrants 
everywhere, hopes for a better life. 
</P>
<P>
	Four months later, he was penniless and on the streets.  
</P>
<P>
	``Twenty-seven and homeless,'' says Hammond, staring at the  
ground, his face flushed with embarrassment. 
</P>
<P>
	Hammond is hardly alone. In fact, beneath Nevada's bustling  
image -- its billion-dollar high-rise casinos and nonstop 
entertainment -- lies a more desperate reality: America's 
fastest-growing state has suicide and dropout rates that lead the 
nation, a teen-pregnancy rate near the top. The number of gun 
deaths recently ranked second only to Louisiana. 
</P>
<P>
	The state's allure may be part of its problem.  
</P>
<P>
	Every month, thousands of new residents flood Las Vegas, where  
two-thirds of Nevadans live. Some are enticed by the low cost of 
living and the promise of a booming economy in a state that has led 
the nation in population growth for 13 consecutive years. Others, 
nomads who've failed elsewhere, gamble on making it amid the 
glitter and hustle of a 24-hour town. 
</P>
<P>
	``We attract a lot of these people, drifters, people that  
haven't been able to hold jobs. They come in droves and then they 
fill the welfare list,'' said Bill Thompson, a professor of public 
administration and gambling expert at the University of Nevada, Las 
Vegas. ``Many are third-chancers, fourth-chancers. We're the last 
chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A variety of figures indicate that many of these dreams end in  
failure: 
</P>
<P>
	-- Nevada had the highest suicide rate in the nation in 1995, the  
latest year for which federal statistics are available. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The Violence Policy Center, an anti-gun group, recently ranked  
Nevada second in the number of gun deaths. Louisiana was first. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Nevada ranks among the unhealthiest states in the country,  
according to Minneapolis-based ReliaStar Financial Corp., finishing 
47th in 1997. It scored poorly for the prevalence of smoking, motor 
vehicle deaths, violent crime, risk of heart disease and for its 
high school graduation rates. 
</P>
<P>
	-- A recent study by UNLV said that some 6.6 percent of Clark  
County residents are pathological or problem gamblers; more than 
half know at least one person afflicted with problem gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	-- A recent national report said 17 percent of students aged 16  
to 19 dropped out of Nevada's high schools in 1996. That ranked the 
state worst in the nation, where the average was 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Nevada was among the 10 worst states in terms of births among  
girls ages 15 to 19 in 1996, according to the Kids Count 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Some officials, including state health officer Dr. Mary Guinan,  
blame Nevada's leaders for perpetuating a lax attitude toward 
social problems. Says Guinan: ``Nevada has not traditionally 
invested in prevention.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Progressive Alliance of Nevada, a lobbying group that promotes  
aggressive state policies on health issues, ranks Nevada 50th per 
capita for spending on health care and No. 1 in health-related 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nevada's stingy,'' said Bob Fulkerson, the group's director.  
``Even in the best of economic times, we have barely paid for 
social health programs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But others say solutions are more elusive.  
</P>
<P>
	``These unfortunate social problems exist worldwide. It's part  
of the human race. Why it stands out in Nevada I don't know,'' said 
Chris Chrystal, spokeswoman for the Nevada Commission on Tourism. 
</P>
<P>
	State officials acknowledge problems, but cite some improvement.  
``I think we've had just this tremendous growth and that certainly 
affects all of us,'' said Gov. Kenny Guinn, who recently proposed a 
program to help improve the state's dropout rate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're struggling somewhat when you look at our sources of  
income, sales tax and gaming taxes. When that doesn't do as well as 
we would like, it puts the state of Nevada in a very difficult 
situation,'' Guinn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hammond, who moved to Las Vegas from Lucerne Valley, Calif.,  
isn't quite sure what went wrong. He thought he could live on $250 
until he found a casino job. But his money ran out before could get 
an interview or a $35 sheriff's card, which is required to work in 
a casino. 
</P>
<P>
	``I figured I would have a job in two weeks. I figured two weeks  
-- it's Vegas, it's happening,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other failed dreams converge at St. Vincent's homeless shelter,  
where a line of 200 men waiting for an evening meal weaves around 
the corner. 
</P>
<P>
	Terrice McCarty is one. The 22-year-old found himself homeless  
after being turned down for jobs at fast-food restaurants. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just gave up. It's basically suicide out here,'' he said.  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
