<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The Western Hemisphere's leading publishers'  
group sent a high-level delegation to Mexico on Tuesday, demanding 
progress in the unsolved cases of journalists who have been killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Inter American Press Association President Jorge E. Fascetto  
said the group would urge the government resolve the cases quickly 
and would propose the creation of a special unit in the attorney 
general's office. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-member delegation planned to meet Wednesday with  
President Ernesto Zedillo. 
</P>
<P>
	The IAPA says more than 20 journalists apparently have been  
killed for doing their jobs in Mexico over the past decade. 
</P>
<P>
	The organization, which represents more than 1,300 publications  
throughout the Americas, began a project in 1995 to follow the 
course of unpunished crimes against journalists. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- President Fernando Henrique Cardoso said  
Tuesday he was preparing a bill that would ban the sale of firearms 
and ammunition in Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardoso said that according to the United Nations, Brazil was  
the world leader in crimes committed with firearms and asked 
Congress to take urgent action on the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am here today to tell you that we will take a energetic  
stance against violence,'' Cardoso said in a his weekly radio 
address. ``Everyday we have alarming news about deaths provoked by 
the indiscriminate use of firearms. Even in schools firearms are 
being used with fatal results.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the bill, only members of the military, police and private  
security firms could purchase firearms. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Tuesday, the Rio de Janeiro state assembly approved a  
similar bill 41-10, banning the sale of firearms throughout the 
state. The state governor is expected to sign it. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Ecuador plans to sell off or grant  
concessions to at least half its state-owned companies by 2001, 
pending Congress' approval, a top government official said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Alvaro Guerrero, head of Ecuador's privatization agency, told  
Dow Jones newswires the government hopes to bring in about $4 
billion from the privatizations, which will include electricity 
generators, concessions to various highways, the state telephone 
company and oil installations. 
</P>
<P>
	The privatization drive, if approved, will begin in December  
with the sale of six of the government's 25 electricity generators, 
Guerrero said. The state telephone company would be sold in the 
first quarter of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	President Jamil Mahuad took office 10 months ago promising to  
modernize Ecuador's economy and sell off its inefficient state 
companies. Powerful unions have said they will try to block the 
privatizations. 
</P>
<P>
	The poor South American nation is locked in its worst economic  
crisis in recent decades with the economy expected to shrink by 5 
percent this year and inflation topping 100 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- President Fernando Henrique Cardoso's  
approval rating has plunged to one of its lowest levels ever, 
according to a poll released Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll, prepared for the National Transportation Confederation  
by the Vox Populi Institute, showed 51 percent of respondents 
considers Cardoso's administration ``bad or very bad,'' 32 percent 
sees it as ``adequate'' and only 15 percent said it was ``good or 
very good.'' Two percent had no opinion. The margin of error was 3 
percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Confederation President Clesio Andrade said Cardoso's poor  
showing was mostly due to negative fallout from investigations into 
irregularities in Brazil's financial and judicial systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardoso was re-elected to a second term in October largely due  
to his successful economic policies. But the recession and 
unemployment that accompanied this success continue unabated. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) -- La Paz Mayor German Monroy was forced to  
resign Tuesday after the city council and Congress accused him of 
corruption and financial mismanagement. 
</P>
<P>
	Monroy, who leaves La Paz virtually bankrupt, was the ninth  
mayor in as many years in the city of one million. 
</P>
<P>
	City Council president Lupe Andrade was sworn in as his  
replacement. A former newspaper editor, Andrade is a member of the 
ruling conservative Nationalist Democratic Action. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor before Monroy, Gaby Candia, was removed as mayor after  
she was charged with corruption and mismanagement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
