<DOCNO> APW19990601.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 09:40:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Econoomy Expands in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The nation's industrial sector expanded for a  
fourth straight month in May, but indications of strong price rises 
in raw materials for the first time in 16 months sent shivers 
through financial markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Purchasing Management said its  
monthly index of business activity rose to 55.2 in May from 52.8 in 
April -- a much stronger showing than analysts had expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Most startling, however, was the rise in the association's price  
index, which jumped to 52.2 in May from 49.9 in April. It was the 
first time since December 1997 that manufacturers indicated they 
were seeing higher input prices, the trade association said. 
</P>
<P>
	Such readings disturb financial markets, which have been  
concerned that the Federal Reserve may follow through on its threat 
to raise interest rates if it sees inflation building up in the 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average, down almost 270 points last  
week as inflation jitters grew on Wall Street, was off an 
additional 110 at midday, and long-term Treasury bond yields were 
edging closer toward 6 percent, reaching the highest level in more 
than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a certain feeling (in the market) that the question is  
when, not if, rates will be raised,'' said Anthony Chan, chief 
economist at Banc One Investment Advisors in Columbus, Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there were indications in other economic gauges released  
today that inflationary pressures for the time being are limited. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board, a nonprofit business research group, said  
in a separate report that its Index of Leading Economic Indicators 
-- a gauge of future economic activity -- declined in April for the 
first time since June 1998, suggesting some softening in the 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	And a Commerce Department report said construction spending fell  
by a sharp 2.4 percent in April, the biggest monthly decline in 
more than five years for an industry that has been a driving force 
in the economic expansion. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchasing managers, a group that represents executives who  
buy raw materials and supplies for manufacturers, saw some good in 
the rise in prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``Though commodity prices are active and rising, we must keep in  
mind the extent of the decline that they have experienced. Many 
commodity producers have had a tough time over the last year and a 
half and some upward movement probably constitutes welcome 
relief,'' said the report released by Norbert J. Ore, director of 
purchasing at Chesapeake Corp., and chairman of the Business Survey 
Committee of the purchasing managers' group. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that he did not expect the price increases -- which  
showed up most strongly in petroleum products, metals, plastics and 
paper -- to be passed by manufacturers to their customers because 
``there is still considerable excess capacity'' in the industrial 
sector. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board said the Index of Leading Economic  
Indicators fell 0.1 percent in April to 107.1, the first decline 
since June 1998, when the gauge fell 0.2 percent. A revised figure 
for March showed the index unchanged at 107.2 from the previous 
month following five consecutive monthly increases. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had been expecting a slight rise in the index.  
</P>
<P>
	Michael Boldin, director of business cycle research at the  
Conference Board, said that a single month's dip in the index did 
not necessarily signal that the economy's strong growth would 
falter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We look at trends over six months before we have any  
concern,'' Boldin said. He noted that despite April's decline, the 
index was up some 1.3 percent over the past six months. 
</P>
<P>
	``This looks like only a temporary pause, although last week's  
drop in the stock market adds some complications,'' Boldin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``With most of the leading indicators, including the stock  
market, showing increases this year and the economy showing growth 
in so many areas, this expansion should continue and become the 
longest ever in early 2000,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board's index of coincident indicators, which  
measure current activity, rose 0.2 percent in April, while it's 
lagging index which reflects the economy's past performance, rose 
0.4 percent. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
