<HEADLINE> Study: Clot Drugs Help Blood Flow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *BY SUSAN PARROTT   	
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A new regimen for treating heart attacks could  
save thousands of patients who aren't helped by current 
clot-busting therapy and could eliminate the need for some 
angioplasty or bypass surgery, a new study shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors added a ``super-aspirin'' called abciximab, or Reopro,  
to a standard clot buster, alteplase, also known as Activase. They 
found it restored normal blood flow in the hearts of more than 
three-quarters of heart attack victims. 
</P>
<P>
	The international study was published in today's edition of  
Circulation, a journal of the American Heart Association. It was 
intended to see if abciximab could boost the effectiveness of 
alteplase. Alteplase and similar drugs such as TPA (tissue 
plasminogen activator) are already a mainstay of heart attack 
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	``We demonstrated that a combination of two drugs is better than  
one drug for opening blocked arteries,'' said Dr. Elliott M. 
Antman, director of the Coronary Care Unit at Brigham and Women's 
Hospital in Boston. ``We can open up blocked arteries faster and 
more extensively.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both drugs are administered intravenously.  
</P>
<P>
	Antman said the new therapy could be the biggest advance in  
heart attack treatment since clot-busting drugs were introduced 15 
years ago. But he said that additional research may be needed 
before the therapy is put into clinical practice. 
</P>
<P>
	The drugs are complementary, Antman said, because alteplase  
dissolves blood clots, while abciximab keeps platelets and proteins 
from clumping. 
</P>
<P>
	Aspirin also blocks platelets. But abciximab is much more  
potent, which is why the drug is often called a ``super-aspirin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Antman's study included 888 heart attack patients at 63  
hospitals in North America, Britain, the Netherlands, France and 
Germany and examined the ability of the drugs to dissolve blood 
clots within 60 to 90 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	The study showed that 72 percent of patients who received  
abciximab plus half the standard dose of alteplase achieved optimal 
blood flow in their arteries within 60 minutes. Only 43 percent of 
patients had normal blood flow with TPA alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Within 90 minutes, 77 percent of patients treated with both  
drugs had optimal blood flow, compared with 62 percent with 
alteplase alone. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers ``have made a major contribution'' to the  
management of heart attacks, Dr. J. Ward Kennedy of the University 
of Washington wrote in an editorial about the research in 
Circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	The advent of clot-busting therapy has revolutionized heart  
attack care by halting deadly damage to heart muscle. However, 
clot-busters alone are not always effective, and many individuals 
develop recurrent blood clots. 
</P>
<P>
	``By enhancing the effects of clot-busters, abciximab may  
improve the treatment for heart attacks, and allow more patients to 
be treated with drugs rather than angioplasty and surgery,'' Antman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers estimate that the new double-drug treatment will  
save 20 additional lives for every 1,000 heart attack patients who 
receive it. 
</P>
<P>
	The study was funded by Eli Lilly and Co. and Centocor, which  
together market abciximab. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
