<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teens Tried for Death of Gay Man </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Lawyers for two high school  
dropouts admitted Tuesday that the teen-agers beat a gay man to 
death, but they claimed it was not because of his sexual 
orientation. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryan Donahue, 17, and Billy Dodge, 18, are on trial for  
allegedly beating and kicking Steven Goedereis in front of a closed 
convenience store last year. The teen-agers are charged with 
second-degree murder and could be sentenced to life in prison if 
convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Goedereis, 29, was beaten beyond recognition. Blood splatters  
were found on the overhang of the building. There was a sneaker 
imprint on his forehead. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say the attack was provoked when the soft-spoken,  
118-pound Goedereis called one of the boys ``beautiful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for Dodge and Donahue offered a dramatically different  
version of what happened. They said that Dodge thought Goedereis 
was a man who'd been stalking his girlfriend and that Donahue 
claimed Goedereis had tried to rape him. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a case of second-degree murder where Mr. Goedereis  
was singled out because of his sexual preference,'' said Mitchell 
Beers, Dodge's attorney. ``He was chosen because somebody thought 
he was a stalker -- and Bryan told Billy a man tried to rape him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors hope the boys' own statements to police will prove  
otherwise. Both men told police Goedereis had complimented them on 
their looks. And Donahue allegedly told police, ``The fact that he 
was gay upset me the most.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
