<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Hunts Federal Hackers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Computer hackers who vandalized five  
government Web sites are being hunted by the FBI and could face 
jail time, FBI and Justice Department officials said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials took a dim view of the hackers who left a note  
threatening to attack other sites in retaliation for an FBI 
investigation in Texas into hacking at a corporate Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time-consuming and takes a lot of spade work, but we can  
track down many of these hackers, and that's going on now,'' FBI 
spokesman Frank Scafidi said. ``We'll catch a few, no matter how 
deep they hide in their basements. Someone will go to jail for some 
real time. That will have impact.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Scafidi said a Dallas company he would not identify ``lost a few  
million dollars'' because of hackers. 
</P>
<P>
	Hackers who cause $5,000 damage in one year can be charged with  
a federal felony that carries up to five years in prison, said 
Scott Charney, head of the Justice Department's computer crime 
section. Merely trespassing on a government computer, without 
authorization and without causing a loss, can bring up to a year in 
jail. 
</P>
<P>
	``Vandalism at government Web sites could cost more than $5,000  
in employee time and salaries to repair,'' Charney said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, hackers defaced Web sites for the Interior Department  
and a federal supercomputer laboratory in Idaho Falls, Idaho. 
</P>
<P>
	Messages left at the sites suggest they were attacked to  
retaliate against what the vandals called the FBI's harassment of 
hacker groups, including one that boasted of breaking into the 
White House site last month. Earlier, a flood of access requests 
forced the FBI to shut down its site, and other hackers defaced the 
U.S. Senate site. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do they think we're going to roll over and let them access  
anything they want on the Internet because they issue this 
threat?'' Scafidi asked. ``That's not the way it works.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They're hurting honest individuals -- researchers, students,  
reporters -- who need to get information from these government 
sites,'' Scafidi added. ``It's not hurting the FBI, because they 
can't reach our sensitive data from there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The latest spate of attacks are outside a tradition of so-called  
``ethical hacking devoted to opening up government,'' Charney said. 
``These attacks are preventing people from obtaining government 
information. It's not good for the public or democracy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like all types of crime, computer crimes are not all solved.  
Cybercrime can leave an electronic audit trail to the culprits, 
Charney said. But the Internet has special difficulties: Access is 
global and there are anonymous remailers that strip and discard the 
identities of those who send messages. 
</P>
<P>
	And computer crime is growing as computer literacy grows.  
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Sentencing Commission found 76 defendants convicted of  
violating computer statutes during 1989-1994 but noted that an 
uncounted number of computer criminals were charged with wire 
fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1999 computer crime survey done by the Computer Security  
Institute and the FBI's San Francisco office found that system 
penetration by outsiders increased for the third year in a row. 
Such intrusions were reported by 30 percent of the 521 computer 
security professionals surveyed. 
</P>
<P>
	Losses also mounted: 163 respondents reported almost $124  
million in losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on the rise was reporting of such incidents to law  
enforcement: 32 percent had done so compared with only 17 percent 
three years earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI executed four search warrants last week in Texas in a  
computer intrusion probe, including a search at a prominent Houston 
hacker's home. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Interior Department's Web page, the hackers left a  
message saying they were ``going after every computer on the Net 
with a .gov (suffix). ... We'll keep hitting them until they get 
down on their knees and beg.'' At the site maintained by the Idaho 
National Engineering and Environmental Laboratory, a note 
threatened the electronic destruction of powerful computers that 
``serve'' pages on the Internet ``if the FBI doesn't stop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, a grand jury in northern Virginia indicted  
Eric Burns, 19, on three counts of computer intrusion. Burns, 
reportedly known as ``Zyklon,'' is believed to belong to the group 
that claimed to have attacked the White House and Senate sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon announced that additional  
``firewalls'' were installed in Defense Department computers 
Tuesday to add layers of protection against hacking into Pentagon 
Internet sites. ``We obviously have been watching what's been 
happening on other government agencies, and we are responding to 
that. But it's also part of something that we've been developing 
for some time,'' Bacon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
