<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Polygamist Stands Trial for Incest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A teen-age girl who grew up in a  
polygamist sect testified at her uncle's incest trial today that 
she had four sexual encounters with him after becoming his 15th 
wife. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl, now 17, took the stand as the prosecution's star  
witness against David O. Kingston, 32. The case has focused 
attention on the secretive Kingston clan, which has as many as 
1,000 members and business assets worth up to $150 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The clan shares many of the beliefs of other polygamous groups  
in Utah, but stands apart, former members say, in practicing 
incest. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl said that in a meeting with her parents and Kingston in  
September 1997, ``he said that some of his family had dreams that 
I'd come into his family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Oct. 13, 1997, he called her and suggested they marry on the  
15th -- a date Kingston thought was appropriate because she was to 
be his 15th wife, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was kind of a shock. It was in two days. I just wanted more  
time,'' she said, appearing composed and speaking softly. 
</P>
<P>
	With her father performing the ceremony and the defendant's  
other wives in attendance, the girl married her uncle on the 15th, 
she said. Her uncle later gave her a ring with 15 diamonds, she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	After the ceremony, they had four sexual encounters, all in  
1998, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl, who now is in state-supervised foster care, said she  
repeatedly tried to avoid her husband-uncle and would stay out late 
with friends when she knew he was planning to visit. 
</P>
<P>
	Kingston is charged with incest and unlawful sexual contact and  
could be sentenced to 20 years in prison if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	On April 21, the girl's father, John Daniel Kingston, pleaded no  
contest to child abuse for beating his daughter with a belt. He 
faces up to five years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts place Utah's polygamist population somewhere between  
20,000 and 30,000. About 70 percent of Utah's population are 
members of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, which 
renounced polygamy in 1890 after Congress passed tough anti-bigamy 
laws. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
