<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Construction Spending Plunges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Construction spending, which had been one of  
the driving forces in the economic expansion, fell by a sharp 2.4 
percent in April, the biggest monthly decline in more than five 
years, the government reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department said the declines were widespread with  
decreases reported in single-family homes, apartment buildings, 
office buildings and big government projects. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2.4 percent drop caught analysts by surprise. Many had been  
expecting the country's construction boom to continue in April 
althought at a slightly slower pace than previous months. 
</P>
<P>
	The April decline followed five straight monthly increases  
including a 1.3 percent advance in March and a sizable 2.1 percent 
gain in February. The April decline was the first setback since a 
0.3 percent drop last October and it was the biggest monthly 
decrease since a 3 percent plunge in January 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Home building and other construction activity, driven by low  
mortgage rates, was a key contributing factor to the strong 
economic growth in the early part of the year. Both sales of new 
homes and existing homes hit record highs during the winter. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the pace of home sales have cooled somewhat in recent  
months, reflecting rising mortgage rates. Sales of existing 
single-family homes fell 3.3 percent in April after hitting a 
record high in March. Sales of new homes were up in March, but that 
followed four monthly declines. 
</P>
<P>
	The construction report showed that spending on residential  
construction fell by 1 percent in April to a seasonally adjusted 
annual rate of $324.7 billion with both single-family homes and 
apartments suffering declines. 
</P>
<P>
	Construction spending for all private building projects was off  
1.9 percent in April as spending on factories, office buildings, 
hotels and hospitals all saw declines. Spending on private 
construction had been up 1.9 percent in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Spending on government construction projects fell an even  
sharper 4.2 percent in April, the largest decline in this category 
since a 4.8 percent decrease last May. Public spending had fallen 
0.8 percent in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Spending for highways, hospitals and water supply facilities  
were all down while spending on military facilities and housing 
redevelopment recorded increases. 
</P>
<P>
	For April, spending on all construction projects totaled $697.4  
billion at a seasonally adjusted annual rate, up 8 percent from the 
spending level in April 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
