<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cathay Airways Cancels More Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Cathay Pacific Airways canceled 47 flights  
Wednesday, as angry pilots staging a sickout planned to meet with 
Hong Kong's labor commissioner to seek any way out of the pay 
dispute that has affected 20,000 passengers over six days. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay said it was working to get all travelers to their  
destinations, and it was able to replace 21 of its grounded 
services with flights chartered from other airlines. But the Hong 
Kong carrier still is not selling tickets or making any new 
bookings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hong Kong Aircrew Officers Association, meanwhile, said it  
would meet in the afternoon with the territory's labor 
commissioner, Matthew Cheung, to explain the pilots' predicament 
and seek ways of getting the two sides together. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all have to be optimistic,'' John Findlay, the secretary  
general of the air crew union, said by telephone. ``The longer the 
dispute drags on, the more inconvenience the public's going to go 
through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay is seeking pay cuts of up to 8 percent from the pilots in  
exchange for stock options as it tries to cut costs and return to 
profitability amid Asia's economic crisis and Hong Kong's 
recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Relations between the two sides deteriorated last week, when  
Cathay bosses gave the pilots until June 11 to either accept its 
offer, quit or be fired. 
</P>
<P>
	Numerous pilots started phoning in sick, saying the situation  
has left them too stressed to fly -- and forcing the massive 
disruptions in Cathay's schedule. The airline has had to scrap some 
150 flights between Hong Kong and a variety of destinations in 
Asia, North America and Europe. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
