<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Meets Potential Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton interviewed  
potential campaign staff at the White House on Tuesday, and told at 
least two associates that she intends to seek the Senate seat from 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The associates, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Mrs.  
Clinton is virtually certain to seek the seat being vacated by 
retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan and is close to finalizing 
that decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton intends to notify New York Rep. Nita Lowey, a  
Democrat who was considering the race herself, of her plans but it 
may be several days before the first lady talks to the 
congresswoman, the associates said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not aware of any decision having been made,'' Lowey  
spokesman Howard Wolfson said Tuesday. Wolfson said his boss ``has 
not been told anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A senior adviser to the first lady who is intimately involved in  
her deliberations said the decision is not quite final, ``but she's 
edging awfully close to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The official said Mrs. Clinton seemed even more likely to run  
after spending the Memorial Day weekend with her husband in 
Florida. Barring a ``dramatic change of heart,'' she will run, the 
aide said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other Clinton advisers said there are tentative plans for her to  
announce the formation of an exploratory committee during a trip to 
New York in early July, though they cautioned that another scenario 
under consideration is to announce the committee simply through a 
statement from her White House office. 
</P>
<P>
	For the record, Mrs. Clinton's spokeswoman, Marsha Berry, said:  
``Nothing has changed except that they are back from vacation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady met Tuesday at the White House with potential  
campaign workers, including Hank Morris, a New York consultant 
coming off Chuck Schumer's victorious 1998 Senate campaign to 
unseat Alfonse D'Amato; Gabrielle Fialkoff, who was the chief 
fund-raiser for New York City Council Speaker Peter Vallone's 
unsuccessful gubernatorial bid last year; and Richard A. Riley, a 
veteran New York public relations specialist. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is scheduled to be in New York Wednesday to give  
the commencement address at City College and attend two political 
events. After the graduation ceremony, she will attend a Manhattan 
luncheon for state Democrats and an evening fund-raiser for U.S. 
Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Several of Mrs. Clinton's friends and advisers said they expect  
the next step in her deliberative move toward a campaign to be the 
announcement of a formal exploratory committee. That won't likely 
be made official until after Mrs. Clinton's travels abroad June 
15-30. For now, she is scheduled to travel through Europe with 
President Clinton to the summit of G-8 leaders in Germany, and then 
split off for a solo tour through Israel, Jordan and Morocco. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
