<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wash. Revokes 'Prozac' Dr.'s License </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) -- A psychologist who gained notoriety as the  
``pied piper of Prozac'' because of his aggressive promotion of the 
antidepressant drug lost his license to practice on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington state Health Department's Examining Board of  
Psychology had charged Dr. James Goodwin with unprofessional 
conduct for failing to comply with a 1996 disciplinary order that 
he enter into an agreement with an adviser to monitor his practice. 
</P>
<P>
	In its order on Tuesday, the board called Goodwin's conduct  
unprofessional and wrote that revoking his license is ``the only 
sanction that sufficiently protects the public.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goodwin, 52, said he planned to appeal in federal court in hopes  
of winning back his license. He also said he would continue to see 
patients as a mental health therapist. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodwin contends he has followed the wishes of the examining  
board, and he added: ``There are people on the licensing board 
running psychology in this state who are mentally ill and causing 
many of us problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goodwin has been in practice in the north-central Washington  
city of Wenatchee since 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1990s, he attracted widespread attention for his  
belief that everyone suffers from at least some level of depression 
and would benefit from a combination of antidepressants and 
therapy. 
</P>
<P>
	In December 1993, the licensing board accused Goodwin of  
breaching patient confidentiality, diagnosing patients without 
adequate evaluation, pressuring patients into taking Prozac and 
retaliating against a psychologist who protested his treatment 
methods. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 12:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Christian Coalition Shifts Top Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pat Robertson, president and founder of the  
Christian Coalition, is restructing the leadership of his powerful 
conservative organization to assume more authority and move former 
GOP lawmaker Randy Tate to Washington to keep tabs on Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Tate will lose the title of executive director, becoming senior  
vice president for government relations. An official close to the 
group, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Tate will not be 
replaced as executive director. The Christian Coalition is based in 
Chesapeake, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson is said to be upset that the GOP-led Senate responded  
to the school shootings in Colorado by passing gun control 
measures. He wants Tate to create a more aggressive lobbying 
operation. 
</P>
<P>
	The move leaves Robertson in charge of day-to-day operations of  
the group he founded after his 1988 run for the Republican 
presidential nomination. In the last several months, Robertson has 
slowly reasserted his authority over the group, which has had 
fund-raising and organizational problems. It is one of the most 
influential conservative political groups in the nation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
