<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 23:40:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.C. Activist Arrested in Shootings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAMLET, N.C. (AP) -- A man who gained national notoriety when he  
held newspaper employees hostage 11 years ago has been arrested on 
murder charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Eddie Hatcher, 41, was taken into custody without incident while  
driving away from a house in Hamlet, about 75 miles east of 
Charlotte, Sheriff Glenn Maynor said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They got me charged with murder?'' Hatcher said as he was led  
from Hamlet's police headquarters. ``I didn't kill nobody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maynor said Hatcher was wanted in a drive-by shooting Monday  
night near Maxton, where Hatcher used to live. Investigators said 
Bryan McMillian, 19, was killed at his home when Hatcher fired into 
a building with a high-powered rifle. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know what the motive behind this one was,'' said  
homicide Capt. Randal Patterson. ``He shot the house. He didn't 
know what he was going to hit and probably didn't know who all was 
in the house.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shelby McMillian, the slaying victim's mother, said Hatcher was  
upset with her son because someone had stolen property from 
Hatcher's home and taken it to McMillian. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatcher also had been sought since May 19, when a man was shot  
and wounded in a convenience store in Lumberton, 110 miles east of 
Charlotte. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatcher and Timothy Jacobs, both Tuscarora Indians, took over  
The Robesonian newspaper in Lumberton on Feb. 1, 1988. The armed 
men said they were protesting what they said was corruption in 
Robeson County government. They held hostages for 10 hours before 
surrendering. 
</P>
<P>
	They were acquitted of federal hostage-taking and firearms  
charges, but were later indicted on state charges. Both went to 
prison -- Hatcher for five years and Jacobs for less than three -- 
and were eventually paroled. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatcher was being held Tuesday night at a prison in Raleigh that  
has medical facilities able to treat the symptoms of AIDS, which 
Hatcher said he contracted while in prison. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 16:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tiananmen Victims Sue China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Survivors of the Tiananmen Square massacre and  
relatives of victims said Tuesday they had filed a lawsuit in China 
demanding an investigation and an apology from the government. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ten years after the Tiananmen massacre, the perpetrators have  
still not been brought to justice,'' said Xiao Qiang, executive 
director of Human Rights in China, a group based in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit filed last month in Beijing also seeks the release  
of political prisoners arrested in the protest and the return of 
people who went into exile afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	Announcement of the lawsuit was timed to coincide with the 10th  
anniversary of the June 4, 1989, massacre in Beijing's central 
square. Hundreds of people were killed when the government sent in 
soldiers and tanks to crush seven weeks of pro-democracy protests. 
</P>
<P>
	Many who took part said they were patriots who only wanted  
government reforms. Supporters of the lawsuit said they will be 
sending evidence they've collected to the United Nations and other 
governments to try to pressure China's politicians to respond. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said the student-led protests were an  
anti-government rebellion that threatened communist rule. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Chinese government took timely and resolute measures which  
were necessary for the development and stability of the country,'' 
Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said Tuesday. ``We have 
already come to a correct conclusion over this. There will be no 
change whatsoever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ding Zilin, a professor at People's University who organized the  
lawsuit, said by telephone from Beijing at a news conference in New 
York that her son was killed in the massacre. She has spent years 
gathering evidence from other victims' families, including photos 
and eyewitness accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Ding said the painstaking process of finding others who joined  
in the suit -- 160 victims' families and 70 of the wounded -- 
included raising the incident with every taxi driver she met and 
staking out tombstones dated ``June 4, 1989'' to seek out mourners. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not allowed to speak openly about the facts of how our  
loved ones were murdered and we cannot mourn our dead in public,'' 
she said. ``But what distresses us survivors the most, and makes us 
feel most guilty, is that the unfair charges against our loved ones 
have not been dismissed. We cannot even say a simple `rest in 
peace' to their buried souls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those at the news conference included Li Lu, a student leader of  
the 1989 movement who described watching his classmates get run 
down by a tank; Zhang Liming, whose sister was murdered by 
soldiers; and Zhang Yalai, whose leg was amputated after he was 
shot in the square. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 23:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Fiber Benefits Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A study of more than 68,000 women found that  
dietary fiber -- particularly from breakfast cereals -- can 
significantly lower the risk of heart attacks, researchers reported 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The fiber helps by improving cholesterol levels, lowering blood  
sugar, boosting sensitivity to insulin and lowering the risk of 
blood clotting, according to a study published in today's Journal 
of the American Medical Association. 
</P>
<P>
	A previous study of men had similar results.  
</P>
<P>
	Healthy female nurses studied at Brigham and Women's Hospital in  
Boston were divided into five groups, from highest to lowest fiber 
consumption, and their diets were tracked for 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Women in the highest fiber group ate about 22 grams per day.  
They had a 47 percent lower risk of heart disease than women in the 
lowest group, who consumed about 11 grams of fiber a day. 
</P>
<P>
	``For every five-gram increase in fiber -- which is equal to a  
bowl of cereal per day -- the risk of heart disease was reduced by 
more than 30 percent,'' said Dr. JoAnn Manson, the author of the 
study. 
</P>
<P>
	She said fruits and vegetables also are good sources of fiber.  
She cautioned that over-the-counter fiber supplements are not 
effective substitutes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
