<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Va. Family's Murder Called Targeted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Associated Press Writer-    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The FBI and police in a Washington suburb are  
investigating the ``targeted'' killing of an Iraqi-American 
businessman, his school teacher wife and their 16-year-old son. 
</P>
<P>
	Fairfax County, Va., police are not ruling out anything, but  
``it appears it was a targeted incident and does not appear to be a 
random incident,'' police spokeswoman Katie Hughes said today. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the FBI was called in to help gather evidence and  
explore possible international connections in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Fuad Khazi Taima, 63; his wife, Dorothy Mae Taima, 54; and their  
son, Leith Fuad, all died of gunshot wounds to the upper body, 
police said. Their bodies were found in the family home in the 
Washington suburb of McLean, Va., on Friday after an anonymous 
call. 
</P>
<P>
	Police believe the shooting may have occurred on Wednesday when  
neighbors recalled hearing noises that could have been gunshots. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is being handled as a triple murder, not a  
murder-suicide or robbery, Hughes said. She said there was no sign 
of forced entry into the home. 
</P>
<P>
	Tiama's wife was an English teacher and their son a sophomore at  
McLean High School. 
</P>
<P>
	The police spokeswoman said Faud was a businessman who had been  
traveling back and forth between the United States and Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	An FBI spokeswoman, Elisa Foster, confirmed that the FBI was  
assisting in the investigation. She said the FBI is routinely 
called in to help with violent crimes, whether there it has an 
international element or not. She declined to say what aspects of 
the investigation the FBI was handling. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither investigative agency would comment on reports they were  
looking into whether the crime involved either the Iraqi government 
or its U.S. opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	Taimi has been prominent in the Iraqi-American community as  
founder of the American-Iraqi Foundation to help improve U.S.-Iraqi 
relations during the 1980-1988 Iran-Iraq War. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
