<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 12:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Corps Director Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mark Gearan is resigning as director of the  
Peace Corps to become a college president, the White House said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gearan, the corps' director since August 1995, is leaving to  
accept the presidency of Hobart and William Smith Colleges in 
Geneva, N.Y. President Clinton said Gearan is perfect for the job: 
``He is gifted, humane, a leader and deeply committed to the 
education of young people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gearan is a former deputy chief of staff and director of  
communications and strategic planning at the White House. He served 
as Vice President Al Gore's campaign manager in the 1992 
presidential campaign. He also was director of state-federal 
relations for Massachusetts, was press secretary in the 1988 
presidential campaign of Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and for 
three years was executive director of the Democratic Governors 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have relied on Mark Gearan's skills, wisdom and talents for  
many years,'' Clinton said. ``He has rejuvenated the Peace Corps. 
... He can be proud that the Peace Corps will soon have more 
volunteers serving overseas than at any time in a generation. I 
thank Mark for his friendship and service.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gearan informed Clinton of his decision Tuesday, White House  
spokesman Joe Lockhart said. He said there was no word on when 
Gearan would leave or when Clinton would announce a replacement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
