<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 16:46:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Hungarian Is Tops in NCAA Discus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUBURN, Ala. (AP) --Fresh from an exam that took longer than  
expected, Gabor Mate raced across Auburn's campus on a bicycle. 
</P>
<P>
	No matter that he's late. He still greets everyone he passes.  
When he finally climbs off the bike and strolls across the track, 
Mate declines to sit for an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll stand,'' the 6-foot-6 Hungarian said. ``I am a sportsman,  
you know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That he is.  
</P>
<P>
	Mate, a 20-year-old freshman, enters Wednesday's NCAA Outdoor  
Track and Field Championships in Boise, Idaho, as the nation's top 
discus thrower. 
</P>
<P>
	Mate (pronounced Mah-tay) arrived in the United States on Jan.  
1. He expected to do well at Auburn, but never this well. 
</P>
<P>
	His throw of 202 feet, 7 inches at last month's Reebok  
Invitational is the best in the NCAA this year. He's won six of the 
seven tournament's he's entered. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know that in college there are a lot of good throwers so it  
is a big pleasure to have the best mark right now,'' he said in 
accented, yet fluid, English. ``But I am too young for this sport -- 
you could not call yourself world class until you are around 26 
years old. I still have years to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Realizing that made it easier for Mate to leave Hungary. In his  
hometown of Bekescsaba, he could be an athlete or a student -- not 
both. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Mate nor his father would settle for that. So the two  
discussed sending Mate to the United States to study and train. 
</P>
<P>
	They made up their mind watching the 1996 Olympics. Hungary's  
Balazs Kiss had left the country to attend Southern California and 
won a gold medal in the hammer throw during the games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew then that the U.S. college system offered me many  
opportunities that I would not have at home,'' Mate said. ``I want 
to be an Olympian, but if I tried to do that in Hungary I would be 
nothing after the age of 35. In the U.S., I can learn to be a 
successful businessman also.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But first Mate had to pay for an American education. He said two  
months of his parents' salary comes out to be about $500. So a 
scholarship was his only option. 
</P>
<P>
	After graduating from high school in 1997, Mate took off all of  
1998 to train. His goal was to attract college recruiters while 
competing in junior events. He wrote to schools, but only one coach 
got in touch. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Clayton was an assistant at Florida when he contacted the  
Hungarian federation about athletes interested in coming to the 
United States. They gave him Mate's name. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have a tradition of strong throwers in Hungary, so he  
could have trained there and had a great career,'' Clayton said. 
``But he wouldn't have had an opportunity to get an education, and 
that's something that is important to Gabor and his family. Gabor 
is very strong in the classroom and values getting a degree.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mate was immediately interested in Florida, but then Clayton  
took an assistant job at Auburn. 
</P>
<P>
	Mate made his first trip to the United States in November. He  
and his father visited Auburn and South Carolina, bypassing other 
schools out of loyalty to Clayton. 
</P>
<P>
	Clayton promised he would help Mate throw between 3 and 6 feet  
further within a year -- Mate is already throwing 10 feet further 
then when he arrived at Auburn. 
</P>
<P>
	Should Mate win an NCAA title this week, he and Clayton won't be  
satisfied. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our real goal right now is for the Sydney Olympics, for him to  
meet the qualifying standard and make his country's team,'' Clayton 
said. ``Right now, he only ranks about fifth or sixth in Hungary, 
so we want him to get up there with the best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mate also has another goal -- to convince Clayton to offer a  
scholarship to his 15-year-old sister, Katalin. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are a sports crazy family and right now she is so jealous  
for me and what I am doing here,'' Mate said. ``But she is the 
talented one and someday I will be so jealous for her because she 
might be the best in the world.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 16:46:01 </DATE_TIME>
