<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 05:40:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Remembering War Dead on USS Intrepid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Standing in sweltering heat, John Bonomo  
struggled against tears to explain why he spends each Memorial Day 
aboard the USS Intrepid, the aircraft carrier that was his home 
during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	He and another former crew member, Hector Giannasca, also in his  
70s, returned to the ship's decks today to pay homage to a pair of 
friends who grew up together, went to war together, and were killed 
together on a grim day in 1945 when a Japanese kamikaze fighter 
targeted their ship. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never knew what a kamikaze was,'' Giannasca said, shaking  
his head in disbelief over an enemy that trained pilots for 
suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Scores of military personnel in full uniform gathered with  
Bonomo and Giannasca and other former crew members to recall fallen 
comrades who served on the Intrepid and in other conflicts. 
</P>
<P>
	They stood as an Air Force band played the national anthem and  
the hands of old men quivered as they held their salutes. Tears 
fell as a trumpeter's horn sounded ``Taps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Intrepid, commissioned in 1943 and converted to a museum off  
a New York pier 86 in 1982, serves as the platform for the city's 
Memorial Day celebration each year. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of similar ceremonies were held around the country.  
</P>
<P>
	The Intrepid now carries historic aircraft including the Grumman  
E-IB Tracer used in Korea and the ``Melody II'' Bell UH-1M Huey 
from Vietnam. A plaque marks the spot where 10 men died during a 
kamikaze attack on Oct. 29, 1944. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must remember the fallen,'' said Vice Admiral James C. Card  
of the Coast Guard. ``And we must remember the causes for which 
they fell.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 14:50:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> It's `Josh' Mania in Baseball Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Most scouts agree the No. 1 pick in baseball's  
amateur draft Wednesday will be a high school kid named Josh. But 
which Josh? 
</P>
<P>
	Josh Hamilton, an outfielder from Athens Drive High School in  
North Carolina, and Josh Beckett, a right-hander from Spring High 
School in Texas have posted impressive numbers and are expected to 
be the first two players selected. 
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay, Florida, Detroit, Arizona and Minnesota have the  
first five picks. Four teams -- Anaheim, Atlanta, Cleveland and the 
New York Mets -- do not have any picks until the second round. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that we're picking No. 1, we're excited about getting a  
very good player,'' Devil Rays scouting director Dan Jennings said. 
``We just want to get the best player in the country, whether it's 
a high school player or a college player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last high school player taken with the first pick was Alex  
Rodriguez, chosen by Seattle in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	While some teams have balked at the escalation in signing  
bonuses negotiated by first-round picks -- the Philadelphia Phillies 
declined to sign J.D. Drew, who then was taken by St. Louis last 
summer -- Tampa Bay will likely be able to sign the franchise's 
first No. 1 pick. They gave free agent Matt White a $10.2 million 
signing bonus in 1996, which is still the highest ever for an 
amateur player. 
</P>
<P>
	Only twice since 1971 have the first three picks been high  
school players. It could happen again this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton, who is 6-foot-4, is an outstanding hitter with a  
strong arm. He is projected as a pro right fielder, even though 
he's got a 94-mph fastball. 
</P>
<P>
	Beckett, also 6-4, has a shot at becoming the first high school  
right-hander selected No. 1 overall. He has impressed scouts with a 
fastball that reaches the mid-90s consistently, and a lively 
curveball. Even if he's taken second, Beckett would be the first 
high school righty taken that high since Bill Gullickson in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	B.J. Garbe, an outfielder/right-hander from Moses Lake High  
School in Washington, is also at the top of many scouts' wish 
lists. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's probably a better crop of high school prospects in the  
first round this year,'' Kansas City Royals scouting director Terry 
Wetzel said. ``And there aren't a whole lot of college position 
players in the first round.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some scouts have predicted that up to 20 of the 30 first-round  
selections will be high school players. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there are just more high school players that will go  
in the first round,'' Baltimore scouting director Tony DeMacio 
said. ``However, there are some good, quality college arms out 
there. It's just one of those years where there just aren't many 
college position players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Southern California catcher Eric Munson is expected to be a  
top-five pick, possibly in the top three. While his left-handed 
stroke and ability to flat-out hit have scouts excited, his 
defensive shortcomings also have them somewhat concerned. 
</P>
<P>
	Northeast Louisiana right-hander Ben Sheets, Baylor  
right-hander/designated hitter Jason Jennings, Miami shortstop 
Bobby Hill, Providence outfielder Keith Reed and North Carolina 
righty Kyle Snyder are expected to be first-rounders. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan Christianson, a catcher from Arlington High School in  
California, Bobby Bradley, a right-hander from Wellington High 
School in Florida, and Brett Myers, a righty from Englewood High 
School in Florida, are expected to be among the first high school 
players selected. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore and San Diego will benefit most from having extra  
first-round picks as compensation for losing Type A free agents. 
The Orioles have four of the first 23 picks, while the Padres have 
six of the first 51. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, our plan is just to take the best available player  
at each pick,'' DeMacio said. ``Whether that's a high school or 
college pitcher or hitter, we want to get the best player there. 
The strategy remains the same.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
