<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 07:20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> RocketCash Courts Teen Web Shoppers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARATOGA, Calif. (AP) -- RocketCash Corp. today launched its  
version of an online mall -- complete with security and the watchful 
eyes of parents -- that aims to turn the 20 million teen-agers 
expected to be on the Internet this year into cybershoppers. 
</P>
<P>
	RocketCash's technology enables parents to use their credit  
cards to create online spending accounts for their teenagers and 
then set their children's access to specific RocketCash merchant 
partners. 
</P>
<P>
	Parents can also limit when the account can be used and set up  
an automatic allowance to replenish the account, the Saratoga-based 
company announced in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Teens then log on to RocketCash.com and select one of the  
pre-approved merchant sites. RocketCash partners include 
Amazon.com, Beyond.com, CDNOW, iTurf's dELiAs.com, eToys, jcrew.com 
and Reel.com. 
</P>
<P>
	The RocketCash payment system completes transactions at merchant  
sites without disclosing credit card numbers or other personal 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	Chase Treasury Solutions, a division of The Chase Manhattan  
Bank, will hold funds of behalf of RocketCash until instructed to 
pay for purchases made at merchant Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Because most online purchases require credit cards, less than  
one percent of the $141 billion spent by teen-agers at the retail 
level last year was spent via e-commerce transactions, according to 
RocketCash. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 06:44:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  China Insists Crackdown Was Correct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China today ruled out any change in its position  
that the Tiananmen Square democracy protests needed to be crushed, 
saying its crackdown 10 years ago ensured the stability required 
for economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Chinese government took timely and resolute measures which  
were necessary for the development and stability of the country,'' 
Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said. ``We have already come 
to a correct conclusion over this. There will be no change 
whatsoever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of people were killed when the government sent in  
soldiers and tanks to crush seven weeks of protests centered on 
Tiananmen Square. The government said the peaceful student-led 
protests were an anti-government rebellion that threatened 
communist rule. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu said progress since the June 4, 1989, crackdown has ``proved  
convincingly that without political stability'' China would not 
have the social and economic development it enjoys today. 
</P>
<P>
	Relatives of those killed and critics of the crackdown view the  
military assault as government-sanctioned murder. In news 
conferences this week in New York and Hong Kong, they are expected 
to renew calls for compensation, an official apology and punishment 
for those responsible. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has ignored their previous pleas. Police and  
officials have stepped up surveillance and harassment of victims' 
families and dissidents ahead of the June 4 anniversary to prevent 
any public commemorations or protests. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a small number of people in and out of China who are  
scheming and staging activities aimed at inciting the overthrow of 
the Chinese government and damaging the social order,'' said Zhu, 
the Foreign Ministry spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	``The majority of people are against this, and this will not be  
well received,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether victims' families were also being subversive by  
appealing for compensation, Zhu said individuals ``can file their 
complaint according to legal procedures. However, their activities 
must observe the law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the past month, authorities have detained 60 dissidents for  
trying to commemorate the anniversary of the crackdown and are 
still holding 18, the Information Center of Human Rights and 
Democratic Movement in China said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0236 </DOCNO>
