<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farmer Unions Likely To See Runoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALINAS, Calif. (AP) -- The United Farm Workers and an  
inexperienced rival union face a runoff in their efforts to 
represent pickers and packers at Coastal Berry Co., the nation's 
largest strawberry grower, state labor officials said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the UFW and the upstart Coastal Berry of California Farm  
Worker Committee predicted victory in the votes now set for 
Thursday in Oxnard and Friday in Watsonville, where Coastal Berry 
is based. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Agricultural Labor Relations Board announced the  
runoff Tuesday after counting most of the 60 ballots that were 
contested after last week's election, which failed to give either 
union the necessary majority. 
</P>
<P>
	The ALRB said the Coastal Berry Committee has 670 votes to the  
UFW's 589. But 83 workers voted against any union representation, 
meaning the Coastal Berry Committee would need five of the six 
remaining contested ballots for outright victory. 
</P>
<P>
	However, even the upstart union's representatives don't believe  
the remaining ballots will give them the necessary margin. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are preparing for a runoff election while we are  
investigating the unresolved ballots,'' said Octavio Galarza, the 
ALRB agent in charge of the elections. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coastal Berry Committee's vice president, Sergio Leal,  
predicted that the UFW will fare even worse in the runoff. ``We 
know we will have the votes to win,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Efren Barajas, a UFW spokesman, said their union also believes  
it will win, despite interference by antiunion growers who have 
feared that a victory at Coastal Berry might spread to other berry 
fields. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't just the Committee, but the entire industry of  
strawberry growers that was doing everything possible to make sure 
we didn't win this,'' Barajas said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's president, Ernie Farley, said he simply hopes that  
the organizing would be over soon, without further disrupting the 
strawberry harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	The runoff will be the third union vote at Coastal Berry. A  
victory by the same Coastal Berry Committee last year in an 
election boycotted by the UFW was thrown out because some workers 
weren't given a chance to vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The UFW targeted Coastal Berry several years ago in hopes of  
building momentum for unions throughout the state's $600 million, 
20,000 worker strawberry industry. 
</P>
<P>
	At its most powerful in 1970, the UFW had 80,000 members, but  
dwindled to 20,000 by the death of its founder Cesar Chavez. Since 
then, it has grown to 27,000 members. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
