<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge: Case Vs. Lewis Docs Is 'Slim' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A judge refused today to dismiss a malpractice  
suit against two doctors who treated the late Boston Celtics guard 
Reggie Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, however, the judge described the case against  
the two consultants as ``very slim.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith's comments came this morning as the  
defense's case was about to start. 
</P>
<P>
	Defendants frequently ask judges for so-called ``directed  
verdicts,'' the equivalent of a dismissal. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge was referring to Drs. Mark Creager and Peter Friedman,  
not to Dr. Gilbert Mudge, the noted cardiologist and lead physician 
who cared for Lewis, who collapsed while shooting baskets in July 
1993 at the age of 27.. 
</P>
<P>
	Donna Harris-Lewis, the basketball player's widow, sued Mudge  
and the consultants, claiming they misdiagnosed and mistreated her 
husband. A third consultant settled the case for an undisclosed 
amount. 
</P>
<P>
	``Frankly, the case (against Creager and Friedman) is very slim,  
but that's why we have jurors,'' the judge said after four weeks of 
prosecution testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	The consultants' defense lawyers had suggested the doctors did  
little to care for Lewis, beyond administering tests. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said their involvement was greater than that, but said  
in Creager's case especially, the participation was minimal. 
</P>
<P>
	``The issues in my mind are not black and white or clear cut,''  
Fremont-Smith said. ``A better procedure in a case such as this is 
to allow it to go to a jury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis collapsed during a playoff game in April 1993, and saw a  
team of doctors at New England Baptist Hospital. They diagnosed him 
with a life-threatening and potentially career-ending heart 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis then sought another opinion from Mudge, who said he had a  
far less serious neurological ailment that causes fainting spells. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
