<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch To Offer Online Trades  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Merrill Lynch, joining startups like ETrade as  
well as long-established brokerages like Charles Schwab, announced 
today it is creating an Internet site for individuals to buy and 
sell stocks for $29.95 a trade. The nation's largest brokerage said 
the site will begin operating in December and will also allow users 
to purchase mutual funds, bonds and other securities. The move 
poses a big risk for Merrill Lynch, which makes billions of dollars 
annually through full-fee commissions on stock and other trades and 
depends on its network of 15,000 brokers for its customer base. 
Merrill Lynch stock was down 8 3/4 at 75 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	ETrade Is Buying Telebanc  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Online broker ETrade will merge with  
online banker Telebanc Financial Corp., creating the first purely 
Internet-based company uniting banking and brokerage services. 
ETrade will acquire Telebanc in a stock transaction worth about 
$1.8 billion. ETrade made its name as a stock brokerage but has 
been trying to diversify. With Telebanc in its fold, ETrade has 
moved closer to becoming a full-service financial site, offering a 
range of online services for all sorts of transactions. 

</P>
<P>
	Car-Hauler Talks Resume  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Negotiators for the Teamsters union and  
companies that haul new cars to auto showrooms resumed contract 
talks today aimed at averting a strike that could mean long delays 
in the delivery of some models. ``We think we're making some 
progress,'' said union president James P. Hoffa. Ian Hunter, chief 
negotiator for the management of the National Automobile 
Transporters labor division said the negotiations were going, 
``slow, but steady.'' Following a post-midnight bargaining session, 
Hoffa announced that today's 12:01 a.m. EDT strike deadline was 
extended for 24 hours to discuss management's ``11th hour'' 
economic proposal. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Mixed; Dow Up 36.52  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks closed higher today as  
investors put their money into companies whose fortunes rise along 
with a growing economy. But worries that the economy is expanding 
too rapidly held the overall market lower for much of the day. The 
Dow Jones industrial average closed up 36.52 at 10,596.26. Broader 
stock indicators closed lower. The technology-laden Nasdaq 
composite index fell 57.98 to 2,412.54. 

</P>
