<P>
	Manufacturers Spark Inflation Fears  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A report by the nation's manufacturers of the  
first rise in prices for raw materials in 16 months sparked 
concerns in financial markets today inflation is heating up. 
Reports indicated the first monthly decline in nearly a year in a 
key gauge of future economic activity and a big drop in 
construction spending, but continued strength in the industrial 
economy. The National Association of Purchasing Management said its 
monthly index of business activity rose to 55.2 in May from 52.8 in 
April. Unexpected, however, was the large rise in the association's 
price index, which jumped to 52.2 in May from 49.9 in April. 

</P>
<P>
	Testimony Resumes in Microsoft Case  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Beginning final testimony in the Microsoft  
trial, the government sought today to use an economist as a lens to 
focus the judge's attention on the software giant's alleged 
aggression toward rivals. As he opened the rebuttal phase of the 
lengthy antitrust trial after a 13-week recess, economist Franklin 
Fisher testified that Microsoft's actions -- such as spending 
millions to create Internet software, then giving it away -- were 
illogical unless its intent was to protect its Windows monopoly. 
Microsoft shares were trading lower at 78 1/2, down 2 3/16. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Airlines Raising Domestic Fares  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The cost of flying to your favorite vacation spot  
is up almost 11 percent this year after another fare increase from 
the major airlines at the start of the summer travel season. The 
third fare increase of 1999 is expected to stick since Northwest 
Airlines has gone along with a 4 percent increase levied by 
Continental Airlines last week. American, U.S. Airways, Delta, 
United and TWA then followed the competition's lead by raising 
fares. Stock for AMR Corp., the parent of American, was up $2.18 3/4 
at $67.25 a share, as was Delta's, up $1.56 1/4 at $58.93 3/4 and 
Continental was up $1.62 1/2 at 40.87 1/2. But UAL Corp., the parent of 
United, saw its stock fall as did TWA's. 

</P>
<P>
	Farmer Unions Likely To See Runoff  
</P>
<P>
	SALINAS, Calif. (AP) -- The United Farm Workers and an  
inexperienced rival union face a runoff in their efforts to 
represent pickers and packers at Coastal Berry Co., the nation's 
largest strawberry grower, state labor officials said today. Both 
the UFW and the upstart Coastal Berry of California Farm Worker 
Committee predicted victory in the votes now set for Thursday and 
Friday. The state Agricultural Labor Relations Board announced the 
runoff after counting most of the 60 ballots that were contested 
after last week's election, which failed to give either union the 
necessary majority. 

</P>
<P>
	Avondale May Accept Litton Offer  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Avondale Industries Inc., a major Navy  
shipbuilder, is prepared to accept a $500 million cash buyout offer 
from defense contractor Litton Industries Inc., but is giving a 
rival bidder two days to top it. Avondale earlier agreed to merge 
with Newport News Shipbuilding in a $470 million stock swap deal. 
Avondale said today the Litton offer, which amounts to $39.50 per 
share, is a better deal. Avondale said it has given Newport News 48 
hours notice of its intention to go with the Litton deal. 

</P>
<P>
	Banks Merging in $5.3 Billion Deal  
</P>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- AmSouth Bancorp plans to buy First  
American Corp. in a $5.3 billion stock deal, creating one the 
largest banks in the Southeast. The deal will create a bank with 
$40 billion in assets and 680 branches in nine Southeastern states, 
including the fast-growing markets of Tennessee and Florida. The 
acquisition was originally worth $6.3 billion, but investors pushed 
shares of AmSouth down more than 13 percent today. 

</P>
<P>
	Brit. Utility Buys Connecticut Firm  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Yorkshire Water PLC is buying Connecticut-based  
water supplier, Aquarion Co., for $440 million and hopes to make 
additional acquisitions in the United States. The cash deal is 
Yorkshire Water's first venture into the U.S. market, where the 
likelihood of consolidation offers greater opportunities than in 
Britain's more mature water treatment industry, a chief executive 
said. The principal business of Aquarion is to provide water for a 
population of more than 141,000 customers in Connecticut and New 
York. It also has real estate and timber processing interests. 

</P>
