<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 17:20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wynalda in Blockbuster MLS Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The Miami Fusion, struggling on the field and at  
the gate, upgraded both areas Tuesday by acquiring Eric Wynalda, 
the United States' leading career scorer, and Brazilian forward 
Welton as part of a four-team deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Wynalda, Welton and Colombian defender Arley Palacios were sent  
to the Fusion by the New York-New Jersey MetroStars, who had 
acquired Wynalda and Welton in separate deals earlier Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The MetroStars obtained Welton from the Los Angeles Galaxy for  
defender Roy Myers, and gained Wynalda's rights from San Jose to 
conclude an earlier deal that sent Raul Diaz Arce and Marcelo Vega 
to the Clash. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange, the MetroStars received the ``marquee'' player  
allocation Miami had been owed when midfielder Carlos Valderrama 
was reassigned to Tampa Bay. That could wind up becoming former 
German national team captain Lothar Matthaeus, a 38-year-old 
sweeper whose career with Bayern Munich apparently is over. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is only the first step in a very ambitious plan to shape  
the MetroStars into the marquee club our fans deserve,'' MetroStars 
general manager Charlie Stillitano said. 
</P>
<P>
	The big winner Tuesday was the Fusion, who have struggled  
through much of its 1 1/2 seasons in Major League Soccer despite 
Miami's multiethnic community and a history of drawing well for 
international games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were able to meet our immediate needs and do so in a time  
frame that allows us to impact the standings now,'' Fusion managing 
director Doug Hamilton said. ``Quite honestly, though we may have 
been able to use that allocation for an international star, we 
added three players to the roster that all have the ability to 
change the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Fusion (4-8) rank last in attendance with an 8,461 average  
and had lost five straight games before last Saturday's 2-1 win 
over Tampa Bay. They are tied for fourth in the Eastern Conference 
with just eight points and have given up a league-high 23 goals. 
</P>
<P>
	There also was the highly publicized feud between Valderrama and  
coach Ivo Wortmann, who accused his midfielder of ignoring his game 
plan and undermining his authority. Wortmann exiled Valderrama on 
April 15, and MLS commissioner Doug Logan reassigned the Colombian 
to Tampa Bay eight days later. 
</P>
<P>
	Welton and Palacios are expected to be available for Saturday  
night's game at Tampa Bay. Wynalda is out until September after 
tearing knee ligaments last March while playing for Mexican team 
Leon. 
</P>
<P>
	Wynalda, 29, has 32 goals in 102 games of international  
competition, including three World Cups. He also scored the first 
goal in MLS history as San Jose beat D.C. United in the league's 
inaugural game in 1996. In three seasons with the Clash, he had 21 
goals and 29 assists. 
</P>
<P>
	Welton, 24, has struggled this season after ranking third among  
MLS scorers last year. He had 17 goals and 11 assists for the 
Galaxy in 1998, but has no goals and one assist in nine games this 
year. The Brazilian has 31 goals and 21 assists in three MLS 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Palacios, who has played 32 games in two seasons for the  
MetroStars, gives Miami a rugged central defender to replace the 
injured Wade Webber. His arrival reunites him with Fusion leading 
scorer Diego Serna, a former teammate at Colombian club 
Independiente Medellin. 
</P>
<P>
	To reach the MLS limit of four international players, the Fusion  
also announced they would waive Trinidadian forward Mickey Trotman. 
</P>
<P>
	The MetroStars, left with an open roster spot for an  
international player, could be close to landing Matthaeus, who 
guided Germany to the 1990 World Cup title, is the career leader 
with 135 international games and fought repeatedly with former 
German and Bayern star forward Juergen Klinsmann, who also was 
coveted by MLS before his retirement last July. 
</P>
<P>
	Matthaeus told German media Sunday that he has received an offer  
from the MetroStars. According to published reports, he wants to 
move to New York to be with his girlfriend and will meet later this 
week with MLS vice president Ivan Gazidis. 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles, the arrival of Myers and Mexican forward Carlos  
Hermosillo should bolster an attack that has fallen from first in 
MLS last season to last. The Galaxy has scored just seven goals in 
11 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Myers will make his Galaxy debut June 6 against Kansas City.  
Hermosillo, who has scored 300 goals in Mexico's top league, was 
given an additional week to rest following the end of the Mexican 
season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
