<HEADLINE> Wheelchair-Bound Mom Charged Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANDUSKY, Ohio (AP) -- A woman who uses a wheelchair and was  
accused of endangering her daughter by wheeling around on city 
streets with the girl strapped to her lap is in trouble again -- 
this time for allegedly operating the chair recklessly on a street. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said they received a complaint that a woman was forcing  
cars to swerve to avoid hitting her. Officers saw Kelly Dillery, in 
her wheelchair, swerve from the edge of the street into the middle, 
said Robert Runner, assistant police chief. 
</P>
<P>
	Police on Friday charged Ms. Dillery, 31, with being a  
pedestrian in the street. She could be fined $100 if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Dillery was convicted of the same charge in January. In  
March, she was acquitted of a charge that she put her 5-year-old 
daughter in danger by strapping the girl to her lap and riding in 
the street. 
</P>
<P>
	Her attorney did not return a message seeking comment on the  
latest charge Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Dillery, who has muscular dystrophy, has said she sometimes  
has to travel in the street because not all sidewalks are 
accessible to her wheelchair. 
  	   	
</P>
