<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Devers, Marsh Out of Pro Track Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) -- Gail Devers, the two-time Olympic women's  
100-meter gold medalist, and Mike Marsh, the 1992 Olympic 200-meter 
champion, have withdrawn from Sunday's inaugural TFA Pro 
Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers said Tuesday that Devers still was not recovered from  
a hamstring injury that sidelined her all of last year. The reason 
for Marsh's withdrawal was not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Devers, the 1992 and 1996 Olympic champion, was scheduled to  
face 1997 world champion Marion Jones in the 100 and was Marsh was 
to oppose 1996 Olympic gold medalist and world record-holder 
Michael Johnson and Prefontaine Classic winner Maurice Greene in 
the 200. 
</P>
<P>
	Devers was replaced by Merlene Frazer of Jamaica and Marsh by  
Obadele Thompson of Barbados. Thompson is also entered in the 100. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dropouts include American record-holder Sheila Hudson in  
the women's triple jump (knee), Patricia Girard of France (fitness) 
and Lacena Golding of Jamaica (no reason) in the women's 100 
hurdles, and Olga Kaliturina of Russia (Achilles') in the women's 
high jump. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Track and Field Association assigned permanent  
numbers to athletes competing in the ProSeries debut event at 
Mitchel Athletic Complex. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Johnson got No. 24, representing his choice of  
events, the 200 and 400. Jones received No. 20, the number she wore 
for North Carolina's basketball team that won the 1994 NCAA 
championship, and 800-meter specialist Joetta Clark was given No. 
4, since her goal is to make her fourth Olympic team in 2000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
