<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trial Ordered in School Threat Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT HURON, Mich. (AP) -- Two 13-year-old boys accused with two  
other teen-agers of plotting a massacre at their middle school 
after the rampage in Colorado will stand trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge James Corden ruled Tuesday that he saw enough evidence of  
a conspiracy to commit murder and bound over Daniel Fick and 
Jonathan McDonald for trial. A trial date was not immediately set. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar hearing for co-defendants Justin Schnepp and Jedaiah  
``David'' Zinzo, both 14, was held last week. A ruling in their 
case was pending. 
</P>
<P>
	The older boys are charged as adults; the younger two are  
charged in juvenile court. 
</P>
<P>
	All four could face life in prison if convicted. However,  
because the 13-year-olds are charged in juvenile court, a judge 
could also decide to sentence them to juvenile detention, where 
they could be held up to age 21. 
</P>
<P>
	The students' classmates said the defendants talked of staging a  
robbery to obtain firearms, seizing the Holland Woods Middle School 
office, using the public address system to call an assembly in the 
gym and then slaughtering students and teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say they foiled the plot after classmates reported  
it to school officials. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
