<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 13:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arkansas Has Inside Track at NCAAs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- Track and field teams have a special goal  
each season -- sweep the conference and NCAA titles in cross 
country, indoors and outdoors. 
</P>
<P>
	Winning all six is never easy. But Arkansas, the dominant team  
the past 25 years under John McDonnell, has accomplished the feat 
four times. The only other school to do it was UTEP, three times 
during the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	This weekend, in the NCAA Outdoor Championships at Boise State,  
the Razorbacks will be going for No. 5, their first since the 
1993-94 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's special,'' McDonnell said, ``but it's not routine. If  
it got routine, you wouldn't win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Routine or not, McDonnell has been perhaps the most successful  
college track coach in history. 
</P>
<P>
	Since becoming the Razorbacks' coach in 1972, McDonnell has won  
25 consecutive conference cross country championships since 1974. 
He has won nine NCAA cross country titles, all since 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	He has also won 19 indoor conference crowns the past 20 years,  
15 of the past 16 NCAA indoor championships, 17 of the past 18 
outdoor conference titles and eight NCAA outdoor crowns, including 
the past seven. 
</P>
<P>
	That's an astounding total of 61 conference titles and 32 NCAA  
championships. One hundred overall titles isn't far off. 
</P>
<P>
	The Razorbacks are heavily favored to stretch their outdoor  
winning streak to eight -- one shy of Southern California's men's 
record of nine in a row from 1935-43 -- in the 78th championships 
beginning Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The women's title figures to be a three-way battle among  
defending champion Texas; LSU, which had its 11-year winning streak 
snapped in 1998; and UCLA. 
</P>
<P>
	``The NCAA is the final big dance,'' McDonnell said. ``The  
conference was the minidance. We're ready to dance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As usual, the Razorbacks are loaded with distance runners and  
jumpers, led by Seneca Lassiter, the two-time defending champion at 
1,500 meters, and Matt Kerr, last year's winner in the 3,000-meter 
steeplechase. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Lassiter has won twice in a row and has run two  
outstanding times this season -- 3 minutes, 37.23 seconds and 
3:37.29 -- he is expected to be seriously challenged by Pac-10 
champion Bernard Lagat of Washington State. Lagat beat Lassiter in 
the NCAA indoor mile in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerr faces strong opposition from sophomore Carlos Suarez of  
UTEP. Even if Lassiter and Kerr don't win their specialties -- they 
should still score highly -- Arkansas also has many other potential 
point producers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lassiter also is running the 800, with Sharif Karie in the 1,500  
and 5,000, James Karanu in the 800 and 1,500, Mike Power in the 
5,000, Andrew Begley in the 10,000, Melvin Lister in the long jump 
and triple jump, Lavar Miller in the high jump and triple jump, 
Kenny Evans in the high jump, Sam Glover in the 400 hurdles, 
D'Marcus Brown in the 110 hurdles and Marcus Clavelle in the shot 
put. 
</P>
<P>
	No other team can match that depth.  
</P>
<P>
	The other men's defending champions are BYU's Leonard  
Myles-Mills (100), USC's Jerome Davis (400), Stanford's Brad Hauser 
(10,000) and Toby Stevenson (pole vault), South Carolina's Brad 
Snyder (shot put), SMU's Libor Charfreitag (hammer throw) and 
Arizona's Esko Mikkola (javelin). 
</P>
<P>
	The women's team championship came down to the final 1,600 relay  
last year before Texas ended LSU's record streak. This time, UCLA 
also figures to be in the mix, with the title to be decided in the 
sprints, hurdles and relays. The three teams are going against each 
other heavily in all three. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas has defending champions in Suziann Reid (400) and Erin  
Aldrich (high jump), plus its 400 and 1,600 relay teams. The 
Longhorns' Tanya Jarrett also is favored in the 400 hurdles. 
</P>
<P>
	LSU had no individual champions last year, but now has potential  
winners in Peta-Gaye Dowdie (100 and 200) and Joyce Bates (100 
hurdles). UCLA has two strong relay teams, plus Shakedia Jones in 
the 100 and 200, Joanna Hayes in both hurdles and shot put and 
discus favorite Seilalu Sua. 
</P>
<P>
	Other returning champions are Georgia's Debbie Ferguson (100 and  
200), Villanova's Carmen Douma (1,500), Cal Poly-San Luis Obispo's 
Bianca Maran (pole vault), George Mason's Angie Brown (long jump) 
and Pittsburgh's Trecia Smith (triple jump). 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's program includes finals in the men's discus and  
10,000 and women's hammer throw and long jump, semifinals in seven 
events, preliminaries in two events and the first five events of 
the decathlon. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
