<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 23:40:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Berry Pickers Head to Polls Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALINAS, Calif. (AP) -- More than 1,500 pickers and packers will  
return to makeshift polls in California's dusty strawberry fields 
this week for a runoff vote on which union they want to represent 
them -- the once powerful United Farm Workers or an inexperienced 
rival. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Agricultural Labor Relations Board announced the  
runoff Tuesday after counting the final 40 eligible votes cast in 
last week's election. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither union had the necessary majority to represent farm  
workers at Coastal Berry, the nation's largest employer of 
strawberry workers, state labor officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coastal Berry of California Farm Worker Committee had 670  
votes to the UFW's 589, labor officials said. Another 83 workers 
voted against any union representation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got most of the votes. Next time we'll get even more,''  
said Sergio Leal, vice president of the Coastal Berry Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Efren Barajas, a UFW spokesman, said organizers will continue to  
fight for victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't just the committee, but the entire industry of  
strawberry growers that was doing everything possible to make sure 
we didn't win this,'' Barajas said. 
</P>
<P>
	At its most powerful in 1970, the UFW had 80,000 members. But  
the figure dwindled to 20,000 by the time the union's legendary 
founder, Cesar Chavez, died in 1993. Since then, it has grown to 
27,000 members. 
</P>
<P>
	The UFW targeted Coastal Berry several years ago in hopes of  
building momentum for unions throughout the state's $600 million, 
20,000-worker strawberry industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's president, Ernie Farley, said he simply looks  
forward to a resolution so he can focus on the strawberry harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	``I credit my workers,'' Farley said. ``They're doing their  
jobs, undistracted by all this labor organizing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
