<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greene Explains Attack on Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Carolina Panthers linebacker Kevin Greene  
said Tuesday he was acting on instinct when he attacked one of the 
team's assistant coaches during a game last December. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everybody and their brother out there who had ever  
played competitive sports at one time or another probably wanted to 
jerk a knot in some coach's tail,'' Greene said after the Panthers 
finished a practice on the opening day of their third minicamp of 
the offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene had been largely silent on the subject of his attack of  
former Carolina linebackers coach Kevin Steele on the sidelines 
during the Panthers' home loss to Washington on Dec. 13. 
</P>
<P>
	One day after the attack the Panthers suspended Greene without  
pay for one game, costing him $117,647.05, the equivalent of one 
game check from his 1998 salary of $2 million. Greene released a 
brief statement that night saying he was wrong, he regretted his 
actions and that he respected Steele. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene had a different tone Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think it was 50-50, both of our faults,'' he said. ``I don't  
think it was 100 percent my fault or 100 percent his fault. I think 
if I didn't have the passion, if I didn't have a love and intensity 
and desire for the game, maybe I wouldn't have reacted. Maybe I 
would have just said, `Hey, you know, who cares?' I might have just 
walked off. But that's not me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greene, Carolina's starting left outside linebacker, got into a  
heated discussion with Steele after the Redskins drove for long 
touchdowns on their first three possessions. Teammates said Greene 
was upset because someone had given him the wrong call on the 
Redskins' third score, a 5-yard burst up the middle by Skip Hicks. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene, a 14-year NFL veteran, jumped up from the bench, lunged  
at Steele, grabbed him by the jacket just below the neck with both 
hands and began shoving him backwards before coaches and players 
separated the two. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene had cultivated an image as a team leader and was viewed  
in the community as one of the team's more popular players. Many 
fans said after the attack that they had lost respect for him, but 
when Greene was asked Tuesday if he was concerned about the 
public's perception of him, he tried to make light of the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure someone did -- at one time or another through high  
school or pee wee football -- probably want to jerk a knot in some 
coach's tail,'' he said. ``So I did it for all those guys so they 
can help pay my fine. Send your dollars here to Ericsson Stadium.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steele, who had interviewed for the head coaching job at Baylor  
shortly before the attack, subsequently got the job and left 
Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene, 36, a four-time Pro Bowl selection, is trying to adjust  
to a new linebacking position with the Panthers this season and is 
not considered a lock to be a starter. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
