<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Overturns Award vs. Suzuki </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) -- The Missouri Supreme Court on Tuesday  
overturned a $37 million trial award to woman paralyzed in a car 
accident because the vehicle manufacturer wasn't allowed to present 
evidence questioning the reliability of a safety test. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 6-1 decision, the panel ruled that at an earlier trial,  
Suzuki Motor Corp. was not allowed to present government reports 
noting that a Consumer Reports test used by the plaintiffs to show 
the vehicle, a Samurai, had defects was flawed. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Katie Rodriguez, 34, the passenger who has won two  
settlements from separate juries in the last three years only to 
see them overturned on appeal, provided a 1988 study published in 
Consumer Reports magazine that found that the Samurai would roll 
over under certain ``ordinary emergency steering maneuvers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Suzuki claimed Ms. Rodriguez was hurt because she did not use  
her seat belt, that the driver had been drinking and that any 
vehicle would have rolled over. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Rodriguez told The Associated Press on Tuesday the Supreme  
Court's decision to remand the case back to the trial court was 
fine by her. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not much has changed except on paper,'' Ms Rodriguez said.  
``It's just another hurdle. I'm a strong woman, a very strong 
woman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	George Ball, an attorney for Suzuki, also expressed  
determination that the company would continue to defend itself in 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to defend this case vigorously in the third  
Rodriguez trial,'' Ball said in a telephone interview from Long 
Beach, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, a jury awarded Rodriquez $90 million in damages as a  
result of a February 1990 accident in which she was a front seat 
passenger. The vehicle was driven by a friend when it hit a curb 
and rolled. A judge later reduced the award to $40 million before 
the Supreme Court ordered a new trial because of questions about 
alcohol consumption by those involved in the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1997 retrial, jurors awarded Rodriguez $37 million.  
</P>
<P>
	But the state's high court found the second trial court failed  
to allow the introduction of reports issued by the National Highway 
Transportation Safety Administration that raised questions about 
the safety testing methodology. 
</P>
<P>
	The Circuit Court of St. Louis City ruled that the government  
reports were hearsay, but the Supreme Court said that federal 
records are relevant and that omitting them was prejudicial. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly the reports go to the heart of the plaintiff's case  
-- the existence of a rollover design defect -- and this reason alone 
may justify reversal,'' the court said. ``Additionally, the fact 
that the reports were generated by a government entity that is 
presumably independent and unbiased and whose ultimate function is 
to protect the public by seeking out product defects, if they 
exist, gave the reports great credibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court also ruled that the trial court was in error  
because it did not allow Suzuki to cross examine an expert witness 
for Ms. Rodriguez about the testing methodology. 
</P>
<P>
	In the lone dissenting opinion, Judge Ronnie White scolded the  
court for sending the case back to the trial court for a third 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kathyn Rodruguez is a real person. She is thirty-four years  
old and has spent the last nine years of her life paralyzed from 
the shoulders down,'' White wrote. ``While this does not mean she 
automatically deserves anything from Suzuki, what she deserves from 
this court is the same thing it owes all Missouri litigants: a 
speedy, just and final resolution of her claim.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
