<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Students Return to Columbine High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- The backpacks dotting Columbine High  
School's hallways have been there since panicked students abandoned 
them and ran from gunfire and terror nearly six weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	A substitute teacher left her purse. Others left keys or books.  
</P>
<P>
	Today, most of the nearly 2,000 students and faculty were to  
return for the first time and retrieve items they left behind April 
20, when they ran from the building as Eric Harris and Dylan 
Klebold opened fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Kaufman, spokesman for Jefferson County Public Schools,  
said students were assigned specific times to pick up their 
belongings in groups of 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Some items are being held as evidence and some areas remain  
off-limits. Things left in the commons area outside the cafeteria, 
where the attack began, or the library, where most people died, 
were taken to the auditorium. 
</P>
<P>
	``The library is still considered a crime scene,'' Kaufman said.  
</P>
<P>
	Harris and Klebold killed 12 students and a teacher and wounded  
21 others before taking their own lives. Columbine students 
finished the school year at nearby Chatfield High School. 
</P>
<P>
	The return was expected to be emotional and counselors were  
called in. Parents were also invited, said school spokeswoman 
Marilyn Saltzman. 
</P>
<P>
	The district will spend the summer renovating rooms damaged by  
bombs, bullets and water. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the dispute over how to memorialize the 15 deaths  
simmered as 13 crosses made a brief return to a hill overlooking 
the school in a Memorial Day tribute. 
</P>
<P>
	Carpenter Greg Zanis, whose crosses have been the subject of  
controversy since they were first erected, put them up again Monday 
on the hill overlooking the school for a brief tribute. He then 
moved them to private property, where they will remain until a 
decision is made on how to remember those killed in the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	State officials have promised to build a memorial in Clement  
Park, but the design has not been finalized. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
