<DOCNO> APW19990601.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 14:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brack Had Everyone's Number at Indy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- For Kenny Brack, the final laps of the Indy 500  
came down to a simple matter of numbers and some long division. 
</P>
<P>
	Brack and his pit crew, headed by feisty car owner A.J. Foyt,  
had the calculations figured to the last decimal point, and it all 
added up to leader Robby Gordon running out of fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	And when that happened, it meant Brack would win the world's  
most famous car race. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew he would have to have to pit again,'' Brack said  
Tuesday, still aglow in his victory. ``He went in at lap 164. We 
went in at 169. To go 36 laps, you can't do it unless you have a 
bigger tank.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Gordon was equipped with the standard 35-gallon tank. So  
Brack was comfortable with his situation. It was just a matter of 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had to pit,'' Brack said. ``We weren't that worried.''  
</P>
<P>
	Still, auto racing is all about speed so Brack decided in the  
final laps to step on the gas -- since he had some left and Gordon 
did not. 
</P>
<P>
	There was, after all, the possibility that, despite a fuel  
indicator pointing to empty, Gordon wouldn't pull in, gambling that 
a yellow flag would come up at the end, protecting his position. It 
never did. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he had a yellow, obviously he'd be able to make it,'' Brack  
said. ``I was faster at the end. A yellow before that last lap 
would not have been so good. I was a second behind when he pulled 
in. It was a relief. After that, it was a cruise to the flag.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his headphone, Brack heard Foyt screaming, ``We won this  
thing!'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was a payoff for careful planning by Foyt and Brack and the  
rest of their team. The Swedish driver was cautious with his last 
fill-up of fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were economy driving after the last pit stop,'' Brack said.  
``By 193 or 194, we had saved enough to go faster at the end. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was conservative at the start. I was leading. I didn't want  
to do anything stupid to keep the lead. We kept pace. I knew there 
would be more yellows and a lot of stuff happening. I stayed on my 
pace. I didn't take unnecessary risks at the start, in the middle 
or at the end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His victory was worth $1,465,190, the second biggest prize in  
Indy history. 
</P>
<P>
	``To win a race like this, you have to prepare every little  
detail, when to take risks and when not to take risks,'' Brack 
said. ``You don't win by taking chances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And how much fuel was left in Brack's tank at the end?  
</P>
<P>
	``About two gallons,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	More than enough, it turned out.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
