<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Candidate Asks for Calm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia's presidential frontrunner  
appealed for peace during campaign stops in two provinces Tuesday 
as her supporters fought with rivals elsewhere in clashes that left 
at least eight injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Megawati Sukarnoputri, the daughter of Indonesia's founding  
president, Sukarno, is the favorite in Monday's parliamentary 
elections. 
</P>
<P>
	She first visited East Timor, where violence has risen among  
factions fighting for and against independence with the approach of 
an Aug. 8 referendum on the future of the former Portuguese colony, 
invaded by Indonesia in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is impossible for acts of violence to resolve the problem  
of East Timor,'' Megawati told 3,000 supporters. ``I hope the 
ballot process will be conducted properly and the Timorese can 
decide their own future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Megawati, 52, later campaigned in Ambon, where violence among  
rival Muslims and Christians has left more than 300 dead this year. 
</P>
<P>
	About 90 percent of Indonesia's 210 million people are Muslim.  
Some conservative Islamic religious leaders have said they oppose a 
woman becoming head of state, despite Megawati's wide popularity. 
</P>
<P>
	But as she campaigned, witnesses said clashes erupted in  
Ujungpandang, on Sulawesi island, 840 miles northeast of Jakarta. 
</P>
<P>
	Megawati supporters tore down a sign hanging from a private  
Muslim university that read: ``Are Muslims willing to be led by a 
woman?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Students responded by burning campaign flags emblazoned with a  
bull's head, the symbol of Megawati's party, the Indonesian 
Democratic Party for Struggle. The students halted a convoy of her 
supporters, threw rocks and damaged a car and a motorcycle. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of security officers rushed in to separate the two  
sides. 
</P>
<P>
	Megawati hopes to unseat President B.J. Habibie, the hand-picked  
successor of President Suharto, who left office last year amid mass 
demonstrations and deadly riots. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaigning for the parliamentary elections will go on for three  
more days, followed by a two-day cooling-off period before the 
voting. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of 100 electoral monitors will be led by former  
President Carter, who said Tuesday that he thinks Indonesians want 
peaceful change. 
</P>
<P>
	``Indonesians have voiced a clear commitment to a more open form  
of government and to a democratic electoral process,'' Carter said 
in a statement from Atlanta. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
