<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 19:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.C. Activist Arrested in Shootings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAMLET, N.C. (AP) -- A man who gained national notoriety when he  
held newspaper employees hostage 11 years ago was arrested Tuesday 
on murder charges, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Eddie Hatcher, 41, was taken into custody without incident while  
driving away from a house in Hamlet, about 75 miles east of 
Charlotte, Sheriff Glenn Maynor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Maynor said Hatcher was wanted in a drive-by shooting Monday  
night near Maxton, where Hatcher used to live. Investigators said 
Bryan McMillian, 19, was killed at his rural home when Hatcher 
fired into a building with a high-powered rifle. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know what the motive behind this one was,'' said  
homicide Capt. Randal Patterson. ``He shot the house. He didn't 
know what he was going to hit and probably didn't know who all was 
in the house.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hatcher also had been sought since May 19, when a man was shot  
and wounded in a convenience store in Lumberton, about 110 miles 
east of Charlotte. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatcher and Timothy Jacobs, both Tuscarora Indians, took over  
The Robesonian newspaper in Lumberton on Feb. 1, 1988. The armed 
men said they were protesting what they said was corruption in 
Robeson County government. They held hostages for 10 hours before 
surrendering. 
</P>
<P>
	The pair were acquitted of federal hostage-taking and firearms  
charges, but were later indicted on state charges. Both went to 
prison -- Hatcher for five years and Jacobs for less than three -- 
and were eventually paroled. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatcher was being held Tuesday night at a prison in Raleigh that  
has medical facilities able to treat the symptoms of AIDS, which 
Hatcher said he contracted while in prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
