<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 14:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ETrade Is Buying Telebanc </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Leading online broker ETrade Group Inc. is  
buying online banker Telebanc Financial Corp. for $1.6 billion in 
stock, creating the first purely Internet-based financial services 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the merger is complete, ETrade customers will be able to  
trade stocks, apply for mortgages and pay bills all on the same Web 
site. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company will carry the name ETrade, company  
executives said Tuesday. Customers will access Telebanc's banking 
services through links on ETrade's main site. 
</P>
<P>
	ETrade, based in Palo Alto, Calif., made its name as a stock  
brokerage but has been trying to diversify. The company already 
sells mutual funds and has a deal with online mortgage provider 
E-Loan Inc. that lets ETrade's one-million-plus customers apply for 
home mortgages online. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Arlington, Va.-based Telebanc in its fold, ETrade has  
moved closer to becoming a full-service financial site, offering a 
range of online services for all sorts of transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	Telebanc Financial is the holding company for Telebank, one of  
several Internet-based banks that serve customers without any 
actual branch offices. Since the banks don't have to pay for 
branches, they say they can operate more inexpensively -- and thus 
pay higher deposit rates and charge lower fees -- than traditional 
banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Spurred by the competition, established brokerage firms like  
Charles Schwab now offer online trading, and brokerage giant 
Merrill Lynch announced Tuesday that it will be online by December. 
But the non-Internet based firms may charge more for services -- 
Merrill Lynch, for example, plans to charge $29.95 a trade, 
compared to ETrade's $14.95. 
</P>
<P>
	Established ``brick-and-mortar'' banks and brokerages still  
control a substantial portion of the financial services market. But 
as those firms start to add Internet services, millions of new 
customers will try online finance, and the Internet-based firms 
will then lure them with cheaper prices, said Mitchell H. Caplan, 
Telebanc's vice chairman, president and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Internet banking is not yet really known nationwide or  
worldwide,'' Caplan said. ``They educate ... and we then go and 
scoop up those consumers with the better-value equation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though most online brokers offer some limited banking services,  
only one other company has tried to combine large-scale Internet 
banking and brokerage. That company, Royal Bank of Canada, owns 
Bull &AMP; Bear Securities Inc. and Telebanc rival Security First 
Network Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	But Telebanc is much larger than Security First and its other  
rivals, Caplan said. He said the company has almost 70,000 customer 
accounts and is bigger than the next five Internet banks combined. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the merger agreement, Telebanc shareholders will get 2.1  
shares of ETrade common stock for each share of Telebanc common 
stock. Officials said the merger should close this fall, pending 
regulatory and stockholder approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of ETrade fell Tuesday in trading on the Nasdaq Stock  
Market, reducing the value of the deal, which was worth $1.8 
billion when it was announced. Shares fell $5.18 3/4, or nearly 12 
percent, to $39.31 1/4, while shares of Telebanc rose $8, or 12 
percent, to $74.50, also on the Nasdaq. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 11:40:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Set in Utah Polygamist Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The practice of polygamy was in the  
spotlight today as attorneys selected a jury to hear the case 
against a man accused of making his underage niece his 15th wife 
and having sex with her. 
</P>
<P>
	David O. Kingston is charged with incest and unlawful sexual  
contact with a minor, but his case also is attracting international 
attention to Utah's peculiar and thriving polygamy practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Kingston was in 3rd District Court this morning, accompanied by  
his first wife, Sharli Rae Jenkins Kingston. Kingston took lengthy 
notes during the beginning of jury selection and made eye contact 
with each of the prospective jurors. 
</P>
<P>
	By noon, the jury of eight men and one alternate -- picked from a  
pool of 50 prospective jurors -- was seated and opening arguments 
were scheduled for this afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, defense attorney Stephen McCaughey made two motions  
which were denied by Judge David Young. McCaughey asked to call 
prosecutor Dane Nolan as a witness in the case, and he also 
requested that information about an alleged beating given to the 
girl by her father be prohibited from the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	McCaughey said Nolan, who interviewed the girl twice, would have  
critical information about alleged inconsistencies in the girl's 
story. Calling Nolan as a witness would have disqualified him to 
serve as an attorney in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	McCaughey has said the the niece has given different stories  
about how many times they had sex. Prosecutors say it happened four 
times in 1997 and 1998; the defense denied they had sex at all. 
</P>
<P>
	Young denied that motion and also ruled that the alleged beating  
could be discussed during the trial. The judge said McCaughey could 
raise his objections to the second decision on rebuttal. 
</P>
<P>
	David Kingston is an accountant for the secretive Kingston clan  
based in Salt Lake County, which has as many as 1,000 members and 
business assets worth up to $150 million. The clan shares many of 
the beliefs of other polygamous groups in the state but stands 
apart, former members say, in practicing incest. 
</P>
<P>
	The case began last summer when the girl, then 16, showed up at  
a rural gas station just south of the Idaho state line. She said 
she had run seven miles from a family ranch where her father had 
beaten her for trying to leave a forced marriage with her uncle. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl's father, John Kingston, pleaded no contest to child  
abuse and could get up to five years in prison at his sentencing 
June 29. 
</P>
<P>
	David Kingston, 32, could get up to five years in prison and a  
$10,000 fine on each of four counts if convicted. He has rejected 
all proposed plea bargains and insists he is innocent, his attorney 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Modern-day polygamists, unlike 70 percent of Utah's population,  
are not members of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints. 
But their practices have roots in the early church, when founder 
Joseph Smith sanctioned plural marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	The early Mormons' practice of plural marriage was renounced by  
the church in 1890, after the U.S. Congress passed tough 
anti-bigamy laws. Then Congress insisted the anti-polygamy clause 
be included in the Utah Constitution when Utah was granted 
statehood in 1896. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
