<HEADLINE> Spurs Might Have Arena Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- A Baptist youth convention planned for the  
Alamodome on June 25-26 could conflict with a San Antonio Spurs 
home game should the team reach the NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The convention is expected to draw 15,000 to 20,000 people to  
the dome on a Friday and Saturday, both eyed as potential game 
dates in the finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Spurs executives said Tuesday they have been negotiating with  
all parties involved to try to work out a compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has to get solved in at least the next week to two weeks.  
We don't have much time beyond that,'' said Russ Bookbinder, Spurs 
vice president of business operations. 
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio leads the Portland Trail Blazers 2-0 in the  
best-of-7 Western Conference finals. The winner advances to the NBA 
Finals to face the winner of the Indiana-New York Eastern 
Conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has to get settled because we're not going to give up a  
home playoff date, from a competitive standpoint. And I think the 
NBA is working towards a solution,'' Bookbinder said. 
</P>
<P>
	No conflict would occur if either of the current playoff series  
lasts six or seven games. But if both series finish in five games 
or less, there could be a problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Alamodome director Mike Abington said the Baptist convention was  
scheduled before it was known the playoff season would last longer 
than usual because of the NBA lockout. 
</P>
<P>
	The shortened season began in February instead of November.  
Normally, the NBA Finals are finished by June 25. 
</P>
<P>
	``San Antonio committed to the convention when there were no  
conflicts,'' Abington said. ``This conflict is a casualty of the 
NBA lockout.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
