<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religious School Subsidy Ban Upheld </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Maine (AP) -- A federal appeals court has upheld a  
Maine law that bars the state from paying students' tuition at 
religious schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Maine law, families who live in towns without public  
secondary schools may send pupils to any public or nonsectarian 
private school, with the state picking up at least part of the 
tuition. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1st Circuit Court of Appeals in Boston agreed with a lower  
judge's ruling that the state is not constitutionally required to 
extend subsidies to parochial schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Conn, a spokesman for Americans United for Separation of  
Church and State, called the ruling a landmark decision against 
school voucher proponents. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the highest federal court that has ruled on the school  
voucher issue,'' he said Tuesday. ``It's a very important 
decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court has let stand a Wisconsin program that  
provides financial help for families whose children attend 
religious schools. But the justices voted not to hear a challenge 
to the Wisconsin program and did not issue a decision or set a 
national precedent. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling in the Maine case was issued Thursday, but the  
parties involved did not learn of the decision until after the 
holiday weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Center for Law and Justice, a group founded by the  
Christian Coalition's Pat Robertson that is representing the 
plaintiffs, vowed to appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	The case began when three parents sued Maine's education  
commissioner for state money to send their children to a Catholic 
high school. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
