<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Ministers Insist on Doping Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PADERBORN, Germany (AP) -- European Union sports ministers  
threatened Tuesday to set up their own doping agency if the 
International Olympic Committee fails to accept their demands. 
</P>
<P>
	French sports minister Marie-George Buffet outlined the program  
during an informal meeting of the ministers in a German castle. 
</P>
<P>
	In comments to the German radio, she called the demands  
``nonnegotiable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Participants at the conference said there was wide agreement on  
the demands, which will be officially presented Wednesday, 
according to German Interior Minister Otto Schily, the informal 
meeting's chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Schily has been one of the sharpest critics of IOC doping  
policies. As interior minister, Schily's responsibilities include 
overseeing sports. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU sports ministers want the IOC to set up a worldwide  
doping agency by Jan. 1, 2000. The agency should be able to conduct 
drug tests without advance warning and must be able to impose 
sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency's seat must not be in Lausanne, Switzerland, which is  
also the headquarters of the IOC. The agency should be financed by 
participating governments, the ministers agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	If the IOC does not accept these conditions, the EU will set up  
its own doping agency, participants said. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU remained on a collision course with the IOC also by  
insisting on a minimum two-year ban for first-time drug offenders. 
</P>
<P>
	Several major sports, such as soccer, cycling and tennis, are  
opposed to a two-year ban, arguing that such punishment for a first 
offense would never hold up to challenges under right-to-work laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Schily was expected to meet Wednesday with Sepp Blatter,  
president of FIFA, the world governing body of soccer, and Lennart 
Johansson, president of soccer's European ruling body UEFA. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the meeting in Paderborn, Blatter said FIFA would not  
back down. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this question, there will be no compromise with FIFA. An  
automatic two-year ban will not be imposed with our approval. 
Never,'' Blatter said during a gathering of soccer officials Monday 
in Lorsch, Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	At a meeting in Lausanne in February, the 15 EU governments and  
the IOC failed to agree on a doping program. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU governments refused to allow the IOC a lead role in the  
proposed doping agency, which would supervise worldwide drug 
testing and policy and have an initial budget of $25 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 23:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
