<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mixed; Gold Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The dollar was mixed against most major currencies  
in European trading today. Gold prices fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar fell to 120.95 Japanese yen from 121.47 yen late  
Monday and also was lower against the British pound. The dollar 
rose, however, against the euro, the currency of 11 European 
nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6072, up from $1.6043, while  
the euro fell to $1.0449 from $1.0481 Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Monday included 1.5230  
Swiss francs, up from 1.5216, and 1.4800 Canadian dollars, up from 
1.4743. 
</P>
<P>
	In late trading in New York, the dollar was worth 120.73 yen,  
1.5228 Swiss francs and 1.4831 Canadian francs. The euro was worth 
$1.0448 and the British pound was worth $1.6104. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8718 German marks, up from 1.8661; 
6.2777 French francs, up from 6.2585; 1,853.07 Italian lire, up 
from 1,847.41. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $266.90 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$269.50 on Friday. London currency and commodity markets were 
closed Monday for a national holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $267.05, down from $269.95.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold fell $3.90 in Hong Kong to close at $266.25.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $4.98 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$4.90 Friday. 
  	   	
</P>
