<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Old Waverly Site of Women's US Open  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST POINT, Miss. (AP) -- Meg Mallon probably won't have to wave  
a white flag in mock surrender at Old Waverly Golf Club. 
</P>
<P>
	The 54th U.S. Women's Open figures to be a kinder, gentler  
championship when it begins Thursday in an area of Mississippi 
known as the Golden Triangle. 
</P>
<P>
	If a drive strays beyond the rough-framed fairways, it might not  
take a national search party to find it. The course is playing at 
6,431 yards to a par of 71, meaning none of the par-5s have been 
changed to a par-4. 
</P>
<P>
	Karrie Webb even complained that one of the par-5s was too  
short. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the course stays the same condition, I could see 10 under  
winning,'' Webb said. ``If the greens get harder and firmer and 
rough grows a little bit, you're going to see only a few people 
under par.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just one person under par would be an improvement from last year  
at Blackwolf Run, located in an area of Wisconsin that may as well 
have been called the Bermuda Triangle. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Se Ri Pak and amateur Jenny Chuasiriporn  
finished 72 holes in 6-over 290, the highest winning score in the 
Women's Open since Jan Stephenson won at 6 over in 1983. Only 30 
players managed to break 300 over 72 holes. 
</P>
<P>
	Pak, who went 20 holes in a playoff to win, was asked Tuesday  
how Old Waverly suited her game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pretty good,'' she said with a bright smile. ``A lot better  
than last year. Not only me, all players feel the same way, I 
think.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That wasn't the case last year at Blackwolf Run, the Pete  
Dye-design that changed from a brute to a beast when the winds 
kicked up. 
</P>
<P>
	Nancy Lopez was in a group with Mallon and Jane Geddes the first  
two rounds. Mallon hit her first drive in the right rough, hit a 
tree and eventually walked off with a 9. Geddes took a double-bogey 
6. Lopez was shaken. 
</P>
<P>
	``My caddie said to me, `Are you all right?' And I said, `I need  
two Valiums, quick!' It was horrible,'' Lopez said. ``I'm trying to 
keep my emotions, because you know what's in store for you the next 
17 holes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That threesome, with 68 victories and seven major championships  
among them, didn't hit the same green in regulation until the 14th 
hole of the second round. Lopez told this to Mallon, who replied, 
``Hey, we can play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And out came the white flags as they walked up the 18th fairway,  
laughing to keep themselves from crying. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Open prides itself on being the toughest test of golf,  
but no one is quite sure what to expect at Old Waverly. The course 
only opened 11 years ago and has never played host to a 
championship featuring the best in women's golf. 
</P>
<P>
	And no matter how the USGA wants to set up the course, it is at  
the mercy of Mother Nature. Unseasonably cool nights have kept the 
Bermuda rough from growing out of control. The fairways are ample 
and the greens are running smooth. 
</P>
<P>
	``The golf course is playing fair,'' said Dinah Shore champion  
Dottie Pepper. ``This golf course rewards good shots. It's not like 
if you hit some goofy spins off a mound, you knock it 40 feet 
coming back for par.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Webb played 18 holes Monday, the first time she has played a  
full practice round that early in the week, and was asked which 
holes scared her. 
</P>
<P>
	``After playing last year, I don't know if there are any holes  
like that,'' Webb said. ``Last year, I think the whole 18 holes 
scared me. It's definitely not as tough as Blackwolf Run, but I 
don't think any of the players wanted to see it as tough as that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Low scoring might only play to Webb's advantage. Already a  
four-time winner this year, she set the LPGA record for 72 holes 
with a 26-under 262 in the Australian Ladies Masters and won the 
Titleholders Championship at 17-under 271 last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think anyone, not even the USGA, wants to see 6 over  
win a golf tournament,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The galleries already are strong, and officials are hopeful to  
go over 100,000 for the week. The seriousness on their faces is 
indication that this is a major championship, the biggest event of 
the year in women's golf. 
</P>
<P>
	Walking across the tightly mowed fairways of Old Waverly, and  
the unusually tame rough, may have been the only thing that lulled 
players into a false sense of a security. 
</P>
<P>
	Is this really a Women's Open course?  
</P>
<P>
	``Not compared to last year, no,'' Juli Inkster said. ``This is  
not as severe as last year's course. But that's the beauty of a 
U.S. Open. It changes every year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, most players might agree that the change was for the  
better. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
