<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SFX Entertainment Buys Canadian Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Livent, the troubled Canadian company that  
produced popular Broadway musicals like ``Ragtime'' and ``Fosse,'' 
is being bought by SFX Entertainment, the nation's leading producer 
and promoter of live shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the deal were not disclosed, but news reports have  
speculated that the price could exceed $100 million. The 
transaction, which does not include Livent's headquarters in 
Toronto, will have to be approved by a New York bankruptcy court. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the latest acquisition for SFX, which has been on a  
two-year buying spree since being spun off from the hugely 
successful radio business founded by its chairman, Robert F. X. 
Sillerman. Sillerman founded the radio company SFX Broadcasting in 
1992, taking the name from a scrambling of his initials. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to all the rights for Livent's current shows, which  
include the long-running Canadian production of ``Phantom of the 
Opera,'' SFX will also acquire Livent's theaters in New York, 
Chicago and Toronto. Other recent Livent productions have included 
``Parade,'' which was just nominated for nine Tony Awards. 
</P>
<P>
	Livent filed for bankruptcy protection last November after its  
new owners, which include Hollywood mogul Michael Ovitz, said they 
discovered massive accounting fraud by Livent's original owners, 
Garth Drabinsky and Myron Gottlieb. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. authorities filed fraud and conspiracy charges against the  
two founders in January, but they have refused to appear in court. 
Drabinsky and Gottleib have remained in Canada and deny any 
wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	SFX is the largest stager and promoter of concerts and other  
live entertainment in the United States. It owns 82 venues 
throughout the country as well as concert promoters like Bill 
Graham Presents and a sports marketing company. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990601.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 13:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gators Receiver Has Tough Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- John Capel ran the fastest 200-meter  
time in the United States this year. He is probably only the 
fourth-best wide receiver on the Florida football team. 
</P>
<P>
	It should seem clear where his future lies.  
</P>
<P>
	But nobody should forget that at Florida, a fourth-string  
receiver garners much more day-in, day-out attention than a 
world-class sprinter. 
</P>
<P>
	With the 2000 Olympics taking place in September, the heart of  
football season, Capel faces a tough decision. Does he stick with 
coach Steve Spurrier's team, or does he give up a season -- maybe 
more -- to try for a spot in the Olympics? 
</P>
<P>
	``I've prayed that God will show me the right direction to go,''  
said Capel, who came to UF on a football scholarship. ``The only 
thing I can do is wait. Maybe that's not in my future to run in the 
Olympics. But if I have a chance to run in the Olympics, I'm pretty 
sure coach Spurrier won't mind it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This may not have been an issue had the freshman from  
Brooksville, Fla., not surprised everyone, including himself, and 
won the 200-meter title at the Southeastern Conference 
Championships last month in 19.99 seconds. That was the best time 
recorded by an American this year, and the second-best in the 
world, behind only Frank Fredericks of Namibia. 
</P>
<P>
	That makes Capel one of the runners to watch at the NCAA  
Championships in Boise, Idaho, where preliminaries in the 200-meter 
race begin Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Every bit as intriguing will be the choice he'll face about a  
six months from now. 
</P>
<P>
	``The decisions for him will probably start to come after the  
bowl game this fall,'' said Florida track coach Doug Brown. 
``Helping the Gator football team to a national title has to be a 
priority for John. Then he can come and help the Gator track team. 
The challenge for him is: where to go from there. That's something 
we'll have to assess and talk about after the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spurrier affectionately calls Capel ``John, John.'' and rarely  
mentions the receiver without saying how much more he would 
contribute if his hands were better and his pass routes a bit more 
crisp. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the flaws, Capel had an impact on special teams last  
season, returning 10 kickoffs for an average of 27.4 yards and 
eight punts for nearly 10 yards a return. Lining up at receiver, 
however, Capel was a bigger threat running than catching. He ran 11 
times for 80 yards last season, while catching just two balls for 4 
yards. 
</P>
<P>
	He looks like a sure backup next season. But when juniors Travis  
Taylor and Darrell Jackson leave, the position could be his to 
lose. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, Spurrier always replenishes his talent. This spring,  
he started bragging about redshirt freshman Reche Caldwell, a 
football-only athlete, who coaches claim ran a 4.31-second 40-yard 
dash, in the same range as Capel. 
</P>
<P>
	That's the kind of feedback that keeps Capel working on the  
football field, even in the middle of track season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went to about four practices the first couple of weeks'' of  
spring practice, he said. ``But then I would go out on the football 
field by myself. I wasn't trying to make it a big deal by going 
from one practice to the other, so I would go out on the field 
every once in a while and would run routes and have footballs shot 
at me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Capel is not alone. Dozens of players around the country run  
track to stay in shape for football. Very few, however, will have 
to choose one over the other with as much riding on it as Capel. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, I love both sports,'' he said. ``I love football a  
lot more than I like track, but I don't seem them conflicting and I 
don't see it coming to that point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least not for a few more months.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
