<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Finance Minister Is Optimistic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thai Finance Minister Tarrin  
Nimmanahaeminda expressed guarded optimism over his country's 
economic prospects Tuesday, suggesting the country could still meet 
export targets about which the central bank last week expressed 
doubts. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Thailand last week hiked its economic growth  
forecast from 1 percent to 1.5 percent, while lowering its export 
growth target to 2.1 percent from 4 percent. The central bank said 
local demand could fuel economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	Tarrin, speaking to a dinner meeting of foreign correspondents,  
said exports in the first four months were down around 1 percent in 
dollar terms compared with the same period last year. However, he 
added, it was still possible to meet the 4 percent target. 
</P>
<P>
	Thailand's automotive sector had good export potential, he said,  
adding that vehicle exports should pick up from June following the 
arrival of new models on the market. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the government will stick to its 1999 target of 1  
percent gross domestic product growth, as stated in Thailand's 
latest commitment to the International Monetary Fund, which is 
overseeing a $17.2 billion bailout of the ailing economy. 
</P>
<P>
	But Tarrin added that economic growth could top that level given  
a recent economic stimulus package, including cuts to the 
value-added tax and increased public spending, and the possibility 
of exports still hitting the 4 percent growth target this year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
