<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Top Thoroughbred Sire Dies at 29 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Mr. Prospector, who went from an  
undistinguished racing career to prominence as the nation's top 
thoroughbred stallion, died Tuesday. He was 29. 
</P>
<P>
	Mr. Prospector came down with the colic early Tuesday morning  
and was diagnosed with an inflammation of the membrane lining the 
abdomen. Acting on the advice of veterinarians, Claiborne Farm 
owner Seth Hancock had him euthanized at 1:25 p.m., assistant farm 
manager Gus Koch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Koch said Mr. Prospector will be buried in the Claiborne  
cemetery, between Nijinsky and Secretariat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone said earlier that he always did keep good company,''  
Koch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Few would have predicted such a fate for Mr. Prospector when he  
went to stud in 1975, having earned a modest $112,171 in 14 starts 
in 1973 and 1974. Only two of Mr. Prospector's seven wins came in 
stakes races, and the son of Raise A Native and grandson of Native 
Dancer and Nashua was known primarily for his speed. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was the knock on him when he first went to stud, that he  
was going to be all speed,'' Koch said. 
</P>
<P>
	That myth was smashed in 1982, when the Mr. Prospector colt  
Conquistador Cielo won the Metropolitan Mile and, just five days 
later, the 1 1/2-mile Belmont Stakes, and went on to win Horse of the 
Year honors. 
</P>
<P>
	Other champion offspring, including 1985 Preakness winner Tank's  
Prospect, 1988 Breeder's Cup Classic winner Seeking the Gold and 
the champion sprinter Gulch, made Mr. Prospector the continent's 
top stallion. 
</P>
<P>
	According to figures compiled by the industry magazine ``The  
Blood-Horse,'' Mr. Prospector had sired a total of 1,014 foals and 
162 stakes winners through the end of last year. Both figures were 
tops among North American stallions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just feel like this is possibly the greatest horse we have  
been around and the most influential sire that the breed has seen 
in our lifetime,'' Koch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mr. Prospector's legacy will live on. Three colts and two  
fillies from his 1997 crop have been selected for sale at 
Keeneland's top yearling sale this July, with his 1998 and 1999 
crops still on their way to the sales ring and, ultimately, the 
racetrack. 
</P>
<P>
	Koch said Mr. Prospector had completed his 1999 breeding  
schedule at the time of his death, covering 47 mares. As of early 
last month, some 31 of those mares were in foal. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Mr. Prospector's line will be represented by his  
descendants now standing at stud. At Claiborne alone, Koch said, 
Seeking the Gold and Mr. Prospector grandsons Unbridled and 
Coronado's Quest will ensure that his line lives on. 
</P>
<P>
	Koch had been with Mr. Prospector since 1980, when Hancock  
resyndicated him and moved him to Claiborne, in Paris, from 
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was all class, he really was,'' Koch said. ``This horse was  
a gentleman. He never had a problem. He was very easy to work with, 
very easy to be around.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
