<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 23:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Merrill Lynch To Offer Online Trades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. has announced that it will  
offer discount trading over the Internet, marking a dramatic change 
for the nation's biggest stock brokerage. 
</P>
<P>
	Customers will be able to trade stocks online for $29.95 a  
transaction beginning in December. 
</P>
<P>
	The company debated for months whether online trading would  
undermine its traditional brokerage services. Merrill Lynch has 
spent decades building a nationwide network of 14,000 brokers, some 
of whom stand to lose up to 18 percent of their pay as customers 
bypass their services and trade via the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The firm was finally swayed by the rapid loss of business to a  
growing number of online brokers such as Charles Schwab, ETrade and 
Ameritrade. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is probably the most important decision we have made as  
an organization since the mid-1970s,'' said David Komansky, 
Merrill's chairman and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch's Internet strategy, which competitors are likely  
to follow, reflects the revolutionary impact of the Internet on 
financial services. More than 7 million Americans are trading 
online, and more than one-third of individual trades are made 
online. 
</P>
<P>
	``It appeared foolish for us to ignore that part of the  
market,'' Komansky said Tuesday. ``So we decided to attack it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill, however, is charging more than many rivals, some of  
whom offer trades for as little as $5, and will require at least 
$20,000 to open an account. Some online brokers allow people to 
open accounts for just a few thousand dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Merrill's clear targets: Charles Schwab, which caters to  
a similar upper-middle-class clientele and also charges $29.95 for 
online trades. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not concerned,'' said Charles Schwab, chairman and chief  
executive of the San Francisco-based brokerage. ``What they're 
introducing is the affirmation of what we've been talking about a 
long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street's traditional brokerage firms will have to match  
Merrill. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody else sure as heck better follow suit or they're  
going to run the risk of not keeping up with their customers,'' 
said Scott Birnbaum, head of financial services for Mercer 
Management Consulting Inc. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
